<HEAD>Twelve Arrested In Alleged Coup Plot</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS throughout to UPDATE with expanded government account
of plot, background. No pickup</NOTE>
<DATELINE>MONROVIA, Liberia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Police arrested 12 men, including an opposition party leader, in foiling a plot to overthrow the government and assassinate President <PERSON> Samuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Doe </PERSON>, Information Minister <PERSON> Emmanuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Bowier </PERSON> said Tuesday. <PERSON> Bowier </PERSON> told a news conference seven plotters were still at large, including an army captain and two sergeants. He said those arrested included <PERSON> Gabriel </PERSON> <PERSON> Kpolleh </PERSON>, leader of the banned <ORGANIZATION> Liberia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Unification </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, party lawyer <PERSON> Cephar </PERSON> <PERSON> Mbandi </PERSON> and four soldiers,. The minister said the plot was uncovered on March 16. He said it was a conspiracy `` to destabilize the government, create internal strife and overthrow the government by assassinating the president of <LOCATION> Liberia </LOCATION>.'' <PERSON> Bowier </PERSON> said arms, ammunition and military uniforms were found in a building in the <LOCATION> Sinkor </LOCATION> district of <LOCATION> Monrovia </LOCATION>. Investigations continued but the situation was under control, he said. Bowier read from a prepared statement and declined to answer questions. Journalists were warned not to run editorial comments or cartoons on the plot before the defendants go on trial. The minister gave no court date. The Unification party on Monday released a statement expressing concern over the arrests of <LOCATION> Kpolleh </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Mbandi </LOCATION>. It said several properties owned by <PERSON> Kpolleh </PERSON> and his family were destroyed during investigations by security forces and that his wife narrowly escaped being raped. It did not elaborate. <PERSON> Bowier </PERSON> advised reporters not to believe any press releases issued by the <ORGANIZATION> Unification </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> party </ORGANIZATION>, saying it was banned and its statements had no credibility. <PERSON> Doe </PERSON>, who came to power in a bloody April 1980 coup, has been the target of several assassination attempts. An attempted coup on Nov. 12, 1985, resulted in more than 600 deaths and the destruction of the village of the ringleader, former Brig. <PERSON> Gen </PERSON> <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Quiwonkpa </PERSON>, who was killed in the attempt. <PERSON> Quiwonkpa </PERSON>, who had been living in exile, led the attempt following elections that opposition leaders and independent observers said were rigged. <LOCATION> Liberia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>'s oldest republic, was founded in 1847 by freed <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> slaves. Descendents of the slaves, who were a minority, controlled the government until <PERSON> Doe </PERSON>, from the <ORGANIZATION> Krahn </ORGANIZATION> ethnic group, stormed the presidential mansion in April 1980, killing then-President <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Tolbert </PERSON>. The economy declined under the rule of the former army master sergeant. Major Western creditors suspended aid to <LOCATION> Liberia </LOCATION> pending payment of debts. Last year the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> sent 17 financial experts to <LOCATION> Monrovia </LOCATION> to oversee operations of the <ORGANIZATION> Finance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION>.
</TEXT>
