<HEAD>At Geneva Talks on Afghanistan, Attention `Centers On Washington'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> mediator <PERSON> Diego </PERSON> <PERSON> Cordovez </PERSON> spoke Tuesday of the slow pace of <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> peace talks in <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION>, but cautioned that lack of quick movement does not mean a stalemate. Negotiators at the U.N.-sponsored talks apparently were waiting for new signals from the <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> meeting between <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> Foreign Minister <PERSON> Eduard </PERSON> <PERSON> Shevardnadze </PERSON> and Secretary of State <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON>. <PERSON> Cordovez </PERSON> met with the Afghan delegation for less than 30 minutes Tuesday and with the Pakistani team, which speaks for the Afghan guerrillas, for more than an hour. He later spoke briefly to reporters, admitting that there was `` very slow progress'' but that it `` should not be confused with a deadlock.'' There was a short-lived rumor that the Afghans, led by Foreign Minister <PERSON> Abdul </PERSON> <PERSON> Wakil </PERSON>, were preparing to leave <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION> Wednesday. But a Pakistani negotiator, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said the talks would proceed on schedule. <PERSON> Wakil </PERSON> said earlier there was no reason for suspending the talks. <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION>'s chief representative, acting Foreign Minister <PERSON> Zain </PERSON> <PERSON> Noorani </PERSON>, has said <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> was prepared to stay in <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION> `` as long as it takes'' to conclude a peace settlement. The talks are stalling over the question of what <LOCATION> Afghan </LOCATION> government should oversee implementation of the settlement and over future Soviet military aid to <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION>. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> demands that <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> assistance cease at the same time as <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> aid to the anti-Marxist guerrillas fighting the Soviet-backed <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION> government. <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> has rejected this as interference in relations between two sovereign states. `` Attention now centers on the discussions in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>,'' a Pakistani source said. <PERSON> Noorani </PERSON> said last week that the superpowers may `` at least find it easier to settle among themselves'' the aid issue. The <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> intervened militarily in <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> at the end of 1979 to support the government in its fight against the Islamic guerrillas. Approximately 115,000 Soviet troops are still there. Soviet leader <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> says he wants to withdraw the Soviet troops from <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> this year if agreement can be reached at <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION>.
</TEXT>
