<HEAD>Dissident Editor Jailed on Charges of Defaming Military</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SANTIAGO, Chile (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A military prosecutor on Tuesday jailed <PERSON> Francisco </PERSON> <PERSON> Herreros </PERSON>, director of the leftist magazine <ORGANIZATION> Cauce </ORGANIZATION>, for purportedly defaming <LOCATION> Chile </LOCATION>'s armed forces in an editorial, a magazine spokesman reported. <PERSON> Herreros </PERSON> was taken to <LOCATION> Santiago </LOCATION>'s main prison after being questioned by prosecutor <PERSON> Luis </PERSON> <PERSON> Acevedo </PERSON>, according to <PERSON> Alvaro </PERSON> <PERSON> Briones </PERSON>, a senior <ORGANIZATION> Cauce </ORGANIZATION> editor. Under <LOCATION> Chile </LOCATION>'s military government, the armed forces codes empower prosecutors to indict and jail civilians brought before military courts. The editorial written by <PERSON> Herreros </PERSON> and published by Cauce in June 1987 criticized the influence given to the military courts in recent years. According to lawyers and human rights activists, more than 90 percent of those tried by military courts in the last five years were civilians, including a number of journalists. <PERSON> Acevedo </PERSON> has five days to file formal charges against <PERSON> Herreros </PERSON> or release him, according to the military code. The suit against <PERSON> Herreros </PERSON> was started by the army. <LOCATION> Chile </LOCATION> has been ruled by the armed forces since a coup ousted the elected government of Marxist President <PERSON> Salvador </PERSON> <PERSON> Allende </PERSON> in September 1973.
