<HEAD>Pershing 2 Missile Launches Successful</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The Army successfully test-fired five <ORGANIZATION> Pershing </ORGANIZATION> 2 missiles slated to be banned from deployment under a treaty with the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>. The treaty, signed Dec. 8 by President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> and Soviet leader <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>, does not require either side to withdraw or destroy missiles until it has been ratified by both governments. The <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> is expected to approve the pact in late spring. The unarmed missiles were successfully fired Monday under battlefield conditions, the <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> said. The Pershing is a field missile _ each of which costs $ 4 million _ launched from its own assembly that can be carried by a truck. The Intermediate-range Nuclear Forces, or INF, treaty, calls for the destruction of all missiles with a range of 300 to 3,400 miles.
