<FIRST>r a PM-AgStationCentennial     03-22 0390</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Ag Station Centennial,0399</SECOND>
<HEAD>Agricultural Experiment Station Marks 100th Anniversary</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT LEE ZIMMER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>URBANA, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Ben </PERSON> <PERSON> Midgette </PERSON> bends and removes spikes from railroad ties, and <PERSON> Rod </PERSON> <PERSON> Korthals </PERSON> blows smoke through a scale-model hog house. They are among 3,000 scientists, administrators and graduate assistants on staff at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Illinois </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agricultural </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Experiment </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Station </ORGANIZATION>, which celebrated its 100th anniversary Monday. But the center, one of 66 in the country, is about more than agriculture. `` I've yet to see one person ... who did n't think there were exciting things going on here,'' said station director <PERSON> Donald </PERSON> <PERSON> Holt </PERSON>. `` One thing is clear _ research is crucial to the future of <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> agriculture and our society in general.'' In one laboratory, <PERSON> Midgette </PERSON> compared the strength of railroad ties made from different woods, looking for the longest-lasting material. An African oak was so hard that it caused a bolt to break in a machine that measures the force required to pull out a spike. `` It snapped and went straight up,'' said <PERSON> Midgette </PERSON>, who figures this African oak will out-last conventional ties. `` We've got indentations in the ceiling.'' Korthals pumped smoke into the clear plastic model of a hog house to demonstrate how the air moves through the building with various ventilation systems. He said it should help farmers select the most efficient design for their own swine buildings. The 320 research projects funded by the station last year involved subjects such as agricultural economics, veterinary medicine, home economics and food science. The center has a $ 25 million budget from state and federal appropriations, as well as gifts, grants and contracts, many from the private sector, <PERSON> Holt </PERSON> said. It began in the Morrow Plots, site of the longest-running continuous corn experiment in the <LOCATION> Western </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hemisphere </LOCATION>. The test plots were created in 1876, the year Gen. <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Custer </PERSON> and 264 cavalrymen were killed at <LOCATION> Little </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bighorn </LOCATION>. Much of the station's research still is aimed directly at production agriculture. Visitors on Monday saw a rainfall simulator used to study the effects of soil erosion, experiments on the biological control of insects, and research into the possible use of wild soybeans to improve commercial varieties. They also saw work being done to create new human foods from soybeans, to study tree growth and to learn more about infant nutrition and child development.
</TEXT>
