<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> has urged <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>'s military leader, Gen. <PERSON> Manuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Antonio </PERSON> <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON>, to leave the country and live in <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION>. The <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> has encouraged other world leaders to give up power and go into exile. Among them: <PERSON> Syngman </PERSON> <PERSON> Rhee </PERSON> _ The <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korean </LOCATION> president went into exile in <LOCATION> Hawaii </LOCATION> in May, 1960 following widespread political unrest and allegations that he had rigged the presidential election. He died in 1965. <PERSON> Shah </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> _ <PERSON> Shah </PERSON> <PERSON> Mohammad </PERSON> <PERSON> Reza </PERSON> <PERSON> Pahlavi </PERSON> gave up power during the Islamic revolution and flew to <LOCATION> Egypt </LOCATION> in his private plane on Jan. 15, 1979. He was allowed temporary refuge in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> for medical treatment, but was not allowed to live in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> permanently. He went to <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> and then to <LOCATION> Egypt </LOCATION>, where he died in 1980. <PERSON> Anastasio </PERSON> <PERSON> Somoza </PERSON> _ The Nicaraguan president fled the country Jan. 19, 1979 under pressure from the <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> States </ORGANIZATION> and after the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> refused to support him. A Sandinista-led coalition took power. <PERSON> Somoza </PERSON> lived in <LOCATION> Paraguay </LOCATION> and was assassinated on Sept. 7, 1980. `` Baby Doc'' <PERSON> Duvalier </PERSON> _ <PERSON> Jean-Claude </PERSON> <PERSON> Duvalier </PERSON> a