<HEAD>`60 Minutes' Producer Marks 40 Years at CBS</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHRYN BAKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Don </PERSON> <PERSON> Hewitt </PERSON>, who marks his 40th anniversary with <ORGANIZATION> CBS </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> today, recalls that he landed his first job at the network after a friend suggested his experience at a newsphoto service might come in handy. `` I said, what does <ORGANIZATION> CBS </ORGANIZATION> want with picture experience? Radio does n't need any pictures. He said, ` No _ television.' I said whata-vision?'' Today, the 65-year-old outspoken creator and executive producer of `` 60 Minutes'' is looking beyond current television technology, foreseeing a time when networks are superfluous and television news is beamed directly into subscribers' homes. <PERSON> Hewitt </PERSON> began his career as associate director and later producer of the network's first television newscast, `` <PERSON> Douglas </PERSON> <PERSON> Edwards </PERSON> With the News'' and later the `` CBS Evening News'' with <PERSON> Walter </PERSON> <PERSON> Cronkite </PERSON>. He remembers covering the coronation of Queen <PERSON> Elizabeth </PERSON> <PERSON> II </PERSON> with <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Murrow </PERSON> and flying back to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> aboard a chartered airliner editing the kinescope that viewers would see on the news _ no videotapes, no satellite transmissions. `` I did n't think there was ever going to be satellites, bounce signals off a star, are you crazy?,'' he said, laughing. But <PERSON> Hewitt </PERSON>, who considered buying <ORGANIZATION> CBS </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> a few years ago, thinks it's feasible to one day broadcast news directly to homes News services already are beaming footage to local television stations, so <PERSON> Hewitt </PERSON>'s idea is not so far-fetched. `` I think that the network news departments, they might not even work for a network 10 years from now,'' he said. `` There might not be any networks because it may be an outmoded delivery system. `` I'm not sure you do n't have a large newsroom somewhere and you just have direct broadcast ... feeding news into people's homes, for a price same way they pay for a newspaper.'' He also foresees delivering newspapers into home printers by satellite. `` I think about it more than most people, as you can see. And I wonder how long the networks in their present form will be around,'' he said. Some other samples of <PERSON> Hewitt </PERSON>'s opinions: _ `` 60 Minutes'': `` I've always said all we do in this broadcast is shine lights on people in dark corners, and if people in dark corners are doing things they should n't be doing, all we did was turn the light on.'' _ The importance of pictures on television: `` The accepted wisdom in television was always you put words to pictures I do n't believe that. You put pictures to words. You start with the words. The audio is always more important to me than the video.'' _ Televised presidential debates -LRB- <PERSON> Hewitt </PERSON> produced the famous 1960 meeting of <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Nixon </PERSON> and <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON> -RRB-: `` It's still a terrible format and we should n't be doing them They should have real debates. ... The <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> candidate and <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> candidate should head up a team of two or three debaters who are really good and can really cross-examine the other side and give them a hard time, and they ought to do it in front of a joint session of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, and it will produce something other than this sterile show where what it is is a joint press conference, not really a debate.'' _ This year's election: `` I do n't think there's enough caffeine in <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> to keep the electorate awake during a Dukakis-Bush campaign. _ Politicians: `` I do n't put politicians on the air if I can help it, because I instinctively do n't believe them I believe they're only interested in getting themselves elected, and they only say what they think will get themselves elected. _ Ratings: `` No matter what I think about ratings, and whether they're accurate and everything, I do n't say anything because they've been awfully good to me. _ The future: `` I know where I'll be in nine years I'm going to be here. My contract is n't up until I'm 74. Ironclad, nobody gets out. Now the question is, will there be a CBS? I think so. Some form. Maybe not this form.''
