<HEAD>Banning Reporters Won't Necessarily Ease Israeli Image Problem</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOAN MOWER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Banning reporters and photographers from the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Gaza </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Strip </LOCATION> could prove to be a public relations blunder for <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> and might not be effective anyway, several media observers say. <PERSON> Larry </PERSON> <PERSON> Gross </PERSON>, a professor at <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Annenberg </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communications </ORGANIZATION> at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pennsylvania </ORGANIZATION>, said it would be `` bad policy'' for <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> to impose more restrictions on reporters covering unrest in the occupied territories. `` It would be a public relations risk _ one I hope they do n't take,'' <PERSON> Gross </PERSON> said He said <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> could jeopardize its reputation as the only true democracy in the <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION>, which <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials cite in providing millions of dollars to the country each year. But the Israelis are obviously watching the situation in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> to determine if the advantages of restricting the press outweigh the disadvantages, he said. <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>'s widely condemned white government has succeeded in dampening outside interest in that country's racial problems by banning coverage of any security activities, experts agree. The order went into effect in June 1986. But Gross doubted <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> would be able to `` keep the lid on'' coverage of the occupied territories in a way the <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africans </LOCATION> have virtually halted reporting in black areas. <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>'s domestic political opposition and a thriving domestic press could prevent a blackout on coverage of the territories, he said. Local Israeli army commanders already have authority to close areas in the occupied territories at random, and they have been doing so with increasing frequency. A parliamentary committee in <LOCATION> Jerusalem </LOCATION> is studying whether to ban the media formally from the territories. <PERSON> Yael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dayan </PERSON>, a well-known <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> peace activist, said during a recent <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> visit that tough restrictions on the press would likely fail, because Israelis demand news and have an aggressive press corps. <PERSON> Eric </PERSON> <PERSON> Goldstein </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> to Protect Journalists, a <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York-based </LOCATION> group that monitors conditions for journalists worldwide, said <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> might be able to stave off intense scrutiny by banning cameras. `` But in the long run the greater public interest is served by allowing the press access,'' he said. The committee opposes restrictions on reporters. Some Americans have joined Israeli government officials in complaining that reporters, particularly those working for foreign television networks, have helped incite rock-throwing Palestinians in the territories. <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> Mayor <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> Koch </PERSON> has said a television ban would be justified, and former Secretary of State <PERSON> Henry </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Kissinger </PERSON> reportedly told prominent American Jews during a meeting that banning television cameras would be a good idea. <PERSON> Kissinger </PERSON> says his remarks were distorted. <PERSON> Jeff </PERSON> <PERSON> Cohen </PERSON> of Fairness and Accuracy in Reporting criticized a `` censorship lobby'' for supporting restrictions that, in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, would be considered an unacceptable violation of freedom of the press. `` It would be one more comparison with <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>, and it would hurt <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>,'' he said. FAIR is a liberal <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> group that examines the media. <PERSON> Fred </PERSON> <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Friendly </PERSON>, former president of <ORGANIZATION> CBS </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> and a professor at <ORGANIZATION> Columbia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Journalism </ORGANIZATION>, said it would be wrong to ban reporters from the occupied territories. `` That ca n't be right _ that's what <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> did,'' he said. But Friendly said television coverage, with its time constraints and powerful pictures, can fail to portray a story accurately. ` What is also wrong is letting the picture run away with the story,'' he told <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Mortimer </PERSON> <PERSON> Zuckerman </PERSON>, editor-in-chief of <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; World Report, had the same complaint. `` Television has polluted the public debate because it is inherently difficult for pictures to give context, history and meaning to events,'' he recently wrote.
