<TEXT>
 Republican presidential candidate <PERSON> Pat </PERSON> <PERSON> Robertson </PERSON>, faced with bumping up against the federally-imposed campaign spending limit, revised some of his state spending figures downward in his newly filed campaign financial statement. The spending allocations for nine states showed lower cumulative expenditures in the report filed Monday than the figures <PERSON> Robertson </PERSON> reported a month earlier. <PERSON> Robertson </PERSON>'s staff did not return a phone call Monday to answer questions about the revisions. In his report filed Monday with the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Election </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION>, the former TV evangelist reported he had spent $ 19 million through Feb. 29 against the spending cap of $ 23 million that applies to expenditures for the entire primary season. Even with the downward revisions in some state spending figures, the total was still more than the $ 17.6 million in spending against the cap that he reported through the end of January. Candidates who receive federal matching funds must agree to stay within the spending limit. The reports candidates filed Monday show new financial activity for the month of February as well as cumulative totals. <PERSON> Robertson </PERSON>'s revisions were in figures reported for <LOCATION> Califonria </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> District </LOCATION> <LOCATION> of </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Columbia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Oklahoma </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Tennessee </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>, and <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION>. The biggest was in <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> where his previous report showed an allocation of $ 1.1 million, but the new report shows an allocation of $ 746,514 through February. <PERSON> Robertson </PERSON>, who has spent more overall than any ot