<FIRST>r w PM-TMIWater     03-22 0494</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-TMI Water,490</SECOND>
<HEAD>Utility Moving To Boil Away Contaminated Water</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFF BARKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The operator of the <LOCATION> Three </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mile </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION> nuclear plant has taken the first step in a plan to dispose of 2.3 million gallons of contaminated water that is a legacy of the 1979 accident at the plant. GPU Nuclear, operator of the plant near <LOCATION> Harrisburg </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Pa. </LOCATION>, said Monday it is spending $ 800,000 for a system to boil away the water, even though that method has yet to be approved by the <ORGANIZATION> Nuclear </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Regulatory </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> and public hearings are months away. `` We expect the <ORGANIZATION> NRC </ORGANIZATION> to approve the evaporation eventually, but it's possible that that would n't happen,'' <ORGANIZATION> GPU </ORGANIZATION> Nuclear spokesman <PERSON> Gordon </PERSON> <PERSON> Tomb </PERSON> said Monday in a telephone interview. Tomb identified the contractor as <ORGANIZATION> Pacific </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nuclear </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Systems </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> of Federal Way, <LOCATION> Wash. </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> NRC </ORGANIZATION> spokeswoman <PERSON> Sue </PERSON> <PERSON> Gagner </PERSON> said utilities commonly make major expenditures for equipment before the commission grants permission for its use <ORGANIZATION> GPU </ORGANIZATION> Nuclear said the <ORGANIZATION> NRC </ORGANIZATION> might not consider the plan until December and the utility wants to be ready when approval comes. But <PERSON> Kay </PERSON> <PERSON> Pickering </PERSON>, spokeswoman for <ORGANIZATION> Three </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Island </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Alert </ORGANIZATION>, a citizens' group, said she was alarmed when <ORGANIZATION> GPU </ORGANIZATION> Nuclear told the <ORGANIZATION> NRC </ORGANIZATION> at a meeting last week that the company had authorized the contractor to design, install and begin testing the evaporation system. `` This is very distressing to the individuals and organizations involved here,'' she said. Most of the water is left over from the 1979 accident, while some has been used to decontaminate the plant. GPU Nuclear said the average additional radiation exposure from the evaporation would be about the same as `` the exposure from one to two hours of natural background radiation in the <LOCATION> Harrisburg </LOCATION> area.'' The $ 7 million process involves boiling the water into steam released from a 100-foot-high stack, and packaging impurities for shipment to a low-level radioactive waste dump. Tomb said testing at the plant would not use radioactive water. <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Gerusky </PERSON>, a member of a citizens' advisory panel on the <ORGANIZATION> TMI </ORGANIZATION> cleanup and director of <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Bureau </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Radiation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Protection </ORGANIZATION>, said some area residents `` were concerned about any releases from <ORGANIZATION> TMI </ORGANIZATION>'' and favored leaving the water in storage tanks. He said the <ORGANIZATION> NRC </ORGANIZATION> has given its blessing to the evaporation plan, but the commissioners have withheld formal approval pending public hearings. Disposal of the water is part of the $ 1 billion cleanup of Three Mile Island 2. During the accident, uranium fuel was allowed to lose the vital coolant that covers it, causing material in the core to begin melting. <ORGANIZATION> GPU </ORGANIZATION> Nuclear announced plans in December 1986 to place Unit 2 in storage indefinitely. The <ORGANIZATION> NRC </ORGANIZATION> is expected to issue a report next month on whether the `` monitored storage'' plan poses any threat to the environment, <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Masnik </PERSON> of the commission said Monday. While there are no plans to restart TMI-2, its twin reactor was not harmed in the accident and resumed operating in October 1985.
