<HEAD>Robertson Forces Will Dominate At Nevada State GOP Convention</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRENDAN RILEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CARSON CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Supporters of former television evangelist <PERSON> Pat </PERSON> <PERSON> Robertson </PERSON> will apparently control the state <ORGANIZATION> GOP </ORGANIZATION> convention in <PERSON> Reno </PERSON> next month as a result of weekend county conventions, party officials said. <LOCATION> Nevada </LOCATION> Republicans use a three-step system of caucuses and conventions to pick their national convention delegates. The process began with precinct caucuses last month, at which a straw poll was conducted. In the straw poll, Vice President <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> led with 27 percent, followed by <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Dole </PERSON> with 22 percent and <PERSON> Robertson </PERSON> with 15 percent. But <PERSON> Robertson </PERSON> supporters claimed victory by saying most of the 23 percent undecided voters in the poll actually were <PERSON> Robertson </PERSON> supporters. The straw poll participants were not bound to presidential candidates, however. At the county conventions, held over this past weekend, delegates were elected to the state convention April 21-23, where in turn national convention delegates will be elected. The delegate breakdown for the state convention wo n't be known for several days. But the <PERSON> Robertson </PERSON> forces dominated Republican conventions in <LOCATION> Nevada </LOCATION>'s two biggest counties, <PERSON> Clark </PERSON> and <LOCATION> Washoe </LOCATION>. Party leaders said it appeared <PERSON> Robertson </PERSON> got more than half the 800 state delegates in those two counties alone. <PERSON> Robertson </PERSON> also picked up some delegates at the <ORGANIZATION> GOP </ORGANIZATION>'s county conventions elsewhere in <LOCATION> Nevada </LOCATION>, although his supporters showed less strength in the outlying areas, party officials said. State GOP Chairwoman <PERSON> Sally </PERSON> <PERSON> Vitkus-McKinney </PERSON> said Monday that party newcomers _ which most <PERSON> Robertson </PERSON> backers are _ are welcome. But she added there is frustration because <LOCATION> Nevada </LOCATION> probably will wind up with its 20-member delegation to the national convention committed to somone who wo n't be the presidential nominee. <PERSON> Robertson </PERSON>'s state director, <PERSON> Steve </PERSON> <PERSON> Wark </PERSON>, said there's no way he would encourage the <PERSON> Robertson </PERSON> delegates to switch to <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> at the state convention level, even though their candidate is clearly far behind. `` <PERSON> Robertson </PERSON> supporters are not about to roll over. They're making a statement and sticking to their commitment,'' he said However, he said <PERSON> Robertson </PERSON> supporters would be prepared to support <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> at the national Republican convention. <PERSON> Robertson </PERSON>, after big losses on Super Tuesday, indicated he intends to remain in the race, but has virtually given up hope of getting the nomination. He has talked more at recent appearances about his role at the convention, his long-term influence on the party and a possible bid in 1992.
