<SECOND>PM-Farm Scene,860</SECOND>
<HEAD>Smaller Crop, Higher Demand Mean That Ain't Hay</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Hay prices nationally have been averaging around 12 percent higher than a year ago, reflecting a smaller 1987 crop and some increase in demand. The Agriculture Department in January revised 1987 hay output downward to 149.1 million tons from last October's preliminary forecast of 153.7 million tons. A new report by the department's <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> says that the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> hay area turned out to be about 500,000 acres larger than estimated in October but that the yield was reduced by 4 percent to 2.46 tons per acre. The 1987 hay crop was 6.4 million tons smaller than the record of 155.5 million tons produced in 1986. `` Alfalfa and alfalfa mixture hay production turned out to be 84.6 million tons, down 7 million tons from 1986, and all other hay production of 64.6 million tons was 600,000 tons above the previous year's 64 million,'' the report said. Acording to <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION> production figures for 1987, <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> was the leading all-hay state with more than 9 million tons, followed by: <LOCATION> Wisconsin </LOCATION>, 8.88 million; <LOCATION> Minnesota </LOCATION>, 7.8 million; <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Dakota </LOCATION>, 7.09 million; and <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION>, 6.93 million. Last May 1 at the start of the 1987-88 hay crop season, the inventory on hand was estimated at 32.4 million tons, the most since 1980. Adding the 1987 crop, that made a total hay supply of 181.5 million tons for the marketing year that runs through April 30, slightly less than the 1986-87 suppply of 182.2 million tons. The hay stockpile on Dec. 1 was reported at 119.7 million tons, meaning that 61.8 million tons had been consumed during the seven months since May 1. In the same period a year earlier, hay consumption was 60.5 million tons, the report said. Hay prices paid by farmers and ranchers averaged $ 64.60 per ton during the May-November period, up $ 4.74 per ton from a year earlier. In December and January of this year, prices averaged $ 63.75 per ton, up $ 7.65 from a year earlier. According to <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION> estimates, the value of hay production in 1987, based on market prices, was more than $ 9.1 billion, ranking the crop third among all <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> farm commodities. Only corn at $ 12.2 billion and soybeans, $ 10.4 billion, were valued higher. Those value estimates, incidentally, are not sales receipts or marketings. The <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION> estimates are based upon total farm values, whether a commodity is sold or used by the producer.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> has sold <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> 30,000 metric tons of surplus non-fat dry milk for $ 1,260 per ton, about a third less than it cost <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> taxpayers. Acting Undersecretary <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Goldberg </PERSON> said Monday the surplus powdered milk was sold by the department's <ORGANIZATION> Commodity </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Credit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> to <ORGANIZATION> CONASUPO </ORGANIZATION>, the <LOCATION> Mexican </LOCATION> government's food purchasing authority. <PERSON> Goldberg </PERSON> said the sale `` reflects the world market price for non-fat dry milk at the time the sale was negotiated'' with <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>. Deliveries are scheduled through March 1989. In addition, the CCC provided <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> with a three-year credit arrangement at commercial rates of interest, he said. According to a recent CCC report, about 454 million pounds of non-fat dry milk were held in storage, with a value of more than $ 385 million, or about 85 cents per pound. There are approximately 2,205 pounds in a metric ton, which translates to a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> value of $ 1,874 per ton. The surplus was acquired by CCC through purchases of cheese, butter and non-fat dry milk to support the price of milk paid to dairy farmers. <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> in 1985 farm law mandated the export sale of 150,000 tons of dairy products annually for the three fiscal years ending Sept. 30, 1988. The latest deal with <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> boosted sales this year to 77,520 tons, <PERSON> Goldberg </PERSON> said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Exporters have sold <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> an additional 200,000 metric tons of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> wheat at subsidized prices, the <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said. The sale, equal to 7.34 million bushels, was handled by <ORGANIZATION> Continental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Grain </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> and will be shipped in the 1988-89 wheat marketing year that will begin on June 1. <PERSON> Melvin </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Sims </PERSON>, general sales manager for the department's <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agricultural </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>, said Monday the sales were part of an authorized 1.2 million tons of wheat announced Feb. 5 under the Export Enhancement Program, or EEP Although no selling prices or other details were announced, recent prices of wheat at farm points have averaged around $ 2.67 per bushel, indicating a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> farm value of about $ 20 million. A metric ton is about 2,205 pounds and is equal to 36.7 bushels of wheat. <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> bought more than 4 million tons of wheat under previous EEP arrangements, which allow exporters to sell commodities at reduced prices in order to meet foreign competition and then collect free government surpluses of grain or other commodities as bonuses, or subsidies. <PERSON> Sims </PERSON> said the bonus averaged $ 24.45 per ton, or about 67 cents per bushel of wheat. The bonuses will be paid in the form of surplus commodities owned by the department's <ORGANIZATION> Commodity </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Credit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>. <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> has 260,000 tons remaining for use under the <ORGANIZATION> EEP </ORGANIZATION> initiative announced on Feb. 5, he said
