<FIRST>r w PM-US-Japan-Nuclear     03-22 0468</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-US-Japan-Nuclear,460</SECOND>
<HEAD>Senate Clears Way For Uranium Agreement With Japan</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAWRENCE L. KNUTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> has removed a roadblock to a 30-year nuclear cooperation pact with <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, rejecting claims by opponents that the new agreement could add to the proliferation of nuclear weapons. The <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> voted 53-50 Monday evening to reject a resolution to disapprove the agreement, which provides for the sale of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> uranium and uranium enrichment equipment to <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> over the next 30 years. It replaces a more restrictive cooperation arrangement which was to expire at the end of the century. As the matter stands, the agreement will take effect at the end of April, 90 legislative days after it was submitted to <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>. Under the rules governing consideration of the agreement, it could be rejected only if both the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> passed resolutions of disapproval and the president signed them. The most controversial element of the new agreement is a provision giving <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> advance consent for 30 years to reprocess U.S.-controlled spent nuclear fuel and to use plutonium separated from that fuel without the case-by-case approval required by the present agreement. Plutonium is the key ingredient in the production of nuclear weapons. Since the process involves shipment of the nuclear material to reprocessing plants in <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>, opponents of the agreement contended it will loosen <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> control on the movement of plutonium, open opportunities for terrorists and potentially lead to the proliferation of nuclear weapons. Responding to these and other concerns, the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Relations </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> voted 15-3 at the end of last year to recommend that the agreement be renegotiated. The <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration and supporters of the agreement on the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> floor said that permitting it to take effect would continue <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> influence over the Japanese nuclear program while providing the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> with a major long-term sales market. But Sen. <PERSON> Claiborne </PERSON> <PERSON> Pell </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-R.I. </LOCATION>, chairman of the Foreign Relations panel, echoed many other senators in contending the agreement does not meet the non-proliferation standards of the Atomic Energy Act. Sen. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Glenn </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Ohio </LOCATION>, said the agreement does not meet legal requirements and gives no assurance of effective non-proliferation safeguards. <PERSON> Glenn </PERSON> said the present law works well and that its case-by-case approval arrangements should not be scrapped. But some supporters of the agreement said opponents were motivated less by a genuine concern over nuclear proliferation than by anger at Japanese trading practices. `` There is a certain amount of emotional <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> bashing going on around here,'' said Sen. <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> McClure </PERSON>, R-Idaho. Contending that rejecting the agreement would hurt the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> _ which would lose hundreds of millions of dollars in uranium sales _ and not <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, <PERSON> McClure </PERSON> added: `` Actually it's <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> bashing we're engaged in here. Rejecting this agreement will hurt us and not the Japanese.''
