<DATELINE>WEST SPRINGFIELD, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Mike </PERSON> <PERSON> Nigro </PERSON> said he was changing the oil on his truck when he first heard someone coming down the street singing `` O Sole Mio.'' It was his mailman, <PERSON> Dennis </PERSON> <PERSON> Jordan </PERSON>. `` I thought the truck had fallen on me and the angels were singing to me,'' <PERSON> Nigro </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Jordan </PERSON>, a full-time postal worker and a part-time tenor, has brought music to the ears of his customers along his mail route. The 29-year-old letter carrier warms up his voice while on his route with some easy stuff such as Neapolitan folk songs. He breaks into arias from `` The Barber of <LOCATION> Seville </LOCATION>'' after a good lunch. `` When I'm in the mood, I'll sing my lungs out,'' he said. <PERSON> Jordan </PERSON> has taken formal voice lessons for 12 years and performed with Project Opera in <LOCATION> Northampton </LOCATION> and other local groups. `` I do n't usually sing opera while I'm working,'' he said recently. `` I'm afraid of using the wrong pitch.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>ALFORD, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 It might be described as `` Thoreau Meets the Media Monster.'' <PERSON> Denny </PERSON> <PERSON> Alsop </PERSON> has embarked on a month-long zigzag canoe trek along 10 <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> rivers _ armed with a jug of water and a telephone. <PERSON> Alsop </PERSON>, 41, says he will use the portable phone to keep in touch with the media along the way of his trek from the Berkshires to <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION> to draw attention to <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION>' water resources. `` I think it's wonderful that in the midst of one of the most densely populated states in the nation, by focusing on an idea and an element in the environment, I can go and have a great adventure,'' <PERSON> Alsop </PERSON> told the three dozen environmentalists, schoolchildren and others gathered at the launch site Monday. The 33-day trip, sponsored by the <ORGANIZATION> Massachusetts </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Audubon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Society </ORGANIZATION>, includes a planned stop at <LOCATION> Walden </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Pond </LOCATION> near <LOCATION> Concord </LOCATION>, where the famed 19th century writer <PERSON> Henry </PERSON> <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Thoreau </PERSON> lived in an isolated cabin for more than two years.
