<TEXT>
 The first reactor at the <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> Nuclear Project will be allowed to operate at full power despite last-minute efforts by opponents to halt it because of alleged dangerous flaws. The Nuclear Regulatory Commission voted 5-0 Monday to approve a full-power operating license for the reactor, part of a $ 5.5 billion, twin-reactor, 2,500-megawatt generating station 10 miles from the <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Coast </LOCATION> near <LOCATION> Bay </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>. A group headed by Citizens Concerned About Nuclear Power of <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Antonio </LOCATION> sued in the 5th <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Orleans </LOCATION> on Friday to stop the license and was rebuffed by the judges without comment on Monday. The Government Accountability Project, based in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, had petitioned the <ORGANIZATION> NRC </ORGANIZATION> staff to delay Monday's vote pending a fuller investigation of 700 allegations of intimidation, other wrongdoing or shoddy construction. But that was rejected late Friday. <PERSON> Billie </PERSON> <PERSON> Garde </PERSON>, a lawyer for the GAP, said after Monday's vote, `` To handle it this way was very insulting to several dozen people who have come to the commission. ... They're not anti-nuclear activists.'' The commission acted after a staff briefing on an investigation of some of the concerns brought to the commission's attention by the GAP, which tries to encourage and protect people who disclose wrongdoing. `` It is the staff's judgment that <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> can be operated without undue risk to the health and safety of the public,'' <PERSON> Jose </PERSON> <PERSON> Calvo </PERSON>, director of an <ORGANIZATION> NRC </ORGANIZATION> special team that investigated the allegations, told the commission in repeating the conclusions of the team report issued a week ago on the 213 allegations judged to be safety-related. GAP presented two previously unidentified whistleblowers at a morning news conference criticizing last week's special team report. One of them, engineer <PERSON> Ashok </PERSON> <PERSON> Garg </PERSON>, who left the project in September 1986, said he provided the team a reference to a plant document from April 1986, which said among other things that 20 percent of valves for plant instruments had been installed backwards. <PERSON> Calvo </PERSON>, however, said in an interview after the commission meeting: `` We reviewed that document, and we interviewed him, but he could n't remember details. With those instrument valves, it does n't make any difference if they are installed frontwards or backwards.'' <ORGANIZATION> Houston </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lighting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <ORGANIZATION> Power </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, the project manager, has about a 48 percent share, <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Power </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Light </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Corpus </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Christi </LOCATION> has slightly more than 25 percent, the city of <LOCATION> Austin </LOCATION> has about 16 percent and the city of <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Antonio </LOCATION> has about 10 percent. Austin at one point sued <ORGANIZATION> Houston </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lighting </ORGANIZATION>, charging mismanagement, but those two parties are close to an agreement under which <ORGANIZATION> Houston </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lighting </ORGANIZATION> would take over <LOCATION> Austin </LOCATION>'s ownership. A construction permit was issued in 1975. The total cost to the four owners will be some 500 percent above initial estimates. The second unit is more than 80 percent complete.
