<HEAD>Some Call for Curbs on Media Coverage of IRA Funerals</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Irish, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MAUREEN JOHNSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Horrifying television film of <ORGANIZATION> IRA </ORGANIZATION> funeral mourners beating up two British soldiers who were then killed has brought demands to restrict coverage of such scenes. Some lawmakers urged restrictions on funeral coverage or interviews with leaders of <ORGANIZATION> Sinn </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fein </ORGANIZATION>, the legal political wing of the outlawed <ORGANIZATION> Irish </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION>. They argue that the cameras' presence encourages rioting and boosts `` terrorist organizations. `` We're fighting what is in the nature of a war here,'' said <PERSON> Ivor </PERSON> <PERSON> Stanbrook </PERSON>, senior legislator of the governing <ORGANIZATION> Conservative </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, in urging a ban on interviews with <ORGANIZATION> Sinn </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fein </ORGANIZATION> leaders. `` We would n't have dreamed during the war of giving currency to <ORGANIZATION> Nazis </ORGANIZATION> so I do n't see why we should give any credence ... to people acting as the <ORGANIZATION> IRA </ORGANIZATION>'s propagandists.'' Prime Minister <PERSON> Margaret </PERSON> <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON> has criticized British TV networks for giving the <ORGANIZATION> IRA </ORGANIZATION> what she calls the `` oxygen of publicity.'' But the Home Office said Monday there were no plans to impose bans on covering IRA-related news events. `` When it comes to covering a demonstration in <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> or a riot or anything, we ca n't start saying you go there or you do n't go there or we would n't have a free press,'' said spokesman <PERSON> Ian </PERSON> <PERSON> Scott </PERSON>. Conservative lawmaker <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Mates </PERSON> said the publicly funded <ORGANIZATION> British </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Broadcasting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> and commercial <ORGANIZATION> Independent </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Television </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> should exercise self-restraint. `` I think you have to look very carefully at the question of whether you would be getting 10,000 people coming to these funerals if it was n't for the fact that they are whipped up out there,'' Mates said in a radio interview. `` They are paraded by the <ORGANIZATION> IRA </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Sinn </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fein </ORGANIZATION> for the TV cameras so that the world can see that their heroes are being buried with the total support of the whole population ... they're made to go along because it's got to be a spectacle.'' Cameras filmed the initial attack Saturday on the soldiers' car in <LOCATION> Belfast </LOCATION>, but were chased off by mourners before the beating began in earnest, and they did not film the shooting of the men a few minutes later. British newspapers, however, published pictures of the near-naked bodies the next day. `` It was a shocking, brutal event and I was as horrified as anyone to see things like that on my television screen,'' said <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Grade </PERSON>, head of commercial Channel 4. `` But you can not sanitize a story ... The <ORGANIZATION> BBC </ORGANIZATION> and ITN made people understand the horror of the situation,'' he told Today newspaper. `` We take great care in what we show,'' said <ORGANIZATION> ITN </ORGANIZATION> spokeswoman <PERSON> Geraldine </PERSON> <PERSON> Sharp-Newton </PERSON>. But `` by not showing it we'll not make it go away.'' Still, there are inconsistencies. British networks often preface violent scenes with a warning to viewers, but none preceded the <LOCATION> Belfast </LOCATION> footage. In the <LOCATION> Irish </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Republic </LOCATION>, the state media can not broadcast interviews with officials of <ORGANIZATION> Sinn </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fein </ORGANIZATION>, on the grounds that they speak for an outlawed organization, the <ORGANIZATION> IRA </ORGANIZATION>. <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> has imposed stringent curbs on reporting in what are defined as `` unrest areas.'' Offenders face prison, fines or expulsion. The South Africans say violent incidents dropped by 35 percent immediately after the restrictions were decreed in June 1986. International criticism of <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>'s handling of <LOCATION> Palestinian </LOCATION> unrest has prompted charges that foreign networks distort the country's image and inflame unrest President <PERSON> Chaim </PERSON> <PERSON> Herzog </PERSON> asked this month whether <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> democracy should `` allow this weapon to be turned against my children and my country.'' <PERSON> Henry </PERSON> <PERSON> Kissinger </PERSON>, the former <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> secretary of state, and Mayor <PERSON> Ed </PERSON> <PERSON> Koch </PERSON> of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> have suggested that <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> ban TV crews outright from the occupied <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Gaza </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Strip </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> has not gone that far, but on March 4 the military for the first time banned reporters and TV crews from extensive areas of the occupied lands. They have since renewed the ban repeatedly, generally on a smaller scale.
