<HEAD>Senate Urges Talks With USSR To Curb `Bandit' Fishing</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> is urging the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration to open negotiations with the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> aimed at curbing uncontrolled `` bandit'' fishing from international waters in the <LOCATION> Bering </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sea </LOCATION>. A 79-0 vote on Monday approved a non-binding, sense-of-the-Senate resolution which declares that foreign fishing fleets are using a zone located between the 200-mile fishing limits established by the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> as `` a staging ground for raids'' into one of the richest fishing grounds in the world. According to the resolution, immediate action to protect <LOCATION> Bering </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sea </LOCATION> fishery resources is needed because of lack of cooperation by other high-seas fishing nations under existing agreements. The resolution calls for the convening of U.S.-Soviet negotiations to impose a moratorium on all fishing in the zone, a ban which would stay in effect until an international fishery management agreement is negotiated. Because of its location, completely surrounded by <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> and Soviet territorial waters, the 4,500 square mile area is known variously as `` the hole in the doughnut'' or `` the doughnut.''
</TEXT>
