<HEAD>Ohio Primary Too Late, Professor Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SPRINGFIELD, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>'s urban problems and those of some other northeast states, are being left behind in the presidential primary shuffle because their primaries are held too late, an elections researcher said. <PERSON> Linda </PERSON> <PERSON> L.M </PERSON>. <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON>, a political science professor at <ORGANIZATION> Wittenberg </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>, also said <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION> should consider holding caucuses, instead of a popular vote. Caucuses allow elected officials and party leaders more say, and `` they're better informed on the issues and they know what it takes to get elected,'' she said. <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION> last year considered moving the May 3 primary to mid-March, but lawmakers dropped the idea when Gov. <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Celeste </PERSON> failed to include it in his budget. Ms. <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON> does n't expect <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> leaders to institute major reforms, partly because they like the long primary season for state and local candidates. She said they more easily can influence those primaries.
