<HEAD>Rightists Win Big in El Salvador</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUGLAS GRANT MINE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The rightist <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nationalist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Alliance </ORGANIZATION> handily defeated the governing <ORGANIZATION> Christian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democrats </ORGANIZATION> in legislative and municipal elections this week, election officials announced. The defeat presented President <PERSON> Jose </PERSON> <PERSON> Napoleon </PERSON> <PERSON> Duarte </PERSON>, the staunchest <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> ally in <LOCATION> Central </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>, with the prospect of an uphill climb in his final year in office. Presidential elections are set for March 1989. <PERSON> Mario </PERSON> <PERSON> Samayoa </PERSON>, the president of the <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Elections </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION>, told journalists `` more than 50 percent'' of the votes cast on Sunday went to the alliance, known by its Spanish acronym of Arena. He declined to be more specific, saying complete returns would be ready shortly. The announcement Monday of a majority for <PERSON> Arena </PERSON> signaled a triumph even greater than the rightists had predicted. They had 13 deputies in the outgoing 60-seat <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assembly </ORGANIZATION>, which the centrist <ORGANIZATION> Christian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democrats </ORGANIZATION> controlled with 33 seats. Arena appeared assured of at least 31 seats in the new chamber. The party predicted it would have 35. Local media projected 33-35 seats for the rightists. The Christian Democrats were expected to get about 22 seats. Voters ignored a leftist guerrilla boycott call and threats of violence to cast ballots. The guerrillas said the elections were illegitimate, contending that free and fair elections could not be held in wartime. <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> sent <ORGANIZATION> El </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Salvador </ORGANIZATION> almost $ 600 million in military and economic aid last year, more than the amount given to any country in the hemisphere. Arena candidate <PERSON> Armado </PERSON> <PERSON> Calderon </PERSON> <PERSON> Sol </PERSON>, a 39-year-old lawyer, won the mayor's race in <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Salvador </LOCATION>, the capital and home to 1.5 million of the country's 5 million people. <PERSON> Calderon </PERSON> <PERSON> Sol </PERSON> defeated <ORGANIZATION> Christian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> candidate <PERSON> Alejandro </PERSON> <PERSON> Duarte </PERSON>, the president's son <PERSON> Samayoa </PERSON> said <PERSON> Arena </PERSON> won most of the rest of the country's municipalities Arena benefited from a groundswell of popular discontent with the <ORGANIZATION> Christian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democrats </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Duarte </PERSON> won the presidency in 1984 on a platform of ending the war and improving the Salvadoran economy. The 8-year-old war continues, unemployment is estimated at 40 percent and annual inflation is estimated at nearly 40 percent. <PERSON> Arena </PERSON>'s campaign slogan was `` Change for the Better.'' Arena President <PERSON> Alfredo </PERSON> <PERSON> Cristiani </PERSON>, who kept his assembly seat, told <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> his party would try to reach agreement on fundamental points with all parties represented in the legislature, including how to wage the war. `` If the guerrillas do not accept the proposal we will make them, which will be the result of a national consensus, they do not leave any other way out but a military solution,'' he said. He indicated that <PERSON> Arena </PERSON>, which has considerable support and good connections with military officers, would work to step up offensives against the rebels. `` This low intensity conflict idea should be erased,'' he said, referring to smaller-scale, U.S.-backed counterinsurgency tactics that have been adopted by the Salvadoran army. In <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> hailed <LOCATION> El </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Salvador </LOCATION>'s national elections and called them a strong victory for the democratic process Sen. <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Lugar </PERSON>, R-Ind., who led an observer team named by President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>, called the election honest and important `` because power transferred peacefully'' and `` the rebels did n't win <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Redman </PERSON>, asked whether the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration had any reservations about a rightist victory, said that `` we do n't choose sides in these kinds of elections.'' The fiercely nationalistic Arena was formed in 1981, with retired army Maj. <PERSON> Roberto </PERSON> <PERSON> d'Aubuisson </PERSON> its founder. <PERSON> D'Aubuisson </PERSON> has strongly criticized the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and is considered the driving force behind early 1980s death-squads.
