<HEAD>With PM-Panama Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 Here is a chronology of events in the Panamanian crisis: THURSDAY, FEB. 25 _ <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>'s president, <PERSON> Eric </PERSON> <PERSON> Arturo </PERSON> <PERSON> Delvalle </PERSON>, announces he is dismissing Gen. <PERSON> Manuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Antonio </PERSON> <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON>, indicted on <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> drug charges, as defense chief and replacing him with Col. <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON> <PERSON> Justines </PERSON>, chief of staff. Justines refuses job. FRIDAY, FEB. 26 _ Noriega-dominated <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assembly </ORGANIZATION> votes to oust <PERSON> Delvalle </PERSON>. Education Minister <PERSON> Manuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Solis </PERSON> <PERSON> Palma </PERSON> named new head of state. <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> opponents call for general strike in protest. SATURDAY, FEB. 27 _ <PERSON> Delvalle </PERSON> goes into hiding in <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>, defying <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON>'s order that he leave country. MONDAY, FEB. 29 _ General strike begins with mixed participation. TUESDAY, MARCH 1 _ General strike gains support. Locally owned banks close. International banks limit withdrawals. Security forces crack down on protests amid scattered violence. WEDNESDAY, MARCH 2 _ Doctors join businesses in general strike. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials announce they will ask <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> banks to freeze <LOCATION> Panamanian </LOCATION> government assets. THURSDAY, MARCH 3 _ Organizers end general strike as support fades. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> federal courts block withdrawal of <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> funds from <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> banks. FRIDAY, MARCH 4 _ <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Panama </ORGANIZATION> says it can not meet banks' cash demands. International banks fearing a run on deposits close their doors. Local banks remain closed. SUNDAY, MARCH 7 _ Retired people unable to cash pension checks rally in streets. MONDAY, MARCH 8 _ Riot police disperse demonstrators in <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> with tear gas and birdshot. TUESDAY, MARCH 9 _ Government says banks can reopen but no one can cash checks or withdraw funds. Few banks respond. FRIDAY, MARCH 11 _ <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> imposes economic sanctions, including eliminating trade preferences for <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> and withholding <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Canal </LOCATION> fees from the <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> government by placing them in escrow. <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> government meets army payroll. <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION> tells <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> it would accept <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> if he asked for asylum. MONDAY, MARCH 14 _ Public employees stage work stoppages and riot after government is unable to pay wages. Riot police use tear gas and truncheons to disperse hundreds blocking traffic. <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> sends 100 additional military personnel to beef up security around canal. TUESDAY, MARCH 15 _ At least a dozen are injured in demonstrations as civil servants take to streets to demand paychecks. Government says it will make partial payments to public employees. WEDNESDAY, MARCH 16 _ <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> survives abortive coup attempt by dissident officers of <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Forces </ORGANIZATION>. Violent demonstrations occur and workers strike at state-run electric, water and telephone companies, ports in <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> and Colon and government ministries. THURSDAY, MARCH 17 _ Government declares a `` state of urgency'' and soldiers patrol capital. Defense Forces take control of utilities and ministries, but most workers remain off their jobs. FRIDAY, MARCH 18 _ <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> meets with <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> officials who offer freedom from extradition on drug charges if he will seek asylum in third country. <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> reportedly says he wants to remain in <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> and take part in formation of transitional government. SUNDAY, MARCH 20 _ <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Secretary of State <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> says indictments against <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> would not be dropped and <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> could not have say about government after his departure. MONDAY, MARCH 21 _ Armed soldiers patrol <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> as general strike paralyzes nation. <PERSON> Solis </PERSON> <PERSON> Palma </PERSON> announces <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> has offered to resign before May 1989 elections if opponents agree to talks. Opposition leaders and <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> reject <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON>'s offer.
