<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Tamil rebels armed with knives, swords and axes attacked two villages in northern <LOCATION> Sri </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lanka </LOCATION> early today and slashed 13 Sinhalese civilians to death, Sri Lankan military officials said. Three people, including a woman and two children, were reported hospitalized with serious injuries. The latest deaths raised to at least 125 the number of civilians slain in their villages since March 2. Most of the victims have been members of the Sinhalese majority community on the island, but 22 of the victims were minority Tamils killed in a reprisal raid on their community March 11. The military officials said today's attacks occurred shortly after midnight in the villages of <LOCATION> Pudukulam </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Madavuvaithakulam </LOCATION>. They lie just south of <LOCATION> Vavuniya </LOCATION>, a town 130 miles northeast of <LOCATION> Colombo </LOCATION>. The officials, who briefed reporters on condition their names not be used, said at least six children and two women were among the victims. They quoted police as blaming the <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tigers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tamil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Eelam </ORGANIZATION> for the attack. The <ORGANIZATION> Tigers </ORGANIZATION> militia, the largest of the Tamil rebel groups, has rejected an Indian-backed peace accord aimed at ending their nearly five-year separatist rebellion. Government officials have said the attacks on villages are aimed at disrupting a long-running government resettlement program for poor Sinhalese. Most of the slayings have occurred in the <LOCATION> Eastern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> District </LOCATION>, where the resettlement program has been having the greatest impact. Tamils, who are mostly Hindus, make up 18 percent of <LOCATION> Sri </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lanka </LOCATION>'s 16 million population They claim they are discriminated against by the majority <PERSON> Sinhalese </PERSON> <PERSON> Buddhists </PERSON>, who control the government and military. Moderate Tamils want more autonomy for their communites in the north and east of <LOCATION> Sri </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lanka </LOCATION>, where they predominate, while militants are fighting for a separate nation. Sinhalese make up about 75 percent of the island's population. The rest are Moslems and descendants of early European colonizers. After the peace accord was signed last July, <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> sent more than 50,000 troops to the island to try to stop the <ORGANIZATION> Tigers </ORGANIZATION>' continuing campaign <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> has become involved because it has more than 60 million ethnic Tamils in its own southern states who are sympathetic to their Sri Lankan brethren.
