<HEAD>A Chilly Night in the Northeast</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 Wintry temperatures gripped the Northeast today as mild weather prevailed over southern states. Temperatures were generally below freezing in the nation's northeast quarter, with readings in the teens and single digits over much of the <LOCATION> Great </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lakes </LOCATION> region and the northern <LOCATION> Atlantic </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Coast </LOCATION> A reading of 7 degrees shortly after midnight set a record in <LOCATION> Binghamton </LOCATION>, N.Y. The old record low for the date was 8 degrees in 1965. In contrast, readings were in the 50s and 60s in the southern and central Plains and the valleys and deserts of the <LOCATION> Southwest </LOCATION>. Highs Monday were in the 80s. Wet weather was confined to widely scattered rainshowers in the Northwest. Snow fell in some higher elevations, and snow advisories were in effect for the <LOCATION> Cascade </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mountains </LOCATION>, where 6 to 10 inches were considered possible today and tonight. Clouds were over much of the <ORGANIZATION> Rockies </ORGANIZATION>, as well as the northern Plains and the Northwest. Today's forecast called for scattered showers in the <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Northwest </LOCATION> and southern <LOCATION> Minnesota </LOCATION>, possible snow in northern <LOCATION> Minnesota </LOCATION> and scattered snow in northern <LOCATION> Maine </LOCATION>. High temperatures were expected to be in the 50s or 60s across much of the nation; the 20s across northern <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> England </LOCATION>; the 30s extending from the northern <LOCATION> Great </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lakes </LOCATION> region into central and southern <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> England </LOCATION>; the 40s in northern <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> state, the northern <LOCATION> Rockies </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> northern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Plains </LOCATION>, the upper <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Valley </LOCATION> an