<HEAD>Government Closes Anti-Apartheid Newspaper</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID CRARY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The government today shut down a militant anti-apartheid newspaper for 12 weeks, contending the church-backed New Nation threatened public safety. A special decree issued by Home Affairs Minister <PERSON> Stoffel </PERSON> <PERSON> Botha </PERSON> said further issues of the black-oriented weekly newspaper are `` totally prohibited'' through June 10. He acted a day after the newspaper, published by the <ORGANIZATION> Southern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> African </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bishops </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Conference </ORGANIZATION>, lost a court appeal seeking to forestall government action while it challenged state-of-emergency censorship regulations. Technically, the New Nation could resume publication after three months, but <PERSON> Botha </PERSON> could close it again if its contents dissatisfied him. The paper's senior staff has not announced whether operations will be resumed after the suspension. With a circulation of 50,000 to 60,000, the 2-year-old newspaper is the largest in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> to devote virtually its entire content, including sports and entertainment sections, to politically-related developments. The newspaper had a full-time staff of 22 and employed 32 correspondents who covered anti-apartheid activity in the rural areas where the majority of blacks live. Several employees already had resigned in anticipation of closure by <PERSON> Botha </PERSON>, who disclosed his intentions in January. The newspaper's editor, <PERSON> Zwelakhe </PERSON> <PERSON> Sisulu </PERSON>, has been detained without charge for 16 months. He joined the New Nation after a year as a <ORGANIZATION> Niemann </ORGANIZATION> fellow at <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>. Authorities have banned four of the paper's editions and seized two. Police have raided the paper's offices, and it was the first of six publications warned by <PERSON> Botha </PERSON> that they could be closed for three-month periods or censored for publishing material he found objectionable. State-of-emergency regulations give <PERSON> Botha </PERSON> nearly unlimited powers to deal with newspapers he feels might contribute to unrest. He does not have to give reasons for his actions. The New Nation lost an initial court challenge of the regulations and intends to pursue its case in an appellate court. But on Monday, a <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> rejected the newspaper's bid to prevent closure during the appeal process. The New Nation's acting editor, <PERSON> Gabu </PERSON> <PERSON> Tugwana </PERSON>, said closure of his paper would be `` an action against the whole media.'' `` There are many more axes hanging in the air that will fall on many others,'' he said, referring to warnings issued by <PERSON> Botha </PERSON> to other publications. In a warning letter to the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nation </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Botha </PERSON> cited several items which he said threatened public safety, promoted revolution, enhanced the image of outlawed organizations or fomented hostility toward the security forces. The items he listed included: _ A picture of <PERSON> Oliver </PERSON> <PERSON> Tambo </PERSON>, president of the outlawed <ORGANIZATION> African </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, opening a new office in <LOCATION> Nairobi </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Kenya </LOCATION> _ A story about an arson attack on the offices of the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Front </ORGANIZATION>, the nation's largest anti-apartheid coalition _ A picture of relatives of condemned blacks at a news conference in which they appealed for clemency for 32 men and women sentenced to hang _ An advertisement quoting a Psalm and urging the government to abolish torture
