<SECOND>PM-East-Appeal,0459</SECOND>
<HEAD>East Dissidents Ask Right To Object To Military Service</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TEDDIE WEYR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 An unprecedented number of dissidents and intellectuals from six East European nations have signed an appeal for recognition of the right to object to military service. The appeal, published Monday in <LOCATION> Vienna </LOCATION>, was signed by 77 Soviets, including <PERSON> Andrei </PERSON> <PERSON> Sakharov </PERSON>, nuclear physicist and 1975 Nobel Peace laureate. The signatories from <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Czechoslovakia </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Yugoslavia </LOCATION> called for recognition `` of citizens' right to conscientious objection and alternative service.'' The appeal was addressed to the 35-nation Conference on Security and Cooperation in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, which has been meeting in <LOCATION> Vienna </LOCATION> since November 1986 to review compliance with the 1975 <LOCATION> Helsinki </LOCATION> Accords on military security, economic coopertion and humanitarian issues. The appeal asked the delegations to work toward an agreement on the right not to serve in the military. Hungarian dissident writer <PERSON> Miklos </PERSON> <PERSON> Haraszti </PERSON>, who signed the appeal and helped initiate it, told a news conference Monday that conscientious objection was one of the main reasons for political imprisonment in <LOCATION> Eastern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>. `` Hundreds of our East European compatriots are sent to prison because of their non-violent conscientious stands,'' the appeal said. `` These young men would like to serve the community by caring for the old and sick instead of performing military service.'' <PERSON> Haraszti </PERSON> said no country in the <ORGANIZATION> Warsaw </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pact </ORGANIZATION> allows its citizens the right to object to military service, while <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> countries do. `` Eastern <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> punishes people for not wanting to look at other countries as enemies,'' he said. <PERSON> Haraszti </PERSON> said 438 people and groups have signed the appeal so far. The London-based <ORGANIZATION> East </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cultural </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foundation </ORGANIZATION>, which helped coordinate collecting signatures, said in a news release it was the first time a large number of Soviet citizens joined a joint East bloc initiative. <PERSON> Haraszti </PERSON> said the appeal, the fourth such joint effort of East European dissidents, carried the largest number of signatures so far. <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Uhl </PERSON>, a member of the Czechoslovak human rights group Charter 77, was invited to come to <LOCATION> Vienna </LOCATION> for presentation of the appeal. However, in a letter read in part at the news conference and then distributed, <PERSON> Uhl </PERSON> complained that `` no Czechoslovak citizens, including those who have passports, could go to <LOCATION> Vienna </LOCATION> in response to your invitation.'' His letter said, `` Internationalization of our demands ... is also very important because it provides a comparison between the legal and factual state of affairs prevailing in the individual East European countries.'' Dissidents in East bloc countries estimated the total number of people in prison for objecting to military service at about 300 to 400.
