<HEAD>Police Report Widespread Unrest During Protest Strike</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Two blacks were killed, seven injured and 39 arrested during a nationwide protest strike that brought the most extensive violence this year, police reported today. Dozens of buses, delivery vans and private cars were stoned or firebombed on Monday, the 28th anniversary of the <LOCATION> Sharpeville </LOCATION> massacre, and in many cases security forces used tear gas, rubber bullets, birdshot and dogs to disperse rioters, police headquarters said. Police said the two deaths and five of the injuries resulted from attacks by blacks on blacks. Two blacks were injured by police. Several of those arrested were trying to prevent children from going to school and workers from going to work, police said. The protest strike was organized by anti-apartheid activists in defiance of emergency regulations barring calls for such actions. Hundreds of thousands of black workers and students stayed away from jobs and classes, both to mark the anniversary of the 1960 police shootings of 69 blacks in <LOCATION> Sharpeville </LOCATION> and to protest the recent bannings of black opposition groups. The <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Education </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Training </ORGANIZATION> said class boycotts were reported at 694 of the black schools under its control, 9 percent of the total. The Star of <LOCATION> Johannesburg </LOCATION>, the country's largest daily newspaper, said protest strikes would continue `` as long as grievances are not directly addressed.'' `` Instead of tension being relieved through the extension of rights and the removal of restrictions, each new round of protests is met with further clamps which inevitably lead to fresh protests.'' Five students from <LOCATION> Johannesburg </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> the </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Witwatersrand </ORGANIZATION> went to local police headquarters today with a bunch of roses for <PERSON> Rosemary </PERSON> <PERSON> Hunter </PERSON>, the president of the student council who was detained under state-of-emergency regulations Monday. The students said a police lieutenant refused to accept the bouquet and told them: `` This is a police station, not a hospital.'' Ms. <PERSON> Hunter </PERSON>, a law student, was taken from her parents' home at dawn Monday. Police have not commented on the detention. By law and custom, apartheid establishes a racially segregated society in which the 26 million blacks have no vote in national affairs. The 5 million whites control the economy and maintain separate districts, schools and health services.
