<HEAD>Astronomers Scoff at Quake Prediction Based On Planetary Alignment</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 1st graf to make it 16th-century, sted ancient,
astrologer; SUBS 3rd graf to conform</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By LEE SIEGEL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Astronomers say a vague prediction by the 16th-century astrologer <PERSON> Nostradamus </PERSON> has caused unfounded fear that an alignment of planets will trigger an earthquake that will destroy <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> in May. `` There is no alignment of planets in May, and even if there were, it would n't have anything to do with earthquakes,'' <PERSON> Edwin </PERSON> <PERSON> Krupp </PERSON>, director of <ORGANIZATION> Griffith </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Observatory </ORGANIZATION>, said Monday. But rumors of an impending earthquake, spurred by writings of the French astrologer and the movie `` The Man Who Saw Tomorrow,'' which is being sold on videocassette, prompted more than 100 fearful people to call the observatory in recent weeks, <ORGANIZATION> Krupp </ORGANIZATION> said. `` We an tell by the phone calls that many people are getting needlessly afraid of the possibility of an earthquake,'' he said, calling the quake predictions `` bunk.'' Astronomer <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Mosley </PERSON>, the observatory's program supervisor, wrote recently: `` There are 11,000 earthquakes each year in the <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> area strong enough to be recorded. There may be a significant earthquake in May 1988, here or elsewhere ... but if there is, it will have nothing to do with the planets' positions.'' <PERSON> Mosley </PERSON> said followers of Nostradamus, who lived from 1503 to 1566, have claimed he predicted such events as the Russian Revolution, the assassinations of <PERSON> John </PERSON> and <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON> and the Japanese attack on <LOCATION> Pearl </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Harbor </LOCATION>. But Nostradamus' predictions, written in rhyme, `` are exceptionally vague, and in general it is only after the fact that a link can be made between his rhymed prediction and an historical event,'' <PERSON> Mosley </PERSON> said. He said `` The Man Who Saw Tomorrow'' claimed <PERSON> Nostradamus </PERSON> wrote that an alignment of <ORGANIZATION> Saturn </ORGANIZATION>, Jupiter, Mercury, <PERSON> Venus </PERSON> and <ORGANIZATION> Mars </ORGANIZATION> will cause a major earthquake in May in <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>. `` The prophecy is quoted incorrectly in the movie,'' <PERSON> Mosley </PERSON> said. `` Nostradamus predicts a severe hailstorm, not an earthquake. ... There is no clue that tells us where this hailstorm will occur.'' <PERSON> Mosley </PERSON> said: `` The last time the planets were supposed to align and trigger mass destruction in <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> was in 1982, the year of the ` Jupiter Effect,''' a book that claims the planets' tidal influence causes quakes. `` Untold millions did not die in 1982 and there's no reason to think that anything will happen in 1988,'' he said. Even if the planets were aligned, `` their gravitational effect would be completely negligible ... and they would have no effect on our planet's weather, tides or earthquakes,'' <PERSON> Mosley </PERSON> added.
