<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 Residents of the Northeast dug out winter overcoats and ski jackets as unseasonable cold gripped the region today, three days into spring. Temperatures were generally below freezing, with readings in the teens and single digits over much of the <LOCATION> Great </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lakes </LOCATION> region and northern <LOCATION> Atlantic </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Coast </LOCATION>. Subzero readings were reported at a few locations in <LOCATION> Maine </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION>. `` Somebody left the door open on the north side of the house,'' said <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON>, a forecaster for the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Weather </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Albany </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.Y. </LOCATION> `` We're getting a strong cold wind right out of <LOCATION> Hudson </LOCATION>'s Bay.'' Spring has been in disguise since it began Sunday; the 21-degree high in <LOCATION> Albany </LOCATION> on Monday was about 20 degrees below normal. `` Some of the early blooming flowers may be negatively affected. Some of the crocuses may not fare too well,'' said <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Good </PERSON>, a horticulturalist in <LOCATION> Ithaca </LOCATION>, N.Y. However, many flowers may not have poked their shoots out of the ground yet, <PERSON> Good </PERSON> said. `` For the most part there has n't been enough warm weather yet to really get things started.'' Ten Northeastern cities reported records this morning, including <LOCATION> Allentown </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Pa. </LOCATION>, where the 15 degree low tied the record set in 1965; <LOCATION> Mansfield </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>, where the 14-degree mark shaved a degree off the 1965 record; and <LOCATION> Syracuse </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.Y. </LOCATION>, where the 5 degrees cut three degrees off a record set in 1959. A reading of 7 degrees shortly after midnight set a record in <LOCATION> Binghamton </LOCATION>, N.Y. The old record low for the date was 8 degrees in 1965. <LOCATION> Bradford </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Pa. </LOCATION>, was the coldest place in the nation at 2 a.m. EST, at zero degrees, and it was 18 degrees at 5:30 a.m. in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION> residents looked out on a <LOCATION> Lake </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Erie </LOCATION> that was still mostly ice-covered. However, a warming trend was expected to put winter to flight this afternoon and Wednesday, with temperatures rising into the 40s and 50s in the <LOCATION> mid-Atlantic </LOCATION> region. <PERSON> Steve </PERSON> <PERSON> Smith </PERSON>, a weather specialist for <ORGANIZATION> Environment </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Canada </ORGANIZATION> at <LOCATION> Churchill </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Manitoba </LOCATION>, on the shores of <LOCATION> Hudson </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> Bay </LOCATION>, disavowed responsibility for the cold. <PERSON> Smith </PERSON> said a high-pressure system was driving the cold air from the north. `` That's why you're getting our weather. So you really ca n't blame us,'' he said. `` They call us the polar bear capital of the world. While you're getting our weather, we've got a south wind that's pushing our temperatures above normal,'' <PERSON> Smith </PERSON> said In <LOCATION> Churchill </LOCATION>, the high Monday was 10 degrees, seven degrees above normal. The low was minus 15.
