<BYLINE>By NABILA MEGALLI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAMA, Bahrain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 An Iranian gunboat and helicopter attacked a Norwegian-operated tanker carrying volatile chemicals through the <LOCATION> Persian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION> at dawn today. A Greek supertanker later was reported set ablaze in another Iranian raid. Two crewmen were killed and four wounded in the first attack, on the 38,534-ton Havglimt, flying the <LOCATION> Singapore </LOCATION> flag, shipping executives reported. <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> fired a missile at <LOCATION> Tehran </LOCATION> today and mounted air raids on seven other cities, the <ORGANIZATION> Iraqi </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> reported. The missile was the 45th aimed at the Iranian capital since the <LOCATION> Iran-Iraq </LOCATION> `` war of cities'' resumed March 13. Shipping executives said an unidentified <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> warship patrolling the gulf picked up 10 seamen, who were floating in a raft after abandoning the Greek supertanker, the 357,130-ton <PERSON> Stavros </PERSON> <PERSON> G.L </PERSON>. The executives said the other 19 Greek crewmen stayed on board to fight the flames. A salvage tugboat soon joined the effort. There were no casualties aboard the Greek vessel, which was attacked about 1 p.m. only a few miles south of where the Havglimt was hit in a dawn attack. The attacks were the seventh and eighth by <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> on neutral shipping since Friday. They came as 51 crewmen remained missing and were presumed dead after an Iraqi raid on two tankers near <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> Kharg </LOCATION> island oil terminal Earlier reports had said 54 crewmen were missing. The escalation of the `` tanker war'' came as <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> were locked in a series of missile duels and air raids on each other's major cities The two nations have been at war for 7 -LCB- years. Today's missile attack on <LOCATION> Tehran </LOCATION> was the 106th such attack since Feb. 29. About 65 Iranian missiles have slammed into <LOCATION> Baghdad </LOCATION> in that time. Also Monday, <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> launched an artillery and rocket attack on <LOCATION> Basra </LOCATION>, inflicting heavy casualties, <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> said. The Havglimt tanker, carrying ammonia and operated by the Oslo-based <ORGANIZATION> Havtor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, was hit at dawn about 12 miles northwest of <LOCATION> Dubai </LOCATION>, said the gulf-based shipping executives, who spoke on condition of anonymity. The dead crewmen were identified as <LOCATION> Singapore </LOCATION> nationals, and the ship's Norwegian captain was among the wounded. Other members of the 26-man, multinational crew were mainly treated for inhalation of ammonia vapors, according to the executives. Four needed hospitalization. The fire in the engine room of the stricken tanker was brought under control by salvage tugboats, but the flames later reignited in the crew's quarters, the executives said. The British destroyer HMS Exeter, on patrol in the area, dispatched a helicopter to help rescue the crew, many of whom had fainted from fumes leaking from blasted cargo holds, the shipping sources said. A navy medical team wore gas masks as they were lowered from the helicopter onto the tanker to help airlift the seamen. The bodies of the dead and the injured crew members were lowered onto a salvage tugboat, which took them to a hospital at the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arab </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Emirates </LOCATION> port of <LOCATION> Dubai </LOCATION>, the sources said. The shipping executive said at least one gunboat raided the vessel with machine-gun fire and rocket-propelled grenades. Forty minutes later, a helicopter fired rockets at the tanker. `` They went for the accommodation quarters. There were plenty, plenty of hits all over,'' said <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> photographer <PERSON> Greg </PERSON> <PERSON> English </PERSON>, who flew over the stricken tanker in a helicopter. <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> resumed attacks on Iranian oil shipping lanes on March 8, after a lull in attacks in the <LOCATION> Persian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION> for about a month. On Monday, Iranian gunboats attacked and set ablaze the 10,168-ton Spanish refrigerator ship Iberian Reefer and the 61,762-ton Liberian-registered Fumi with rocket grenades. No casualties were reported on board either ship. At least 51 crewmen remained missing from <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION>'s Saturday attack near <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> Kharg </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION> oil terminal. The attack destroyed two Iranian-owned ships, the 253,837-ton <LOCATION> Sanandaj </LOCATION> and the 316,379-ton Avaj. The Norwegian <ORGANIZATION> Shipping </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> reported today that the number of missing was `` imprecise,'' but the latest figure was 51. Earlier, Norwegian officials had said 54 crewmen, mostly Iranians and Asians, were presumed dead. A Swedish engineer also was among the missing. <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Shipping </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> said it had no independent confirmation of the deaths and was working on the basis of gulf sources. Both ships were owned by the <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Iranian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tanker </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, but the <LOCATION> Sanandaj </LOCATION> crew was hired by a Norwegian firm, <ORGANIZATION> Viking </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Engineering </ORGANIZATION>, and another <LOCATION> Norwegian </LOCATION> company, Scanact, had part interest in the Avaj. The maritime insurance firm, <ORGANIZATION> Lloyd </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORG