<HEAD>Resolution On Religion And Politics Tabled</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LEE LINDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Delegates to the American Jewish Congress convention voiced concern today about the role of religious groups in politics but tabled a resolution urging churches and synagogues to refrain from active roles in political campaigns. The proposed resolution, which will be redrafted, had suggested it was `` inherently dangerous'' for religious groups to identify with one candidate or one political party. It reaffirmed the right of all people, including clergy, to seek political office. The resolution is expected to be taken up at a later national meeting of the group, but leaders did not indicate whether it would be during the 1988 presidential campaign. Discussion centered on whether delegates should take a strong stand against practices by two religious leaders now running for president, <PERSON> Pat </PERSON> <PERSON> Robertson </PERSON> and Rev. <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>. The tabled resolution said `` certain recent practices of both these candidates are troubling issues,'' citing <PERSON> Robertson </PERSON>'s use of church-owned buses to bring supporters to caucuses and <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>'s effort during the Super Tuesday primaries to collect contributions in churches In their nearly unanimous decision to redraft the resolution, delegates said it could be counterproductive and also should not refer to any individual. On Monday night, an <ORGANIZATION> AJC </ORGANIZATION> leader urged that a new world Zionist meeting be convened in <LOCATION> Jerusalem </LOCATION> in the 1990s to unify Jews everywhere with Israelis and to heal the division over how to achieve peace with the Arabs. `` We are indeed one people, sharing one destiny, no matter where we live,'' executive director <PERSON> Henry </PERSON> <PERSON> Siegman </PERSON> told delegates at the 70th anniversary convention. <PERSON> Siegman </PERSON> reiterated the <ORGANIZATION> AJC </ORGANIZATION>'s support for a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> plan calling for talks on Palestinian autonomy in the occupied <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Gaza </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Strip </LOCATION>, followed by an international peace conference including <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> and its Arab neighbors. He also spoke out against <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> Prime Minister <PERSON> Yitzhak </PERSON> <PERSON> Shamir </PERSON>'s condemnation of Jews who object to his opposition to the plan. `` The Jewish people everywhere, and not only those who vote in support of a particular <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> party, have a right to speak up when they believe certain policies profoundly violate a legacy that belongs to the Jewish people collectively, even if finally only the citizens of <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> will vote and make those decisions on which their security depends,'' <PERSON> Siegman </PERSON> said.
