<HEAD>Spain's Strong Latin Ties Lead To Asylum Offers</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Panama, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSAN LINNEE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MADRID, Spain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The offer of asylum to Gen. <PERSON> Manuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Antonio </PERSON> <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> maintains a <LOCATION> Spanish </LOCATION> tradition of opening its doors to Latin Americans seeking a place of exile. The hospitality stems from historic and cultural ties with <LOCATION> Latin </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> that transcend <LOCATION> Spanish </LOCATION> party politics. But the <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION> that is prepared to offer asylum to <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> is far different from the country that took in ousted <LOCATION> Cuban </LOCATION> dictator <PERSON> Fulgencio </PERSON> <PERSON> Batista </PERSON> in 1959. During the 36-year rule of Gen. <PERSON> Francisco </PERSON> <PERSON> Franco </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION> became a haven for <PERSON> Batista </PERSON>, Colombian ruler <PERSON> Gustavo </PERSON> <PERSON> Rojas </PERSON> <PERSON> Pinilla </PERSON>, ousted Argentine leader <PERSON> Juan </PERSON> <PERSON> D. </PERSON> <PERSON> Peron </PERSON>, toppled Dominican President <PERSON> Juan </PERSON> <PERSON> Bosch </PERSON> and Venezuelan strongman <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON> <PERSON> Perez </PERSON> <PERSON> Jimenez </PERSON>. <PERSON> Rojas </PERSON> <PERSON> Pinilla </PERSON> arrived in 1957 after a stopover in <LOCATION> Bermuda </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Batista </PERSON> spent time in <LOCATION> Madeira </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Lisbon </LOCATION> before settling in <LOCATION> Madrid </LOCATION> and <PERSON> Peron </PERSON> wandered from <LOCATION> Paraguay </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> Venezuela </LOCATION> after his 1955 ouster before arriving in <LOCATION> Seville </LOCATION> in 1960. Both <PERSON> Perez </PERSON> <PERSON> Jimenez </PERSON>, ousted in 1958, and <PERSON> Bosch </PERSON>, a democratically elected president toppled in 1963, lived in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> before coming to <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Franco </PERSON>'s conditions for receiving all were simple: maintain a low profile and do n't meddle in Spanish or foreign politics. In the case of <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON>, Prime Minister <PERSON> Felipe </PERSON> <PERSON> Gonzalez </PERSON> says Spanish policy is to accept requests when asylum could help maintain or restore democracy in a specific country. As conditions for accepting <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION> requires that he himself ask for asylum, that the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> agree not to seek his extradition on drug-trafficking and money-laundering charges filed against him in <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> federal courts, and that <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> honor the 1977 treaty under which control of the <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Canal </LOCATION> will revert to <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> in 2000. <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> has refused to leave <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>. But he has said he is willing to step down as military leader prior to the 1989 presidential elections in <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Santiago </PERSON> <PERSON> Varela </PERSON> <PERSON> Diaz </PERSON>, a <PERSON> Gonzalez </PERSON> spokesman, said since <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION>'s transition to democratic government in 1977, the type of political exile in <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION> has changed considerably `` Since then, <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION> has taken in many Chileans, Argentines and Uruguayans fleeing from military dictatorships,'' he said. `` The case of <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> and <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> is separate, but it is a concrete example of our willingness to serve as a support for a democratic solution to a problem.'' During the waning years of the Franco regime in the early 1970s, not all the Latin American exiles in <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION> were rightist dictators. Former Economics Minister <PERSON> Manuel </PERSON> <PER