<HEAD>GE Recalls Surge Suppressors</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Electric </ORGANIZATION> is recalling about 45,000 GE and RCA brand electric surge suppressors which could present a shock hazard, the <ORGANIZATION> Consumer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Product </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Safety </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> said Tuesday. Known as <ORGANIZATION> Electronic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Protection </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> surge suppressors, the units were sold nationally between October 1986 and December 1987, officials said. No injuries have been reported, but officials said a defect in some of the units could allow their metal housings and the metal housings of any connected appliances to become electrified, creating the potential for a shock. Involved are GE surge suppressor models EPC-6S, EPC-6MS, EPC-4NS and EPC-CPU as well as RCA models SK416 and SKF416. The items sold for $ 40 to $ 60. They resemble a gray power strip with four or six electrical outlets. Each has an on-off switch, a power indicator light, resettable circuit breaker and 6-foot cord. The product was designed to prevent damage from sudden electrical power surges to such equipment as personal computers, stereos, televisions and other appliances. Owners of the units should disconnect them from the outlet, without touching the metal housing, and mail them to <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Electric </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, Attn: <ORGANIZATION> EPC </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Recall </ORGANIZATION>, P.O. Box 8203, <LOCATION> Beaverton </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ore. </LOCATION>, 97076. The units will be replaced and postage costs reimbursed. Anyone needing more information may contact GE at 1-800-626-2000 or the safety commission at 1-800-638-2772.
