<HEAD>Hanford Nuclear Reservation Plant Shut Down</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RICHLAND, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A <LOCATION> Hanford </LOCATION> nuclear reservation plutonium processing plant was shut down and two technicians were suspended in the wake of an incident involving the improper transfer of chemicals, a <ORGANIZATION> Westinghouse </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hanford </ORGANIZATION> spokesman said today. Operations at the Plutonium-Uranium Extraction Plant, or PUREX, were suspended over the weekend as a precautionary measure, said spokesman <PERSON> Rudy </PERSON> <PERSON> Cortez </PERSON>. The temporary suspension resulted from an incident Friday in which a valve was left open and a batch of the wrong chemical solution was transferred to a tank, <PERSON> Cortez </PERSON> said. As a consequence, the certifications of two nuclear process operators were suspended for failing to follow operating procedures, he said. The event was declared to be an infraction of a `` criticality prevention specification.'' A `` criticality'' is an uncontrolled nuclear chain reaction resulting in a rapid buildup of radiation and heat. It is caused by such factors as the amount, shape, density and enrichment of plutonium or uranium and the manner in which they are stored. There was no danger of a criticality incident and no danger of a radioactiuve release to the environment, <PERSON> Cortez </PERSON> said. It has not been determined how long operations will be suspended, he said. The PUREX plant was closed for a time in October 1986 because of safety concerns over plutonium handling and possible accidents. Westinghouse Hanford officials who took over operation of the plants in July 1987 promised to make safety a top priority. The chemical transfer incidents were the latest in a series of safety-related ones at the PUREX facility, which dissolves fuel rods to remove plutonium and uranium for reprocessing. The cause of contamination of two crane operators at the facility March 14 is still under investigation. Radioactive contamination was found in one crane operator's home and another contamination was found on another operator as he prepared to leave the plant. Both men were decontaminated and returned to work the next day.
