<HEAD>Familiar Froufrou at Ungaro, Safe Classics at Laroche</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUZY PATTERSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Fashion Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The inimitable <PERSON> Emanuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Ungaro </PERSON> has toned down his sexy, exaggerated look, but he had enough opulent fabrics in his Tuesday winter ready-to-wear show to please the fans of his show-off styles. <PERSON> Laroche </PERSON>, by contrast, preferred the ultra simple lines, in short skirts and tailored pants. <PERSON> Ungaro </PERSON>, along with <PERSON> Christian </PERSON> <PERSON> Lacroix </PERSON> and some others, remains in the `` feminine-fancy'' school of designing, despite this season's trend to somewhat simpler, more practical styles In one variation on the tent dress, he puts bright flowered and flowing silk or light wool tunics over narrow skirts. But <PERSON> Ungaro </PERSON> also sneaked in a print chemise dress from the 1950s, knotted and draped baggily in back. Rose, salmon and dusky shades of blue and green or brighter tones all turned up in <PERSON> Ungaro </PERSON>'s vast color palette. Crazy over fabrics, he mixed them with somewhat less abandon this time around. <PERSON> Paisley </PERSON>, brown or camel colored short coats were often paired with outfits that had lean knee-revealing skirts in polished leather: a flashy, fascinating new look here. <PERSON> Ungaro </PERSON> still likes big bertha or flounced collars using them on lots of ensembles. He ca n't forget leg o'mutton sleeves, ruffles and bows, either. As usual, velvet was used richly in <ORGANIZATION> Ungaro </ORGANIZATION>'s suits _ as a single-lapelled collar, a wide jacket-hem border, or overall in dressy suits in shades of claret, deep purple or black. Another success in opulence was to pair a velvet-piped paisley long and fitted jacket with a teeny draped black jersey cashmere skirt. Even pants looked dressy, with their little velvet or irridescent taffeta vests and fitted jackets, plus flowered blouses. Bows on derrieres or the hips of draped pants gilded the lily a bit. <PERSON> Ungaro </PERSON>'s body-hugging draped cocktail numbers were less risque than last season, nearly hitting the knee instead of grazing the upper thigh. <PERSON> Ungaro </PERSON>'s less expensive line called `` Solo <PERSON> Donna </PERSON>,'' shown last week, had much of the same allure, but looked much more comfortable. His ribbed spencers with flowered sheaths or his checked skirts with windowpane plaid reefers could even be worn to the office without raising eyebrows. At <PERSON> Guy </PERSON> <PERSON> Laroche </PERSON>, meanwhile, the trend to short skirts continued, but the collection looked more sane than sexy. Designed by <PERSON> Guy </PERSON> <PERSON> Douvier </PERSON>, the clothes had a certain played-down attraction. Soft wool coats were ample and short, with caped and huge squared-off collars. These were worn over tailored trouser suits and dresses in browns, tans or striking jewel colors. Bright belted tunics with dark skirts or straight tunics with elaborate wool embroidery in swirly ribbon patterns were also items for the safe dresser. The diagonal plaid belted suits in frank yellow, green or red make a peppy change. Late-day flocked velvet or cloque silk suits were easily fitted, and dance dresses with shirred tops and puffy taffeta skirts also came down the runway. The shocking pink or black flounced taffeta gowns, short in front, long in back, are no shockers, but are gala enough to wear without looking like a wallflower. <ORGANIZATION> Hermes </ORGANIZATION>, usually known for expensive hand-finished leather bags and scarves, is making a bigger effort to steer customers to the ready-to-wear racks. Designed by <PERSON> Eric </PERSON> <PERSON> Bergere </PERSON>, the line remained firmly in the classic sportswear vein. As the redingote sweeps <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Hermes </ORGANIZATION> had the last word in its brown or red models topped with jumpers' netted bowler hats But fitted suits with oval skirts and plaid spencers or A-line jackets over slim gray flannel hats looked just as appealing for a country weekend or informal moments in town. Even if the clothes do n't set trends, they will never look out of place, especially with those incomparable silk scarves.
