 Authorities have granted Polish Mormons permission to build their first chapel in this communist country, a church missionary said Tuesday. The only other Soviet bloc country in which there are Mormon chapels is <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, where there are about 5,000 members of the Church of <PERSON> Jesus </PERSON> <PERSON> Christ </PERSON> of Latter-day <ORGANIZATION> Saints </ORGANIZATION>. Although Polish authorities registered the <ORGANIZATION> Mormon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION> as an official religious organization in 1977, only recently were there enough Polish Mormons to warrant building a chapel, said Elder <PERSON> Juliusz </PERSON> <PERSON> Fussek </PERSON>. <PERSON> Fussek </PERSON>, 66, a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> citizen of Polish descent, was sent to <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> to do missionary work by the church headquarters in <LOCATION> Salt </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lake </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>. He is a retired printer. There are only about 100 Mormons in this overwhelmingly Roman Catholic country, but <PERSON> Fussek </PERSON> said he saw `` great prospects'' for the church's development `` because people are interested in religion here.'' `` You need members first before building a chapel ... Because there is no point having a chapel and it standing empty,'' said <PERSON> Fussek </PERSON>. `` We are very pleased with the cooperation and help we have received from the government,'' he said. At the end of last year, Polish Mormons applied for permission to build a chapel and cultural-educational center in <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION>'s western <LOCATION> Wola </LOCATION> district, <PERSON> Fussek </PERSON> said The local council for Wola approved the project at a meeting last week and forwarded its decision to the <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION> city president for formal approval, he said. <PERSON> Fussek </PERSON> said the chapel, expected to open in 1989 or 1990, would be paid for by donations from Polish Mormons and the church headquarters in <LOCATION> Salt </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lake </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>. He did not have any estimate of the cost. <PERSON> Fussek </PERSON> said there were about 300-400 Mormons, mostly of German descent, in the country before World War II. The Mormon chapel did not reopen after the war because most of its members fled the country when the Communists took power. More than 35 religious denominations are active in <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> today. Ninety percent of <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>'s 37 million people are baptized Catholics.
