<TEXT>
 Here is a summary of developments Monday and today involving <LOCATION> Honduras </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>:
</TEXT>
<HEAD>HONDURAS:</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION> on Monday withdrew its soldiers from the border but the frontier remained tense, with Honduran patrols on the lookout for any booby traps left behind by the <ORGANIZATION> Sandinistas </ORGANIZATION>. President <PERSON> Jose </PERSON> <PERSON> Azcona </PERSON> <PERSON> Hoyo </PERSON> said the 3,200 <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> troops sent to <LOCATION> Honduras </LOCATION> last week, after the Nicaraguan army was accused of sending 2,000 men across the border in pursuit of Contras, may not be needed much longer. However, the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> troops were to begin a new set of joint maneuvers with the Honduran army today. On Monday, a <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> transport helicopter crashed while participating in a military exercise and 10 soldiers were injured. Other helicopters evacuated the soldiers for medical treatment.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>NICARAGUA:</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 The Sandinista government, in its second day of peace talks with <ORGANIZATION> Contra </ORGANIZATION> rebels, today proposed a 30-day truce, and the U.S.-backed Contras said a cease-fire should last 45 days. The Nicaraguan government proposal calls for the rebels to lay down their arms, while the Contras said rebels should move into cease-fire zones during the truce. On Monday, the two sides agreed to a battlefield truce during the three days of the peace talks.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>WASHINGTON:</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> today met with <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> Republicans in a bid to renew interest in his stalled aid package for the Contras. The proposed aid package would offer a one-year, $ 48 million infusion of humanitarian aid, as well as continued authority for the <ORGANIZATION> CIA </ORGANIZATION> to deliver weapons remaining in rebel inventories, estimated at as much as $ 2.5 million.
