<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The cost of mailing a first-class letter will jump from 22 cents to a quarter on April 3, the <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. Postal Service announced today. The hike is part of an overall increase in postage rates, replacing charges that have been in effect since Feb. 17, 1985. The biggest increase will affect so-called `` junk'' mail, with rates for third-class advertising increasing nearly 25 percent. Magazines and newspapers will pay about 18 percent more, while postage charges for individual consumers will climb nearly 15 percent.
