<HEAD>Government Closes Anti-Apartheid Newspaper</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID CRARY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The government Tuesday shut down the New Nation, a combative, church-backed anti-apartheid newspaper, making it the first victim of a campaign to stifle militant publications. The government `` has killed the messenger instead of listening to the message.'' said <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Soal </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION> member for the liberal <ORGANIZATION> Progessive </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>. Home Affairs Minister <PERSON> Stoffel </PERSON> <PERSON> Botha </PERSON>, who has state-of-emergency powers to censor publications singlehandedly, said in a special decree that further issues of the black-oriented weekly newspaper are `` totally prohibited'' through June 10. Another Cabinet minister, <PERSON> Stoffel </PERSON> <PERSON> van </PERSON> <PERSON> der </PERSON> <PERSON> Merwe </PERSON>, said the New Nation was closed because it advocated violent overthrow of the government and supported communism. `` It is absolutely astonishing that a publication issued under the name of a Christian organization should act in this way,'' he said. The closure came a day after the 2-year-old newspaper, published by the <ORGANIZATION> Southern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> African </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bishops </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Conference </ORGANIZATION>, lost a court appeal seeking to postpone government action while it challenged the censorship regulations. The New Nation technically could resume publication after three months, but <PERSON> Botha </PERSON> could close it again if its contents in the ensuing issues dissatisfied him. Bishop <PERSON> Reginald </PERSON> <PERSON> Orsmond </PERSON>, chairman of the newspapers' publishing board, said the 22-member staff would be retained during the suspension. He declined to predict would would happen to the paper if the suspension was extended. Orsmond accused the government of `` suppressing the voice of the people.'' Authorities have banned four of the New Nation's editions and seized two. Police have raided the paper's offices, and it was the first of six publications warned by <PERSON> Botha </PERSON> that they could be closed or forced to obey an in-house censor if they continued to publish material he found objectionable. Anglican Archbishop <PERSON> Desmond </PERSON> <PERSON> Tutu </PERSON>, whose stepped-up political activities in recent weeks have angered the government, described the New Nation's closure as `` quite scandalous.'' `` Only a government that is scared or already totalitarian, or very close to totalitarian, behaves in the kind of way that ours does,'' <PERSON> Tutu </PERSON> said. With a circulation of about 60,000, the New Nation is the largest newspaper in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> to devote virtually its entire content, including sports and entertainment pages, to politically related developments. One regular feature was a learning section, `` to bridge the deficiencies of apartheid education.'' In simple language, it told readers about black activists not covered in school courses and explained how to apply for a job, feed a baby nutritiously, treat an injured riot victim or protect oneself from tear gas. The newspaper's editor, <PERSON> Zwelakhe </PERSON> <PERSON> Sisulu </PERSON>, has been detained without charge for 16 months. He joined the New Nation after a year as a Neiman Fellow at <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Sisulu </PERSON>'s father, <PERSON> Walter </PERSON>, former secretary-general of the now-outlawed <ORGANIZATION> African </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, is serving a life prison term along with <ORGANIZATION> ANC </ORGANIZATION> leader <PERSON> Nelson </PERSON> <PERSON> Mandela </PERSON> for treason and sabotage. State-of-emergency regulations give <PERSON> Botha </PERSON> nearly unlimited powers to deal with newspapers he feels might contribute to unrest. Under the regulations, he does not have to give reasons for his actions. The New Nation lost an initial court challenge of the regulations and intends to pursue its case in an appellate court. But on Monday, a <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> rejected the newspaper's bid to prevent closure during the appeal process. The last edition of the New Nation, on March 17, said the government was `` bent on destroying what little freedom of expression is left in a country where the majority are voteless.'' `` Because the New Nation dared to act as their voice, it has now been damned to silence,'' the paper said. The issue also carried a quotation from President P.W. <PERSON> Botha </PERSON> on the front page: `` I believe in a free press and in free news media.''
</TEXT>
