<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Don </PERSON> <PERSON> Hewitt </PERSON>, who marks his 40th anniversary with CBS News Tuesday, recalls landing his first job at the network after a friend suggested his experience at a newsphoto service might come in handy. `` I said, what does <ORGANIZATION> CBS </ORGANIZATION> want with picture experience? Radio does n't need any pictures. He said, ` No _ television.' I said whata-vision?'' Today, the 65-year-old outspoken creator and executive producer of `` 60 Minutes'' is looking beyond current television technology, foreseeing a time when networks are superfluous and television news is beamed directly into subscribers' homes. `` I think that the network news departments, they might not even work for a network 10 years from now,'' said <PERSON> Hewitt </PERSON>, who produced the the network's first television newscast, `` <PERSON> Douglas </PERSON> <PERSON> Edwards </PERSON> With the News,'' and later the `` CBS Evening News'' with <PERSON> Walter </PERSON> <PERSON> Cronkite </PERSON>. `` There might not be any networks because it may be an outmoded delivery system.''
