<HEAD>Court Hears Case Examining Adequacy of Miranda Warning</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID FOX</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A warning advising suspects that they may remain silent and are entitled to an attorney is not adequate to protect their rights under the Constitution, the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> was told on Tuesday. <PERSON> Donald </PERSON> <PERSON> Honchell </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> Cook </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ill. </LOCATION>, public defender appealing the 1983 murder conviction of a gang member, said the `` Miranda warning'' does protect a person from self-incrimination under the Fifth Amendment. But he argued that, once a suspect is indicted, the warning alone is not enough to protect the Sixth Amendment guarantee of legal help. The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> is using the <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION> case to decide whether the warnings that police have been required to give since 1966 are adequate to advise suspects of their right to legal aid. It ruled in `` Miranda vs. <LOCATION> Arizona </LOCATION>'' that people accused of crimes must be informed of their rights to remain silent, to have a lawyer, to have counsel present during questioning and to receive free legal assistance if needed. <PERSON> Honchell </PERSON> contended that even if a defendant has waived his rights under <PERSON> Miranda </PERSON>, he has an automatic right to a lawyer as soon as he is indicted and may not be asked from that point on to submit to interrogation. `` There is a shield around the accused through which the police can not get a waiver,'' <PERSON> Honchell </PERSON> said. `` At no time after the indictment should the police be allowed to go to the defendant, seek a waiver and begin to question.'' However, a prosecutor said authorities would be unfairly limited if they can not interrogate a defendant who is read his rights and then agrees to speak without a lawyer present. <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> Donatelli </PERSON>, an assistant <LOCATION> Cook </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> prosecutor, also said the warning is perfectly understandable to defendants. `` They have a common-sense meaning that enables defendants to understand they have both a right to counsel and that things could go against them if they do n't have a lawyer with them when they're in custody and questioned,'' <PERSON> Donatelli </PERSON> said <PERSON> Honchell </PERSON> said police coerced his client, <PERSON> Tyrone </PERSON> <PERSON> Patterson </PERSON>, 22, of <LOCATION> Evanston </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ill. </LOCATION>, into making incriminating statements by telling him he had been indicted. But <PERSON> Donatelli </PERSON> said <PERSON> Patterson </PERSON> understood his rights and agreed to be questioned anyway. <PERSON> Patterson </PERSON>, a member of the Vice Lords street gang, is serving a 24-year sentence at the <ORGANIZATION> Pontiac </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Correction </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> for his conviction in the Aug. 21, 1983 beating death of rival <PERSON> Black </PERSON> <PERSON> Mobsters </PERSON> gang member <PERSON> James </PERSON> `` Pudge'' <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>. According to court briefs, he was arrested on a misdemeanor charge following a gang fight, received a `` Miranda warning'' and signed a statement waiving his right to counsel. Two days later, after initially refusing to discuss <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>'s death, <PERSON> Patterson </PERSON> was told he had been indicted, signed a second Miranda waiver and agreed to answer questions, the briefs said
