<HEAD>Experimental Treatment Avoids Surgery for Bladder Cancer
^Eds: For release at 6 p.m. EST, time set by source</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DAYTONA BEACH, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A bladder cancer treatment that avoids surgery has shown promising results in a preliminary study, a scientist said Tuesday. Twenty-one of 36 patients who have completed the drug-and-radiation therapy were found free of disease for three to 21 months, said <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Prout </PERSON>, professor of surgery at <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION>. Three others showed partial remission, while treatment failed outright for nine patients. The other three were not evaluable, he told science writers at a seminar sponsored by the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cancer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Society </ORGANIZATION>. The study focused on patients whose cancers had invaded the bladder muscle, a condition usually treated by surgically removing the bladder, <PERSON> Prout </PERSON> said. If the bladder is removed, the patient must wear a bag to collect urine for the rest of his life. It also essentially ends sexual activity. The experimental treatment attacks liver cancer with radiation to the pelvis, plus treatment with a mix of the drugs methotrexate, velban and cis-platinum.
