<HEAD>Civil Rights Chairman Blasts Newark Mayor's `Uncivil Rights'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETE YOST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Civil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rights </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> announced Tuesday that he was bestowing an `` Uncivil Rights Award'' on the mayor of <LOCATION> Newark </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.J. </LOCATION>, for pressuring Rep. <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Rodino </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-N.J. </LOCATION>, to retire because he is white. Chairman <PERSON> Clarence </PERSON> <PERSON> Pendleton </PERSON>, who is black, said that <PERSON> Rodino </PERSON> receives the `` Victim of Uncivil Rights Award'' for the way in which he was treated by `` <LOCATION> Newark </LOCATION> power brokers'' who have decided that `` he is not their representative _ he's just the wrong color.'' At a news conference where he criticized the Civil Rights Restoration Act and the resignation under pressure of <ORGANIZATION> Gallaudet </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> President <PERSON> Elisabeth </PERSON> <PERSON> Zinser </PERSON>, <PERSON> Pendleton </PERSON> said he was instituting his own personal `` Uncivil Rights Award'' program in an effort to highlight `` the absurdities committed in the name of civil rights.'' <PERSON> Pendleton </PERSON>'s first recipient was <LOCATION> Newark </LOCATION> Mayor <PERSON> Sharpe </PERSON> <PERSON> James </PERSON>, who is black. <PERSON> James </PERSON> has said the courts carved out <PERSON> Rodino </PERSON>'s 10th Congressional District more than 12 years ago to elect a minority congressman, and that `` it's time to get that done.'' <PERSON> Pendleton </PERSON> said <PERSON> James </PERSON> worked `` with several other <LOCATION> Newark </LOCATION> politicians'' in pressuring <PERSON> Rodino </PERSON> to retire. <PERSON> Rodino </PERSON> announced March 14 that he would not seek a 21st term in <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>. Minorities, who make up the bulk of <PERSON> Rodino </PERSON>'s district, have clamor