<HEAD>Pentagon Concerned by Dip in Reinlistments</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NORMAN BLACK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Military Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The military services had no problem meeting their recruiting goals last last year, but there were `` some adverse signs'' for the future in lower re-enlistment results, the <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> said Tuesday. Releasing its latest quarterly report, the <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said the <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Marine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corps </ORGANIZATION> signed up 66,300 recruits during the first quarter of fiscal 1988, which ended Dec. 31. That compares with a combined goal of 65,400, and all four services met or exceeded their individual quarterly objectives, the <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> said. Moreover, the percentage of first-time enlistees with a high school diploma actually increased slightly _ from 92 percent during the period in fiscal 1987 to 93 percent in fiscal 1988. `` Retention -LRB- re-enlistment -RRB- results for the first quarter of fiscal 1988 were also satisfactory, but with some adverse signs,'' <PERSON> Grant </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Green </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, assistant defense secretary for manpower, said in a statement. `` First-term re-enlistment rates trailed comparable fiscal 1987 statistics for three of the four services. And while overall career retention rates showed some improvement over fiscal 1987, retention among second-term and career <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> petty officers continued to decline after falling short of objectives last year.'' The <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> pays particular attention to the percentage of men and women willing to re-enlist after completing their initial obligation, viewing it as a measure not only of military readiness and experience in the force but also job satisfaction. According to the latest report, 46 percent of military personnel eligible to re-enlist for the first time during the period did so _ down from 49 percent during the comparable period in fiscal 1987. Some of the individual service declines, however, were much more precipitous. For example, the <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION>'s first term re-enlistment rate dropped from 74 percent to 62 percent over the year. The <ORGANIZATION> Marine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corps </ORGANIZATION>' rate dropped from 24 percent to 18 percent, and the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION>'s rate fell from 56 percent to 51 percent. The Army managed to buck the trend with a small increase, from 40 percent in fiscal 1987 to 43 percent this fiscal year. <PERSON> Green </PERSON> noted that various re-enlistment bonus programs had been suspended for 65 days during the period awaiting congressional action. `` But most retention measures have fallen several percentage points below their 1983-84 peaks, and this trend has been particularly noticeable among personnel in higher-technology skills that are in particular demand in the private sector,'' he added. Meanwhile, <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Howard </PERSON>, the <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION>'s chief spokesman, restated the administration's strong opposition to a cut in the 4.3 percent pay raise proposed for military personnel in fiscal 1989, which begins Oct. 1. The 4.3 percent hike exceeds the 2 percent proposed for civilian government workers and some congressional leaders are now arguing military and civilian workers should be treated the same. `` The comparability studies ... show an 11 percent gap between military and civilian pay,'' <PERSON> Howard </PERSON> said. `` The 4.3 percent pay raise is fully justified unless we want to return to the situation that we saw in the past where the disparity was so great that good people could n't afford to stay in the military.''
