<FIRST>u a AM-LiverCancer 1stLd-Writethru a0705 03-22 0608</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Liver Cancer, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0705,0617</SECOND>
<HEAD>Plant May Reduce Liver Cancer in Hepatitis Virus Carriers, Study
Suggests^
^Eds: Subs 2nd graf bgng ``The trends'' to explain why woodchucks
used in study.</HEAD>
<NOTE>For release at 6 p.m. EST.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MALCOLM RITTER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DAYTONA BEACH, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Extracts of a tropical plant appeared to reduce levels of hepatitis virus and liver cancer rates in woodchucks, a hopeful sign for the world's 200 million human virus-carriers at risk for the cancer, a scientist said Tuesday. The trends emerged in analysis of data on about 60 animals that had become infected with the woodchuck version of the hepatitis B virus, said <PERSON> Baruch </PERSON> <PERSON> Blumberg </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> Fox </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chase </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cancer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION>. Woodchucks are used in hepatitis research because the virus they carry so closely resembles the human hepatitis B virus. <PERSON> Blumberg </PERSON> stressed that the results are only suggestive, and a prelude to a formal study of the plant extract's effects. `` Even if it does n't get rid of the virus altogether, it may still be useful,'' he said after speaking to science writers at a seminar sponsored by the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cancer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Society </ORGANIZATION>. That is because the virus now can lie dormant for decades after infection, and if the extract can extend that period, it may essentially block the progression to liver cancer until after a person has died of something else, he said. Infection with hepatitis virus B has long been linked to later development of cancer originating in the liver, as opposed to cancer that starts elsewhere in the body and spreads to the liver. Studies in <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION> have found that male carriers of the virus run more than 200 times the risk of developing liver cancer than non-carriers, giving them a 40 percent chance of dying from the disease, <PERSON> Blumberg </PERSON> said. The cancer is particularly common in <LOCATION> Asia </LOCATION> and sub-Saharan <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>, he said. In the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, the cancer society expects about 6,000 new cancers of the liver this year. The best way to deal with the problem is vaccination at birth for people at risk of the disease, <PERSON> Blumberg </PERSON> said. Such a vaccine is not recommended for the American population generally because the overall risk is so low, he said. <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION> have programs for vaccinating newborn children, he said. His institution has established a vaccine program in <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION> directed at newborn children of carrier mothers and others in their household. He said he hopes other such programs will be established. But the world already has about 200 million carriers of the virus, and more will be added every day until vaccination programs become fully effective, he said. The plant, called Phyllanthus ammarus, grows in <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> and throughout the tropical world, <PERSON> Blumberg </PERSON> said. It can be grown in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, he said. The extract of the plant appears to fight the virus by blocking a substance called DNA polymerase that the virus needs to reproduce itself, he said. When the extract was injected into the bellies of woodchucks infected for a month, evidence of the virus disappeared, he said. Those infected longer showed decreases in the amount of virus in their blood. Treated animals also developed significantly fewer liver cancers than others, <PERSON> Blumberg </PERSON> said. Limited studies in animals suggest the extract does not cause significant side effects, he said. Scientists are trying to isolate the portion of the extract that fights the virus, he said. <PERSON> Raymond </PERSON> <PERSON> Koff </PERSON>, a liver disease specialist and professor of medicine at <ORGANIZATION> Boston </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>, said the work should be followed up with more study. `` Innovative, exciting stuff has to be looked at,'' he said in a telephone interview.
</TEXT>
