<SECOND>AM-AIDS-Government Workers,300</SECOND>
<HEAD>Official Calls New Guidelines `Reasonable'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JERRY ESTILL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Newly issued guidelines for dealing with federal employees infected with the AIDS virus are in line with the general anti-discrimination recommendations of the government's health department `` We worked very closely with the <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Personnel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Managment </ORGANIZATION> in developing them,'' Dr. <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Windom </PERSON> said Tuesday. `` The regulations are reasonable and reflect PHS concerns.'' <PERSON> Windom </PERSON>, No. 2 official of the <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Human </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION>, heads the seven-agency <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> that includes the <ORGANIZATION> Centers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Disease </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Control </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> , </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Food </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Drug </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institutes </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Windom </PERSON> will review the guidelines Thursday with personnel officers from about 30 major federal agencies. `` The federal government, as an enlightened and compassionate employer concerned with the health and welfare of its employees, has an obligation to show the way in addressing the realities of the AIDS epidemic,'' <PERSON> Constance </PERSON> <PERSON> Horner </PERSON>, director of the <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Personnel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Management </ORGANIZATION>, said in a memo accompanying the guidelines' initial distribution this week Quoting from <ORGANIZATION> CDC </ORGANIZATION> statements on AIDS in the workplace, the personnel office memo says, `` The kind of nonsexual person-to-person contact that generally occurs among workers and clients or consumers in the workplace does not pose a risk for transmission of AIDS.'' The guidelines instruct federal agencies to treat AIDS-infected employees `` in the same manner as employees who suffer from other serious illnesses'' and say there is `` no medical basis for employees refusing to work with such fellow employees or agency clients.' Fellow employes who disrupt agency functions by refusing to work with an AIDS-infected person could be subject to `` appropriate corrective or disciplinary action'' under the guidelines. AIDS, or acquired immune deficiency syndrome, is a contagious disease that attacks the body's immune system, rendering it incapable of resisting other diseases and infections.
