<HEAD>Free Market Flourishes Fleetingly In Brooklyn</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MITCHELL LANDSBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 For a few fleeting weeks, free enterprise thrived in <LOCATION> Brooklyn </LOCATION>. That was back in the good old days, about two months ago, when a thrifty commuter entering the <LOCATION> Greenpoint </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Avenue </LOCATION> subway station in the morning could buy a $ 1 subway ride for 50 cents. The bargain was offered by three crafty entrepreneurs, who discovered the key to a padlocked gate next to a turnstile. They unlocked the gate, put the padlock on the turnstile and went into competition with the <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Transit </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Authority </LOCATION>. From about 5 a.m. to 7 a.m. weekdays, the subway station was turned into a bargain basement, according to an account in Tuesday's <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> Newsday. And then the police found out. `` AS OF 2-15 FARE FOR RIDER WILL BE 55 CENTS PER PERSON,'' read a flyer handed to riders shortly after the police crackdown. `` AND NO PENNIES WILL NOT BE ACCEPTED NO MORE. ... PEOPLE WE HAD RUN IN WITH TRANSIT POLICE SO THAT WHY WE RAISE IT. WE COULD N'T AFFORD OF GETTING BUSTED.'' The flyer ended on a promotional note: `` CATCH THAT FARE SPECIAL.'' `` It became amusing,'' observed Transit Police Sgt. <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Sullivan </PERSON>, still slightly astonished by this flowering of the entrepreneurial spirit. `` Because we arrested them, they increased the fare.'' The police had been notified by an irate token clerk, who arrived with a uniformed police officer each morning at 7 a.m. to find her competitors fully engaged in business. The token booth was staffed only at rush hour. The rest of the day, patrons without tokens had to go to the main station entrance two blocks away; those with tokens could go through the cage-like turnstile _ until the discounters arrived. At first, the men scattered when the token clerk arrived. But after a while, <PERSON> Sullivan </PERSON> said, `` They were being so brazen that they would just retreat to the stairwell and wait for the uniformed cop to leave.'' Then they'd return to business, in full sight of the token clerk, whose business dwindled. About 100 riders a day were taking advantage of the reduced fare, plunking their money into a bucket beside the swinging gate. `` This really infuriated the railroad clerk,'' said <PERSON> Sullivan </PERSON>. Her complaints eventually led to undercover operations that resulted in the first arrests on Jan. 29. And the second arrests on Feb. 1. Each time, the men were issued desk appearance tickets and released. And each time, they went right back to work. On Feb. 16, the police raised the stakes against <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Franklin </PERSON>, 35, <PERSON> Kenneth </PERSON> <PERSON> Norris </PERSON>, 36, and <PERSON> Willie </PERSON> <PERSON> Brown </PERSON>, 22. This time they went to jail on charges including disorderly conduct, petty larceny, criminal tampering and other crimes. So far, <PERSON> Franklin </PERSON>, who, like <PERSON> Brown </PERSON>, lived in an apartment near the station, has pleaded guilty to disorderly conduct and served eight days in jail. <PERSON> Norris </PERSON>, who lived in a homeless shelter, has pleaded guilty to petty larceny and been sentenced to 70 hours of community service _ including washing subway stations. `` Even as we made the arrests, we had one guy in handcuffs and people were still walking up to him and trying to hand him money,'' <PERSON> Sullivan </PERSON> said. `` They were pretty slick in their operation. They thought they had all ends covered.''
