Michigan </LOCATION> caucuses, with <PERSON> Gephardt </PERSON> a distant third. <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> aides say that may be the reason for <PERSON> Gephardt </PERSON>'s attacks. On Tuesday, <PERSON> Gephardt </PERSON> stepped up the attack, questioning the sincerity of <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>' support for such legislation. `` I think he remains against it. I think it is a political ploy,'' <PERSON> Gephardt </PERSON> said. `` By what he has done, he is trying to have it both ways. ... Now that he is in <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION> and we are five days out from the caucuses, he wants to fool the people of <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION>.'' <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> said in <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION> late Monday that his position has n't changed `` He has been a strong opponent of the <PERSON> Gephardt </PERSON> bill from the begining, but has always been an advocate of leveling the -LRB- trade -RRB- playing field,'' said <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> spokesman <PERSON> Leslie </PERSON> <PERSON> Dach </PERSON>. <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>' staff on Tuesday pointed to quotes from the <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> governor last year in favor of the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> bill. On July 11, 1987, <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> said, `` I think the trade bill which the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> approved yesterday says if there is a consistent pattern of unfair trade practices ... there I think we have to do something.'' `` I feel a lot better about the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> bill'' than the <PERSON> Gephardt </PERSON> trade legislation, <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> said on Aug. 4, 1987. <PERSON> Gephardt </PERSON> said <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> `` has said in the past you do n't need new legislation. ... He has been profoundly negative about everything I have said about trade.'' The congressman, too, provided quotes from <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> last year _ quotes he said back up his charge of a flip-flop. `` The president today has all the authority he needs to do something about those unfair trade practices. We do not need more laws or more amendments,'' <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> said at the Aug. 8 debate at <ORGANIZATION> Drake </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>, according to <PERSON> Gephardt </PERSON> aides. In debates in <LOCATION> Dallas </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> told <PERSON> Gephardt </PERSON>, `` You want a law. <PERSON> Dick </PERSON>, I want to act.'' And earlier this year in <LOCATION> Lansing </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mich. </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Gephardt </PERSON> aides said, <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> said `` We do not need more legislation.'' The <PERSON> Gephardt </PERSON> amemdment and the <PERSON> Riegle </PERSON> bill do differ, but both try to strengthen potential retaliation against <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> trading partners for unfair practices. In general, the <PERSON> Riegle </PERSON> bill would target specific industries in foreign countries which engage in unfair practices. The <PERSON> Gephardt </PERSON> amendment would trigger retaliation against another country for running a big surplus with this country in part through unfair practices. `` <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> has always felt the president has had the authority to act. The <PERSON> Riegle </PERSON> amendment ... gives the president a better way to get there, but he can pretty much get there on his own now,'' <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> spokesman <PERSON> Dach </PERSON> said.
