<HEAD>Council Votes To Make Hotel Guests Show ID</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WARWICK, R.I. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The City Council has approved an ordinance requiring guests checking into the city's 11 hotels and motels to show identification. The measure was proposed in January following the discovery of the bodies of two women in different hotel rooms. The deaths, one attributed to strangulation and the other to drowning, were not related, authorities said. Mayor <PERSON> Francis </PERSON> <PERSON> X. </PERSON> <PERSON> Flaherty </PERSON> was expected to sign the ordinance in a couple of days, said mayoral spokeswoman <PERSON> Anne </PERSON> <PERSON> Turner </PERSON>. It would go into effect 20 days later, she said. Councilman <PERSON> Lincoln </PERSON> <PERSON> D. </PERSON> <PERSON> Chafee </PERSON>, the only one of the seven council members to vote against the ordinance Monday night, called the measure `` loose and vague'' and cautioned the council against `` stampeding to enact a bad bill.'' The ordinance was amended to say that information from a hotel registrant will be used only for emergencies or during criminal investigations. The <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Civil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberties </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> had complained that the original version violated the rights of individuals. The guest who pays for a hotel room would be required to show a driver's license, major credit card, state identification card, military identification card, passport, vehicle registration or vehicle title documents. Councilman <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Kenneth </PERSON> <PERSON> Wild </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, who proposed the ordinance in January, said it would help police investigate cases such as those of the two women. Identification would not be required of people other than the person signing for the room. Neither woman had paid for the room where she was found dead. In the drowning, two people were charged with leaving the scene of a death, but no one has been arrested in the strangulation, police said.
