<HEAD>With AM-Nixon-Fed</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GUY DARST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Lyn </PERSON> <PERSON> Nofziger </PERSON> tried unsuccessfully to make then-Interior Secretary <PERSON> Walter </PERSON> <PERSON> Hickel </PERSON> an emissary to protesting students after <PERSON> Hickel </PERSON>'s famous protest letter to President <PERSON> Nixon </PERSON> in 1970, according to newly released <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> documents. <PERSON> Nofziger </PERSON>, a long-time political aide to President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> who was convicted of illegal lobbying last month, was working in the White House congressional relations office at the time. A memorandum from <PERSON> Nofziger </PERSON> to H.R. <PERSON> Haldemann </PERSON>, <PERSON> Nixon </PERSON>'s chief of staff, turned up in the latest batch of <ORGANIZATION> Nixon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> files opened by the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Archives </ORGANIZATION> on Tuesday. <PERSON> Hickel </PERSON> wrote <PERSON> Nixon </PERSON> on May 6, 1970, after the invasion of <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION> by <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> forces in <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> had set off a storm of protest on the nation's campuses. He said that attacks on the protesters by Vice President <PERSON> Spiro </PERSON> <PERSON> T. </PERSON> <PERSON> Agnew </PERSON> were creating an impression of a lack of concern for `` the attitude of a great mass of Americans _ our young people.'' The letter, whose prompt appearance in newspapers dismayed the <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION>, said <PERSON> Nixon </PERSON> should, among other things, talk with members of the Cabinet from time to time. <PERSON> Hickel </PERSON> was quoted in news accounts as saying he had had only two personal meetings with <PERSON> Nixon </PERSON> since becoming secretary more than a year before. <PERSON> Nofziger </PERSON>'s memo, dated May 8, 1970,