<HEAD>Mitterrand Announces He Will Seek Second Term</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President <PERSON> Francois </PERSON> <PERSON> Mitterrand </PERSON> ended months of speculation on Tuesday by announcing that he will seek a second term. Opinion polls have put the 71-year-old Socialist in the lead for the two-stage election, beginning April 24, although he was not formally in the race. On Tuesday, <PERSON> Mitterrand </PERSON> appeared on the nationwide evening newscast of state-owned Antenne 2 television. When asked if he would run, <PERSON> Mitterrand </PERSON> paused dramatically, clearly relishing the moment, and answered with a single word: `` Oui.'' Yes. In reply to follow-up questions, the president said he decided to run because he thinks disunity threatened `` to tear the social fabric'' of <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>. `` I saw a risk that the country might fall again into the quarrels and divisions that have hampered it so often. I want <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> to be united ... not be taken in hand by the spirit of intolerance, by parties who want everything, by clans, by cliques,'' he said. As soon as <PERSON> Mitterrand </PERSON> declared, <PERSON> Michel </PERSON> <PERSON> Rocard </PERSON>, until now the <ORGANIZATION> Socialist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>'s only candidate, withdrew from the race and gave the president his full support. <PERSON> Mitterrand </PERSON>'s plans had been the subject of intense speculation. On some occassions he had indicated that he would preferred to retire and at other times hinted he would run because of a sense of duty. In the end, with four weeks remaining before voters go to the polls, duty called. The main conservative candidates, Premier <PERSON> Jacques </PERSON> <PERSON> Chirac </PERSON> and former Premier <PERSON> Raymond </PERSON> <PERSON> Barre </PERSON>, had criticized <PERSON> Mitterrand </PERSON> for being coy and cutting short the democratic debate. <PERSON> Mitterrand </PERSON> justified his silence by saying that with the premier campaigning it was up to the president to look after the nation's affairs in a non-partisan way The conservatives hope to end what the French call `` cohabitation,'' created when the conservatives ousted the Socialists from control of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assembly </ORGANIZATION> in March 1986, but were left with a <ORGANIZATION> Socialist </ORGANIZATION> president with two years to go in his term. The president is chief of state and has major duties in defense and foreign affairs. He appoints a prime minister who must be backed by a majority of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assembly </ORGANIZATION>. The premier then names his Cabinet and runs the government. <PERSON> Mitterrand </PERSON> said Tuesday that after watching the campaign, he feared opposing candidates were bringing on <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> disputes that threatened to damage the country. `` We need social peace,'' he said. `` Someone has to face up to this, and I shall do it.'' <PERSON> Chirac </PERSON> heads the neo-Gaullist Rally for the Republic and <PERSON> Barre </PERSON> the center-right Union for French Democracy. In a statement issued by <PERSON> Chirac </PERSON>'s campaign committee, the premier said: `` The stakes are now clear. There is on one side the <ORGANIZATION> Socialist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> which wants to retake power to lead a Socialist policy and its candidate casts aspersion on all the others.'' There was no immediate reaction from <PERSON> Barre </PERSON>. National polls consistently placed <PERSON> Mitterrand </PERSON> ahead of <PERSON> Barre </PERSON> and <PERSON> Chirac </PERSON> in a campaign that has been more a contest of styles than policies. A handful of minor-party contenders, including <PERSON> Andre </PERSON> <PERSON> Lejoinie </PERSON> of the once-powerful Communists, are expected to draw a combined total of 5 percent of the vote or less. <PERSON> Jean-Marie </PERSON> <PERSON> Le </PERSON> <PERSON> Pen </PERSON> of the extreme-right <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Front </ORGANIZATION> could get about 10 percent of the vote. A poll published in the Journal du Dimanche newspaper Sunday indicated 55 percent of the 1,813 people polled were satisfied with <PERSON> Mitterrand </PERSON>. Forty-eight percent were satisfied with <PERSON> Chirac </PERSON> as premier. Another recent poll, however, indicated 30 percent of those queried were undecided. <PERSON> Mitterrand </PERSON> told the TV audience Tuesday night that he would pursue the programs and policies of the last seven years. `` I have maintained the confidence of the French people,'' he said. He suggested that if he won, he might dissolve the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assembly </ORGANIZATION> and call for new parliamentary elections. The first round of the elections is to be held April 24 with a run-off between the top two candidates scheduled for May 8.
