 Almost a billion dollars must be allocated to the space station next year or <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> will have to abandon plans to build the orbiting platform, <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION> Administrator <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Fletcher </PERSON> said Tuesday. A substantial cut in the space station budget, added to delays caused by cuts in earlier years, will make it useless for the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aeronautics </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Space </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> to continue efforts to build the station, he said. `` This is year is crucial,'' <PERSON> Fletcher </PERSON> told the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> subcommittee on science, technology and space. `` Otherwise, we've got to just forget it and start over at a later date. But senators attending the hearing warned <PERSON> Fletcher </PERSON> that would be extremely difficult to get <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION> its entire requested budget in a year when federal dollars are tight because of deficit-cutting efforts. Seeral pressed him on how much of a reduction could be tolerated in the space station program, but <PERSON> Fletcher </PERSON> said the requested budget was the `` rock bottom'' that <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION> needs. <PERSON> Fletcher </PERSON> said a severe cut in the station budget last year caused a full year's delay, and another cut in fiscal year 1989, which begins Oct. 1, would make it `` a waste of the taxpayers dollars'' to continue the underfunded program. <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION>'s 1989 budget calls for a total of $ 967.4 million for the space station. Plans call for the station to be assembled in orbit and for crews to start living in the orbiting laboratory in the middle of the next decade. The station funds are part of a $ 11.5 billion appropriation request by <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION> that would include money for space shuttle missions, advanced shuttle rockets, aeronautical research and a study of the technology that will be needed one day to send astronauts back to the <LOCATION> moon </LOCATION> and possibly to <LOCATION> Mars </LOCATION>. The budget request, which was approved by President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>, is a 24 pecent increase over <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION>'s current spending blueprint. <PERSON> Fletcher </PERSON> said that unless <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> passes the entire space budget, there is no way for the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> to maintain world leadership in space. `` The entire future of the civil space program rides at risk on this budget,'' he said. `` This is a crucial year ... It will make or break the civil space program.'' <PERSON> Fletcher </PERSON> said the budget is the final boost needed for <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION>'s recovery from the 1986 Challenger disaster, in which a space shuttle was destroyed and seven astronauts killed The shuttle fleet has been grounded since while the space agency corrected flawed equipment that caused the accident. <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION> tentatively plans to resume shuttle flights in August. Two are planned for this year, seven in 1989 and 10 in 1990. `` Without this increase, <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION> will be in serious trouble,'' <PERSON> Fletcher </PERSON> said. `` A major cut would be equivalent to the Challenger disaster itself.''
