<HEAD>Trial Begins For Scholar Accused Of Selling Stolen Lincoln Letters</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs 6th graf, `Mount told...' to CORRECT spelling to
Haughey, sted Houghey.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A scholar abused research privileges at the Library of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Archives </ORGANIZATION> to steal and try to sell letters signed by <PERSON> Abraham </PERSON> <PERSON> Lincoln </PERSON>, <PERSON> Winston </PERSON> <PERSON> Churchill </PERSON> and other historic figures, a prosecutor said Tuesday. <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Merrill </PERSON> <PERSON> Mount </PERSON> also defaced some letters between <PERSON> Lincoln </PERSON> and Civil War generals to remove government markings that would have alerted a rare documents dealer to the fact they were stolen, Assistant <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Attorney <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> <PERSON> Murphy </PERSON> said in his opening statement at <LOCATION> Mount </LOCATION>'s trial. But Mount's attorney, <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> McGinty </PERSON>, argued <ORGANIZATION> Mount </ORGANIZATION> had legally collected the documents and shoddy record-keeping led the <ORGANIZATION> Library </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Archives </ORGANIZATION> to believe the letters were part of their collections. <PERSON> McGinty </PERSON> said the government would offer no evidence showing Mount stole the documents, a point <PERSON> Murphy </PERSON> conceded. Mount, 59, a Washington-based author of several artists' biographies, tearfully denied the allegations, but predicted he would be convicted Mount told reporters outside court that associates in <LOCATION> Ireland </LOCATION>, including Prime Minister <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Haughey </PERSON>, had seen the documents when <PERSON> Mount </PERSON> lived in <LOCATION> Ireland </LOCATION> during the 1960s. But <PERSON> Mount </PERSON> said a government freeze on his assets prevented him from bringing witnesses to the <LOCATION> Unite