<SECOND>AM-Health Costs-Bowen,540</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bowen Says Hospitals Engaging In `Medical Arms Race'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JERRY ESTILL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The government's top health officer said Tuesday that hospitals have engaged in a kind of medical arms race that assures neither quality care nor good value for the dollar. `` Sometimes you can save money and also improve care, like concentrating certain procedures in hospitals that specialize in them,'' said <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Human </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> Otis </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Bowen </PERSON>. `` This not only leads to better results for the patient, it also allows us to benefit from economies of scale.'' <PERSON> Bowen </PERSON>'s remarks to a conference of the <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Care </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Quality </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Alliance </ORGANIZATION> followed a report by the 28-member coalition that cautioned against emphasizing cost control to the point that the `` quality of care _ and quality of life _ are adversely affected.'' The health secretary acknowledged that the government is concerned about rising costs in the Medicare and Medicaid programs, but said, `` We wo n't accomplish anything if we sacrifice quality for lower costs.'' `` One reason today's health care is so expensive is that the financing of that care is little more than a collection of disincentives to practice cost-effective medicine,'' he said. <PERSON> Bowen </PERSON> contended that `` hospitals, in order to attract doctors and their patients, have bought and often duplicated the latest in medical hardware in a kind of medical arms race.'' Another reason for concern, he said, is that government tax policies which do not tax employer-paid health insurance coverage like some other fringe benefits `` have encouraged employers and unions to bargain for ever-greater first-dollar coverage in health insurance plans.'' `` Compounding this folly,'' <PERSON> Bowen </PERSON> continued, `` most insurance plans cover expensive high-tech procedures and slight preventive services. And all of this has made patients and their families all but oblivious to costs, since they pay so little out of pocket.'' Turning to <ORGANIZATION> Medicare </ORGANIZATION>, he said creation of the program 23 years ago `` created a powerful incentive for the health care industry to develop the technology to treat the chronic, degenerative diseases that afflict the aging.'' <PERSON> Bowen </PERSON> said he was not suggesting those procedures are bad. `` On the contrary,'' he said, `` They have improved the quality of life for Americans of all ages.'' `` Still to be decided is how much is too much. ... How much heroic medical care and how many procedures to keep a dying patient alive are desirable for the patient, the family and, not least of all, for society at large? When is such care merely prolonging the act of dying rather than contributing to longer life, or at least some type of quality to it?'' <PERSON> Bowen </PERSON>, a physician whose first wife died of cancer and whose mother recently died in a nursing home, said: `` Sometimes our high-tech capability lures us into pursuing expensive answers when less costly ones are available. Our veneration of technology has become a cultural blindspot that sometimes keeps us from pursuing practical solutions to our problems.'' The theme of the conference was `` Balancing Health Care Costs, Quality, and Access: The Challenge for the Next Administration.'' The alliance membership includes the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, the Alzheimer's Disease and <ORGANIZATION> Related </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Disorders </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> Arthritis </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foundation </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cancer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Society </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Academy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pediatrics </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> on the Aging.
</TEXT>
