<FIRST>r a AM-ProfessionalFund-Raisers     03-22 0581</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Professional Fund-Raisers,0598</SECOND>
<HEAD>High Court To Study State's Disclosure Law</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN FLESHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RALEIGH, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION>'s attorney general is preparing to ask the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> to uphold a state law requiring professional fund-raisers for charities to tell potential donors how the money will be used. The nation's highest court is scheduled to hear arguments Wednesday on <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION>'s petition to reverse lower-court rulings, which struck down the 1985 law as a violation of the First Amendment's freedom of speech guarantee. Both sides agree that the outcome of the case could have a nationwide impact on the professional fund-raising industry, which Attorney General <PERSON> Lacy </PERSON> <PERSON> Thornburg </PERSON> called a `` multi-multimillion-dollar business,'' and on smaller charities that lack personnel to raise money. `` It's really a question of survival,'' said <PERSON> Errol </PERSON> <PERSON> Copilevitz </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> Kansas </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> attorney representing the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Federation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> the </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Blind </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> North </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Carolina </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> Optimist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Club </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> North </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Raleigh </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> N.C. </LOCATION>, which filed a lawsuit in 1985 challenging the law. About 75 charities have filed a friend-of-the-court brief opposing the statute. Many are represented by Independent Sector, an umbrella group including such organizations as the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cross </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cancer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Society </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Copilevitz </PERSON> said Tuesday. <PERSON> Thornburg </PERSON> said <LOCATION> Maine </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Connecticut </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Indiana </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION> had filed briefs in support of <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION>'s law. The most controversial provision requires professional fund-raisers to tell people they solicit what portion of the money will be spent on the charitable cause and how much will be used to cover expenses. `` The purpose of the law is to promote honesty through disclosure ... in very much the same way that banks and other institutions are required to tell, for example, what their interest rate is going to be,'' <PERSON> Thornburg </PERSON> said at a news conference. A study of fund-raising campaigns conducted in <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION> by professionals on behalf of charities between 1980 and 1984 showed that, on average, only 13 percent of gross receipts were returned to the charities, he said. The law presumes that whenever a professional group retains 35 percent or more of the gross receipts, it has reaped an excess profit, <PERSON> Thornburg </PERSON> said. The Solicitations Licensing Branch of the state <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Human </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Resources </ORGANIZATION> is empowered to increase the charity's share if it finds excessive profit for the fund-raisers. If allowed to stand, the law would bolster public confidence in charities, <PERSON> Thornburg </PERSON> said. `` We feel that if a donor knows in advance what portion of the funds are going back to the charity, then they will much more freely give.'' But <PERSON> Wayne </PERSON> <PERSON> Shevlin </PERSON>, president of the Raleigh chapter of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Federation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> the </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Blind </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> North </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Carolina </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, disagreed. `` If the first thing you have to say is how much is going for expenses, most people ... are going to hang up before you've had a chance to go through the spiel,'' <PERSON> Shevlin </PERSON> said. The law might drive out of business many small - and medium-sized charities, he said <PERSON> Copilevitz </PERSON> said most potential donors who want information on how the money will be spent ask for it. Many states _ including <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION> _ require professional and amateur fund-raising groups to provide such details on request, he said. Most states regulate fund solicitation, he said, but <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION>'s law goes far beyond any other. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Earl </PERSON> <PERSON> Britt </PERSON> struck down the measure as unconstitutional on May 14, 1986, a finding upheld by the 4th U.S. <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Richmond </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Va. </LOCATION>, on April 23, 1987.
