<HEAD>United States Sues to Close PLO's UN Mission</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 9 grafs to UPDATE with PLO reaction from U.N. and
Middle East. Picks up 6th graf pvs, `Former U.S...'.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOHN M. DOYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> sued Tuesday to force the <ORGANIZATION> Palestine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> to close its mission to the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION>, and the <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION> envoy defiantly responded that he could live on the street as a refugee. The government sought a federal court order barring the <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION>; <PERSON> Zehdi </PERSON> <PERSON> Labib </PERSON> <PERSON> Terzi </PERSON>, head of the <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION>'s observer mission; and five other <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION> officials or employees from continuing to operate the mission or any <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION> office in <LOCATION> Manhattan </LOCATION> or at any other location. The action is required under the 1987 Anti-Terrorism Act, which found the <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION> and its affiliates were a terrorist organization responsible for numerous violent incidents, including the murder of an <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> citizen during the hijacking of the cruise ship <PERSON> Achille </PERSON> <PERSON> Lauro </PERSON> in 1985. <PERSON> Terzi </PERSON> said he would have no comment on the <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION>'s possible legal response until he reads the complaint. `` The only asset we have in this country is the building we live in,'' he told reporters. `` Maybe they want me to live on the street, but this would not be the first time the Palestinians become refugees.'' He called efforts to freeze <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION> funds `` financial terrorism to strangle us.'' Earlier Tuesday, he had said, `` If they force me to leave, I will have to move to the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION>'' on international territory, out of reach of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> marshals. In 1973, <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION> Chief <PERSON> Yasser </PERSON> <PERSON> Arafat </PERSON> spent a night at the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> because he could not stay on <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> territory. In <LOCATION> Amman </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Jordan </LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION> foreign affairs spokesman <PERSON> Farouk </PERSON> <PERSON> Kaddoumi </PERSON> said Tuesday before the suit was filed,: `` We will keep the office open until the <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> police seal it off. Then we will go to the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> and live there. `` This will become a continuous headache to the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> administration,'' said <PERSON> Kaddoumi </PERSON>. Former <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Attorney General <PERSON> Ramsey </PERSON> <PERSON> Clark </PERSON>, the <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION>'s legal counsel, was not available for comment, his office said Tuesday. <PERSON> Clark </PERSON> did not immediately return messages left at the office. <PERSON> Clark </PERSON> has said, however, that he would seek to have the federal complaint dismissed on grounds that <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> courts lack jurisdiction in the matter involving an international treaty, in this instance between the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION>. Secretary-General <PERSON> Javier </PERSON> <PERSON> Perez </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Cuellar </PERSON> said he would have to wait until the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assembly </ORGANIZATION> adopts a resolution Wednesday before commenting on possible legal action. The 159-member <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assembly </ORGANIZATION> is to vote on a resolution supporting the <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION>'s right to operate and deploring <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> moves to shut the mission. The draft of the resolution calls on the secretary-general to take measures to allow the <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION> to carry out its official functions as a <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> invitee. In a separate action last September, the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> ordered the closing of the <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION>'s information office in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. That was before <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> passed the Anti-Terrorism Act, which President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> signed on Dec. 22. The law took effect Monday. Under the law, <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> determined that `` the <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION> and its affiliates are a terrorist organization and a threat to the interests of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, its allies and to international law and should not benefit from operating in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>.'' Earlier this month, Secretary of State <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> called the act `` one of the dumber things that the <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> has done lately.''
