<HEAD>Lawsuit Challenges Kentucky Federal Prison Unit for Women</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETE YOST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A lawsuit filed Tuesday alleges that an underground prison facility for women in <LOCATION> Lexington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ky. </LOCATION>, was designed specifically to house political activists and that inmates are subjected to inhumane treatment. Civil liberties groups filed the suit in <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> here against nine federal officials, including Attorney General <PERSON> Edwin </PERSON> <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON>. It seeks the immediate transfer of the inmates from the high-security facility to the general population of a federal women's prison. The <ORGANIZATION> Lexington </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Control </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Unit </ORGANIZATION> opened in November 1986, now houses five inmates and contains 16 basement cells constructed beneath the federal prison at <LOCATION> Lexington </LOCATION>. The <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bureau </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Prisons </ORGANIZATION> said last October it will phase out the unit, the only high-security unit for women in the federal prison system. `` The primary purpose for the creation of the unit was to confine prisoners whose political associations and affiliations were determined to pose a security threat,'' said the suit, alleging violation of the women's constitutional rights. `` All the women in the unit are suffering psychological and physical harm as a direct consequence of their isolated confinement in this underground segregation unit.'' A new medium - and high-security facility for women will be opened in June in <LOCATION> Marianna </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Fla. </LOCATION>, and the phaseout in <LOCATION> Lexington </LOCATION> will be completed shortly thereafter, said <ORGANIZATION> Bureau </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Prisons </ORGANIZATION> spokeswoman <PERSON> Kathryn </PERSON> <PERSON> Morse </PERSON> She declined to comment on the suit. The `` small basement facility'' has `` virtually no natural light'' and is illuminated 24 hours a day by fluorescent lights, said the suit, prepared by the National Prison Project of the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Civil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberties </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> and other attorneys. The women, the suit said, are monitored continuously by staff and video cameras, have no opportunity to participate in any of the activities available to the general prison population and are subjected to random strip searches. `` We believe the women's lives are in danger,'' said <PERSON> Susan </PERSON> <PERSON> Waysdorf </PERSON>, a spokeswoman for civil libertarians supporting the suit. `` They're beginning to experience signs of behavior modification, general disorientation, vision problems, loss of appetite, sleeplessnes.'' Among the inmates are <PERSON> Silvia </PERSON> <PERSON> Baraldini </PERSON>, convicted of racketeering and conspiracy in aiding a $ 1.6 million Brink's armored car heist in <LOCATION> Nyack </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.Y. </LOCATION>, that left a guard and two police officers dead Another inmate at <LOCATION> Lexington </LOCATION> is <PERSON> Susan </PERSON> <PERSON> Rosenberg </PERSON>, linked by law enforcement officers to the same bungled Brink's robbery <PERSON> Baraldini </PERSON>, serving a 43-year term, was transferred to <LOCATION> Lexington </LOCATION> after refusing to be interviewed by an <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> agent, the suit said. <PERSON> Rosenberg </PERSON>, serving a 58-year term for possession of weapons and explosives in connection with a 1985 police raid in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION>, was told that she would be confined to the unit until she changes her political beliefs, the suit alleges. When civil liberties groups began to expose <LOCATION> Lexington </LOCATION> as a `` political prison, federal officials hurriedly brought in two other women serving long sentences,'' a coalition of prominent civil libertarians said in a statement about the <LOCATION> Lexington </LOCATION> unit. One of the women brought in later, <PERSON> Sylvia </PERSON> <PERSON> Brown </PERSON>, serving a 27-year term for violating probation and escaping from a federal prison, was told that her release from the unit would depend on her lack of interaction with the political activists, the suit added.
