<HEAD>President Hits Practice of Gerrymandering</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MERRILL HARTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> harshly criticized the process of gerrymandering on Tuesday, complaining that Republicans are getting short-shrift treatment in the redrawing of congressional boundary lines.. `` I promise you this: As far as the president of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> is concerned, he's not going to be sitting around his garden sniffing roses in 1988,'' <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> told a group of Republican elected officials `` I'm going to be out on the campaign trail, telling the <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> people the truth about how the electoral process has been twisted and distorted,'' he said. <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> noted that reapportionment is scheduled in 1991, and said that `` having Republicans in state and local offices is the only hope we have of getting a fair deal. And that's what we're asking for - an end to the anti-democratic and un-American practice of gerrymandering congressional districts.'' Gerrymandering is the political process by which congressional district lines are redrawn in such a fashion as to benefit the party in power, whether Democratic or Republican. <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> said there were 367 congressional races contested by both major political parties in 1984. In these contests, the president said, Republicans won half a million votes more than Democrats, but the <ORGANIZATION> Democrats </ORGANIZATION> won 31 more seats. In his remarks, <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> said that `` gerrymandering has become a national scandal. The Democratic-controlled state legislatures have so rigged the electoral process that the will of the people can not be heard. They vote Republican but elect Democrats.'' The president maintained that `` the congressional map is a horror show of grotesque, contorted shapes. District lines jump back and forth over mountain ranges, cross large bodies of water, send out little tentacles to absorb special communities and ensure safe seats.'' <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> said that while <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Fahrenkopf </PERSON> has challenged Democratic gerrymandering in courts, `` ultimately, it's in the state legislatures that the battle for fairness must be won. And that's why Republicans are going to have to campaign with all our heart and soul for Republican state legislative candidates.'' <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> has steadfastly refused to take sides in the competition for the <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> nomination to succeed him, but has indicated he will campaign actively for the nominee. In his talk Tuesday, the president signaled that he would hit the campaign trail for an array of other causes, including his plan to speak out against the practice of gerrymandering.
