<HEAD>Civil Rights Bill Dominates Presidential Politics</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 6th graf pvs, bgng: Later, Dukakis, with 2 grafs to
UPDATE with Dukakis endorsements</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DAVID ESPO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 Democratic presidential contenders <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Simon </PERSON> and <PERSON> Albert </PERSON> <PERSON> Gore </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON> broke off campaigning Tuesday long enough to return to their <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> desks and vote to override President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s veto of a civil rights bill. Republican contender <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Dole </PERSON> stayed away and straddled the issue. With Saturday's <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION> caucuses looming as the next campaign test for the Democrats, Rep. <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Gephardt </PERSON> attacked <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> for a `` battlefield conversion'' on trade issues so important to the automotive industry. <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> aides retorted that the <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> governor has long been in favor of trade legislation, just not <PERSON> Gephardt </PERSON>'s proposal. <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> was in <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION>, too, turning his anti-drug crusade into a slap at the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration's Central American policy. `` The No. 1 threat to your lives today is drugs,'' he told a high school audience in <LOCATION> Lansing </LOCATION>. `` We're not threatened by 3 million Sandinistas and if so, ca n't be saved from them by 15,000 Contras.'' <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>, at the <ORGANIZATION> Massachusetts </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Statehouse </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION>, did change his stance on one issue, agreeing Tuesday to support a ban on furloughs for first-degree murderers after public pressure stemming from the release of a murderer who raped a <LOCATION> Maryland </LOCATION> woman. `` I try to listen, I try to learn,'' said <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>, who previously had called the furlough program for murderers essential for maintaining order in the state's prisons. Later, <PERSON> Duk