Senate </ORGANIZATION> voted 75-24 to overturn the president's veto, more than the two-thirds majority needed. The House also voted to override, 292-133. <PERSON> Simon </PERSON>, who is hoping to win the <LOCATION> Wisconsin </LOCATION> primary on April 5, said he sponsored the legislation in 1984 when it was first introduced. `` This is something that ought to appeal to the basic good instincts of every member of the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION>,'' he said. He said the issue involved is, `` Are we going to make real the dream of equality in the Constitution?'' <PERSON> Gore </PERSON> returned to <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> from <LOCATION> Harrisburg </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Pa. </LOCATION>, after collecting endorsements from several legislative leaders. He also met with Gov. <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Casey </PERSON>, but came away without an endorsement. <PERSON> Gore </PERSON> used the civil rights bill to attack <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, the prohibitive front-runner for the Republican nomination. <PERSON> Gore </PERSON> said <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, who announced Monday that he supported <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s veto of the measure, always sides with the president, `` even when the proposals are unfathomably dumb.'' `` When push comes to shove the vice president never disagrees with President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>,'' he said, adding that <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> did n't disagree with selling arms to <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> for hostages or in keeping <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> strongman <PERSON> Manuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> on the <ORGANIZATION> CIA </ORGANIZATION> payroll despite evidence of drug involvement. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s top campaign spokesman, <PERSON> Pete </PERSON> <PERSON> Teeley </PERSON>, dismissed suggestions that <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> would begin looking for an issue to disagree with <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> on, just to prove his independence. `` The fact is, six months ago everybody was writing that <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> had to disagree with the president in order to get the nomination. Everyone now sees that that was a myth,'' the spokesman said. Far, far behind in the Republican presidential race, <PERSON> Dole </PERSON> said he stayed in <LOCATION> Wisconsin </LOCATION> rather than return for the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> vote because `` I was n't needed.'' He said he was personally opposed to the president's veto. But asked on a <ORGANIZATION> Milwaukee </ORGANIZATION> radio station call-in program, he said, `` But if it were the deciding vote, I would side with the president.'' <PERSON> Dole </PERSON>, who was attacked by <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> earlier in the campaign for not taking firm stands on issues such as arms control and tax increases, placed a formal statement in the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> record that did not take a precise stand. In part it said, `` I have always supported legislation to overturn <LOCATION> Grove </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> to restore the broad civil rights coverage that existed prior to that case. ... At the same time, I recognize that -LRB- the bill -RRB- is not a perfect bill. I am not fully satisfied with it ... But the fact remains that the administration and its congressional allies had the opportunity to offer amendments and they were voted down.'' <PERSON> Dole </PERSON> was absent when the bill passed the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> originally in January. The legislation stems from a 1984 <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> ruling that says an organization receiving federal aid must follow anti-discrimination rules only for the program that receives the aid, and not for the entire organization or institution. The legislation would erase that distinction. <PERSON> Gephardt </PERSON>'s repeated jabs at <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> centered on the trade issue that is central to his own campaign. The <LOCATION> Missouri </LOCATION> congressman is the sponsor of legislation calling for retaliation against unfair trading practices. <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> opposes the <PERSON> Gephardt </PERSON> provision but declared a few days ago that he favors a different proposal backed by Sen. <PERSON> Don </PERSON> <PERSON> Riegle </PERSON> _ the <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION> senator who bestowed his endorsement on Monday. `` We're getting some battlefield conversions,'' <PERSON> Gephardt </PERSON> said.
