<HEAD>Nicaragua Says U.S. Plotting Invasion, Honduras Rejects U.N.
Observers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>VICTORIA GRAHAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION> told the <ORGANIZATION> Security </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> Tuesday the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> is plotting an invasion of that Central American nation. <LOCATION> Honduras </LOCATION>, meanwhile, rejected <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>'s call for <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> observers to visit the <LOCATION> Honduran-Nicaraguan </LOCATION> border, where there was fighting last week between soldiers of the leftist Sandinista government and U.S.-backed Contra rebels. Nicaraguan envoy <PERSON> Rita </PERSON> <PERSON> Delia </PERSON> <PERSON> Casco </PERSON>, said of the alleged <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> plot: `` The danger is not past. Indeed, it is growing. <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> plans to provide a <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Gulf </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Tonkin </LOCATION> incident to serve as a pretext for direct invasion and escalation of intimidation and threats.'' The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> sent 3,200 soldiers to <LOCATION> Honduras </LOCATION> last week at the request of the Honduran president, who accused Nicaraguan soldiers of penetrating Honduran territory while chasing the rebels. President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> said the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> move was to show support of <LOCATION> Honduras </LOCATION> and as a warning to <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>. Ms. <PERSON> Casco </PERSON>, director of the <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION>'s department of international organizations, said the situation `` points to the possibility of imminent imperialist military action on a broad scale.'' The Gulf of <LOCATION> Tonkin </LOCATION> incident occurred when <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> said North Vietnamese boats attacked two <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> destroyers in that waterway on Aug. 2, 1964. <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> passed the Gulf of <LOCATION> Tonkin </LOCATION> Resolution five days later and the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> began a military buildup in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> that led to major <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> involvement in the Vietnam War. A four-member <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> team was leaving Tuesday night to inspect the Nicaraguan side of the border with <LOCATION> Honduras </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Francois </PERSON> <PERSON> Giuliani </PERSON> told reporters that <LOCATION> Honduras </LOCATION> turned down a <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> offer to send observers to that country. Honduran Ambassador <PERSON> Jorge </PERSON> <PERSON> Ramon </PERSON> <PERSON> Hernandez </PERSON> told the council a <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> team was not necessary because the five <LOCATION> Central </LOCATION> <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> presidents, in a regional peace plan signed last August, had set up an executive committee to verify compliance with the accord. <PERSON> Hernandez </PERSON> said Sandinista troops invaded <LOCATION> Honduras </LOCATION> and his nation had the right to self-defense. `` Our military response has been limited so far and the international assistance we are asking for basically has a deterrent nature,'' he said. Honduran jets raided Nicaraguan positions last week in the <LOCATION> Bocay </LOCATION> region, which straddles the border between the two countries. No injuries were reported. On Sunday Honduran officials said the Nicaraguans were withdrawing and the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> troops would leave the country soon. Maj. <PERSON> Gary </PERSON> <PERSON> Hovatter </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> military spokesman in <LOCATION> Honduras </LOCATION>, said Tuesday that the American troops were conducting training exercises that could last from 10 to 14 days. <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. Ambassador <PERSON> Herbert </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Okun </PERSON>, the deputy permanent representative at the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION>, told the council that <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION> had launched a massive attack against the rebels, who have base camps in <LOCATION> Honduras </LOCATION>. `` The Sandinistas committed aggression against <LOCATION> Honduras </LOCATION>,'' he said. `` It was not the other way around.'' <PERSON> Okun </PERSON> said the <ORGANIZATION> Sandinistas </ORGANIZATION> retreated into <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION> without crushing the rebels because <LOCATION> Honduras </LOCATION> reacted forcefully and the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> demonstrated its determination to help <LOCATION> Honduras </LOCATION>. He said stability will return to <LOCATION> Central </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> only when <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION> complies with the regional peace plan and gives up `` its self-appointed right to subvert neighboring democracies and to launch premeditated attacks.''
