<HEAD>Mitterrand Has Had Wide Swings in Popularity</HEAD>
<HEAD>With France-Mitterrand</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFFREY ULBRICH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President <PERSON> Francois </PERSON> <PERSON> Mitterrand </PERSON>, who said Tuesday he will seek re-election next month, has managed in one seven-year term to be both the least and most popular chief executive in the 30 years of the Fifth Republic. <PERSON> Mitterrand </PERSON>, 71, led the leftist surge in May 1981 that ousted President <PERSON> Valery </PERSON> <PERSON> Giscard </PERSON> d'Estaing and the center-right alliance that had controlled the National Assembly for 23 years. The victory avenged Socialist <PERSON> Mitterrand </PERSON>'s defeats in the presidential elections of 1965 by <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Gaulle </PERSON> and 1974 by Giscard d'Estaing. After five years, French voters turned against the Socialists in the March 1986 parliamentary elections and returned control to the right _ creating what became known in <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> as `` cohabitation'' between a <ORGANIZATION> Socialist </ORGANIZATION> president and a conservative premier. Socialist policies had dragged <PERSON> Mitterrand </PERSON>'s popularity rating in public opinion polls as low as 27 percent, but under the unwanted marriage with the conservatives it soared again to a consistent 55 percent or more. The president pursued costly social programs after the Socialists gained power, but then reversed course, instituting austerity measures. Economic troubles brought his party to power, and caused its downfall five years later. After the Socialist defeat, <PERSON> Mitterrand </PERSON> eased into the role of elder statesman and held himself above the day-to-day battles of governing, commenting on issues only occasionally. He was born Oct. 26, 1916, in <LOCATION> Jarnac </LOCATION> in western <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> and attended universities in <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION>, earning degrees in law and letters. He was drafted into the army in 1938, and shot and captured during the <LOCATION> German </LOCATION> invasion in May 1940. <PERSON> Mitterrand </PERSON> escaped from a prison camp in <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, returned to <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> and created a Resistance network. His long feud with <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Gaulle </PERSON> began when <PERSON> Mitterrand </PERSON> refused to unite his Resistance group with <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Gaulle </PERSON>'s. It was in the Resistance days that he met <PERSON> Danielle </PERSON> <PERSON> Gouze </PERSON>, and they married in 1944, soon after <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> was liberated. He held several government posts, including interior and justice minister, during the chaotic postwar Fourth Republic. In the early 1970s he built the moribund <ORGANIZATION> Socialist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> into a major political force, but the Union of the Left he formed with the Communists fell apart in 1977. Not until the final days of the 1981 campaign did the two main leftist parties join forces again to defeat <PERSON> Giscard </PERSON> and oust the conservatives. <PERSON> Mitterrand </PERSON> shocked much of the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> by bringing Communists into his government, but the union lasted only three years. In 1984, the Communists pulled out in a dispute over economic policy.
</TEXT>
