<HEAD>Demonstrators, Counter-Demonstrators Face Off in Brawley Protests</HEAD>
<DATELINE>POUGHKEEPSIE, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Demonstrators protesting against the state grand jury in the <PERSON> Tawana </PERSON> <PERSON> Brawley </PERSON> case met counter-demonstrators for the first time on Tuesday, while at least two protesters scuffled with police. There were no arrests. Roughly 100 marchers led by the Rev. <PERSON> Al </PERSON> <PERSON> Sharpton </PERSON> and <PERSON> Brawley </PERSON> family lawyer <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Vernon </PERSON> <PERSON> Mason </PERSON> gathered outside chanting, `` Governor <PERSON> Cuomo </PERSON>, have n't you heard? This is not <LOCATION> Johannesburg </LOCATION>.'' That group was predominantly black. About 75 whites, who at first watched silently, began to shout back. `` Get Tawana to testify. We care too,'' some of them said. There was no scuffling between the two groups. Miss <PERSON> Brawley </PERSON>, a black 16-year-old, claims she was kidnapped and sexually assaulted by at least six white men during four days in November. <PERSON> Mason </PERSON> and another attorney, <PERSON> Alton </PERSON> <PERSON> Maddox </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, have advised their client not to cooperate with investigators. <PERSON> Sharpton </PERSON>'s group had promised to disrupt grand jury proceedings in the case. About 50 people from <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> joined as many local residents Tuesday morning for a march from the <LOCATION> Mid-Hudson </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bridge </LOCATION>. Later, members of <PERSON> Sharpton </PERSON>'s group attempted to push through a line of police who stood shoulder to shoulder in front of the doors of a state armory, where the grand jury has been meeting. At least two protesters struggled with police and were taken into a van, but were released and allowed to return. `` If it comes necessary for arrests to be made, we'll make them,'' Police Chief <PERSON> Stewart </PERSON> <PERSON> Bowles </PERSON> said. `` I'd rather not.'' Despite temperatures which hovered n