<HEAD>Brazilian Lawmakers Vote To Maintain Presidential System Of
Government</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSANA HAYWARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BRASILIA, Brazil (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Legislators voted Tuesday to keep the presidential system of federal government rather than switch to the parliamentary structure with a prime minister. President <PERSON> Jose </PERSON> <PERSON> Sarney </PERSON> called the action `` an important victory.'' <PERSON> Sarney </PERSON> said the 344-212 vote by the lawmakers rewriting the constitution was `` better for the country. <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> understood that.'' Later Tuesday, legislators approved a five-year term for presidents, rejecting by 305-223 a proposal to set the term at four years. The present presidential term is for six years, and <PERSON> Sarney </PERSON> was installed in office in 1985. <PERSON> Sarney </PERSON> had opposed a change to the parliamentary system, saying it would bring further economic and social chaos. Opponents argued that a parliamentary structure was an option for the nation that emerged in 1985 from 21 years of military rule. `` Presidentialism does n't exist and does n't work anywhere but the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>,'' said Sen. <PERSON> Affonso </PERSON> <PERSON> Arinos </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> Liberal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Front </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>. `` Military, authoritarian and dictatorial regimes emerged mostly because of presidentialism in <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION>.'' Leftist legislators opposed to <PERSON> Sarney </PERSON> backed the presidential system. But they also demanded direct presidential elections this year with <PERSON> Sarney </PERSON> stepping down in March 1989. <PERSON> Sarney </PERSON> said he would leave office in 1990. `` We did n't want a queen of <LOCATION> England </LOCATION>, we want elections, direct elections this year,'' said Rep. <PERSON> Jose </PERSON> <PERSON> Genoino </PERSON> of the leftist Workers' Party. The lawmakers have been meeting since February 1986 to rewrite the constitution. <PERSON> Sarney </PERSON>, 57, was elected vice pr