<HEAD>Is the United States Losing It Economically?</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also on financial wires.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOHN CUNNIFF</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Analyst</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Is the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> headed downhill, spending and taxing away its might and power? The thesis has arisen again, popularized by, among other events, an academic's best-selling book describing the rise to dominance and eventual deterioration of mighty nations through the ages. Several factors fit into the notion that assigns the latter role to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, including budget imbalances, big defense budgets, trade difficulties, slow growth and onerous taxes. Hastening the demise, according to neat but perhaps not correct analyses, is the Kontradief Theory, named for a <LOCATION> Russian </LOCATION> economist who many years ago claimed to have found a 50-year cycle of economic rise and fall. As viewed by the most gloomy of forecasters, the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> economy and much of the world's economy has entered a decline phase. The gloomy prospect seemed to fit a <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Erdman </PERSON> scenario, judging at least by the covers of his books. He is, you might know, author of `` The Crash of'79,'' `` The Last Days of <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'' and `` The Panic of'89.'' He laughed. No way, said the economist-author. While the country has troubles, he said, it is in the process of renewing itself, with lots of 30-year-olds with new ideas and energy now entering positions of power. `` Forget it,'' he said of the decline thesis. `` We've got the resources. We're dynamic. And we've got an infusion of the best of other countries through immigration.'' Why, he asked, should we listen to `` a dead Russian economist who made his observations before airplanes flew and before the development of service economies?'' But oddly, in the midst of one of the longest economic expansions ever, the notion of a dynamic <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> is sometimes lost, buried under concern for the worst aggregation of economic problems since the Great Depression of the 1930s. But dynamic <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> exists in the concepts of many scholars, among them <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Birch </PERSON>, who won a wide following for his research on small business while teaching at <ORGANIZATION> Massachusetts </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Technology </ORGANIZATION>. Small business, says <PERSON> Birch </PERSON>, represents renewal. It has become the `` big picture in <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>.'' Such businesses are innovating, exporting and creating jobs, he reminded a meeting of <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Small </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Business </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION>, an organization of independent business people that had it origins during the 1930s. Turbulence in the business community often gains attention, with takeovers and demises and problems at well-known companies. But underlying the surface turbulence, <PERSON> Birch </PERSON> suggests, is a strata of economic stability and growth. `` We turn over about 8 to 10 percent of our corporations and about 8 to 10 percent of our jobs in this country every year,'' said <PERSON> Birch </PERSON>, founder and president of <ORGANIZATION> Cognetics </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, an economic research firm in <LOCATION> Cambridge </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mass </LOCATION>. It means, he continued, that `` we turn over half of the American economy every five years _ half of all the companies and half of all the jobs change every five years.'' New business, he pointed out, find niches, create products and eventually compete and force larger companies to innovate or die. After tracking about 12 million businesses for close to two decades, `` what we began to realize was that there was this huge changing of the guard taking place,'' he said. `` The dinosaurs were dropping like rocks, and a whole bunch of little manufacturing companies were taking their place,'' he added. The turbulence that accompanies the process is economic decay and a waning of power to some viewers. To others, it is seen as renewal.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv PMs Wednesday March 23</NOTE>
