<HEAD>Argentines May Dislike the English but They Love Their Language</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RANDALL HACKLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>QUILMES, Argentina (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Argentines may have fallen out with the English over the <LOCATION> Falkland </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Islands </LOCATION>, but the upper-crust still likes the way they talk. That is evident on the quaintly <LOCATION> British </LOCATION> campus of <ORGANIZATION> St. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> George </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> College </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Quilmes </LOCATION> where Argentine children are still being sent to learn English with the proper accent and prepare to go on to <LOCATION> Cambridge </LOCATION> or <LOCATION> Oxford </LOCATION> For as much as $ 7,800 a year in tuition, the 330 boys and girls who attend the only British-style boarding school in <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION> are assured as fine an education as if they lived in <LOCATION> England </LOCATION>, said headmaster <PERSON> Graham </PERSON> <PERSON> Sims </PERSON>. Ninety instructors from <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> teach children aged 3 through 18 the fundamentals as well as computer programming, chemistry, advanced mathematics and English literature. English at <ORGANIZATION> St. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> George </ORGANIZATION>'s is the most common classroom language, although <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION>'s Education Ministry requires that bilingual schools teach some courses in Spanish. The school operates on British discipline. `` We are very strict and that means the boys and girls are not allowed any physical contact in school. Holding hands is out,'' <PERSON> Sims </PERSON> said in an interview. `` We've all got to lead disciplined lives. If not we become pretty hopeless human beings.'' <PERSON> St. </PERSON> <PERSON> George </PERSON>'s is in <LOCATION> Quilmes </LOCATION>, a city of 100,000 people 12 miles south of <LOCATION> Buenos </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Aires </LOCATION>. Once a popular residential area for the British who earlier this century built most of <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION>'s railways, it is most noted now for a brewery and the school Dotting the 62-acre campus are a chapel, rugby fields, gardens, two swimming pools, a horse-riding academy and dormitories where students are required to place their folded clothes and towels on racks in the bathrooms. The only inkling this is not <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> is when schoolchildren break into Spanish after class or when <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION>'s flag is raised each morning outside the administration building. `` It really is a little piece of <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION>,'' said <PERSON> Ray </PERSON> <PERSON> McKay </PERSON>, counselor at the <ORGANIZATION> Lincoln </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> in northern <LOCATION> Buenos </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Aires </LOCATION>, the only American school in <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION>. `` The student body is almost all Argentines from wealthy families who want their kids to speak English.'' <PERSON> Lincoln </PERSON> has 550 students, most of them children of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Embassy personnel, diplomats and businessmen in <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION>. Its schedule follows the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> system, with summer vacation from June through August. The English-style and Argentine schools have their vacation from January to March, the Southern Hemisphere summer. <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> George </LOCATION><LOCATION> 's </LOCATION>, founded in 1898, is considered one of the four top schools in <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION> for learning English. `` We offer a 24-hour-a-day education experience,'' said <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Stoyle </PERSON>, director of studies at <ORGANIZATION> St. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> George </ORGANIZATION>'s. Wakeup calls are at 6:30 a.m. and lights are out across campus by 10 p.m., which is the normal dining hour in <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION>. Student <PERSON> Magdalena </PERSON> <PERSON> Winter </PERSON>, 15, hopes someday to become a diplomat. `` Most people here believe we're getting a very good education so we learn to put up with things that maybe we do n't always like,'' she said. Three other top British-style schools, <PERSON> St. </PERSON> <PERSON> Andrew </PERSON>'s, <PERSON> St. </PERSON> <PERSON> Catherine </PERSON>'s and <LOCATION> Northlands </LOCATION>, are in the northern suburbs of <LOCATION> Buenos </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Aires </LOCATION>, but they do not offer boarding. <PERSON> St. </PERSON> <PERSON> Andrew </PERSON>'s is observing the 150th anniversary of its founding by Scottish settlers. With 1,900 students, <PERSON> St. </PERSON> <PERSON> Andrew </PERSON>'s is the largest of the British-tradition schools and oldest of the bilingual schools in <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION>. One of its headmasters, <PERSON> Watson </PERSON> <PERSON> Hutton </PERSON>, was credited with introducing soccer to <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION> at the turn of the century. `` Without him there'd be no -LRB- <ORGANIZATION> Diego </ORGANIZATION> -RRB- <PERSON> Maradona </PERSON>,'' said headmaster <PERSON> Kevan </PERSON> <PERSON> Prior </PERSON>, referring to the star of <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION>'s 1986 World Cup champions. <PERSON> St. </PERSON> <PERSON> Andrew </PERSON>'s has been coed since 1980. `` We have a particular ethos, particular spirit, something the parents of Argentine upper middle-class children choose,'' Prior said. Tuition is $ 1,600 to $ 2,400 a year. <ORGANIZATION> Northlands </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> near <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Andrew </LOCATION>'s is considered the top girls school in <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Headmistress </PERSON> <PERSON> Jehane </PERSON> <PERSON> Taylor </PERSON> takes pains to separate her school from anything British. `` This is an Argentine school with no funds from <LOCATION> England </LOCATION> that happens to teach English,'' she said. Sensitivities over anything British comes from problems regarding the <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> Falkland </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Islands </LOCATION> in the <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Atlantic </LOCATION>, off <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION>. The Argentines have claimed them since 1833 and here they are called the Malvinas. <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION> invaded the Falklands in April 1982 and were driven off by British forces three months later. `` During the Falklands these British-style schools got lots of phone treats, some of them obscene,'' said <PERSON> McKay </PERSON> of the American school. `` Some kids were pulled out by their parents and there were some classroom tiffs over the so-called imperialist British. `` So it's really kind of remarkable now that so many Argentines send their kids to these schools. I suppose it's kind of the snob thing to do.'' <PERSON> St. </PERSON> <PERSON> Catherine </PERSON>'s School for girls, like <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> George </LOCATION><LOCATION> 's </LOCATION>, offers the international baccalaurete program for its 1,100 students. The program allows students to enter colleges in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> at a second-year level or qualify for advanced study in <LOCATION> England </LOCATION>. A St. <PERSON> Catherine </PERSON>'s coordinator, <PERSON> Marie </PERSON> <PERSON> Philpotts </PERSON>, described the school as `` British to a certain extent.'' Tuition ranges from $ 1,050 to $ 1,600 a year compared to $ 1,000 to $ 2,000 a year at <LOCATION> Nortlands </LOCATION>. Mrs. <PERSON> Taylor </PERSON>, head of <LOCATION> Northlands </LOCATION>, said the tradition of Argentines sending their children to English-style schools goes back several generations. The school, founded by a British governess in 1920, gives 985 students `` an Anglo-Saxon point of view and a Latin point of view,'' giving students `` different ways of looking at knowledge,'' Mrs. <PERSON> Taylor </PERSON> said.
