<HEAD>Ouster Of Baptist Liaison With Jews Opens Old Wound</HEAD>
<HEAD>Laserphoto NY90</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE W. CORNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Religion Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The ouster by <ORGANIZATION> Southern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Baptist </ORGANIZATION> officials of a scholar for contending that God upholds his compact with Judaism opens an old wound in Christian-Jewish relations. It also pointed to a lingering, but increasingly repudiated, attitude in some church quarters. Historical church theories that God revoked his commitment to Jews, replacing it with a pact with Christianity, figured for centuries in anti-Jewish prejudice and persecution. However, many Protestant and <ORGANIZATION> Roman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> scholars have rejected that notion, as have some denominations. `` If God's covenant has been broken with the Jews, it's reasonable that other covenantal relationships might also be broken,'' says the Rev <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Sheridan </PERSON>, who was removed from his post. `` Therefore, we in the church would be an endangered species.'' However, <PERSON> Sheridan </PERSON> contends that God does n't go back on his promises, either to the mother religion, Judaism, or to the offspring of it, Christianity, and he cites <ORGANIZATION> Romans </ORGANIZATION> 11: `` Remember, it is not you -LRB- Christians -RRB- that support the root, but the root that supports you ... and so all <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> will be saved ... For the gifts and call of God are irrevocable.'' <PERSON> Sheridan </PERSON>, 46, of <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.J. </LOCATION>, was dismissed after 13 years of working with Jews as regional director of the interfaith witness department of the <ORGANIZATION> Southern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Baptist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Home </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mission </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION>. `` My point is that the covenant with the Jews was not abrogated,'' he said in an interview, maintaining that they are saved through God's mercy, just as are Christians, but without accepting <PERSON> Jesus </PERSON>. Christians, unlike Jews, needed <PERSON> Jesus </PERSON> to draw them to the one, same God, <PERSON> Sheridan </PERSON> said. A letter notified him he was relieved from his assignment Jan. 31 because of his `` theological position relative to evangelizing the Jewish people'' _ something he opposed as unnecessary. It also offends Jews, implying their faith is useless. <PERSON> Sheridan </PERSON>'s ouster `` strikes me like the Middle Ages,'' commented Rabbi <PERSON> Leon </PERSON> <PERSON> Klenicki </PERSON>, director of the interfaith department of the Anti-Defamation League of B'nai B'rith. In <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION>, the mission board's president, the Rev. <PERSON> Larry </PERSON> <PERSON> Lewis </PERSON>, said <PERSON> Sheridan </PERSON>'s view was n't acceptable. The board lately came under fundamentalist sway, as have most of the 14.6-million-member denomination's agencies. <PERSON> Lewis </PERSON> said, `` The Bible teaches there is no other way to salvation except through a personal faith in Jesus Christ.'' <PERSON> Sheridan </PERSON>, with degrees from <ORGANIZATION> Southern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Baptist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Theological </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Seminary </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Louisville </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ky. </LOCATION>, and <ORGANIZATION> Princeton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Theological </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Seminary </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Princeton </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.J. </LOCATION>, linked his ouster to the heresy of Marcionism. `` That's what this thing borders on,'' he said. `` The Marcion heresy was that the God in Jewish Scripture -LRB- the Old Testament -RRB- is different than the God of the gospels -LRB- New Testament -RRB-.'' <PERSON> Marcion </PERSON>, a second-century preacher whose views were condemned by the church, rejected the Old Testament, which historic Christianity accepts along with the New Testament. `` I believe in Jesus Christ,'' <PERSON> Sheridan </PERSON> said, `` that <PERSON> Jesus </PERSON> <PERSON> Christ </PERSON> is God, but for me to believe that the God of <PERSON> Jesus </PERSON> <PERSON> Christ </PERSON> is not the God of Jews rooted in their Scripture is the heresy of two different gods.'' <PERSON> Sheridan </PERSON> said that after a tense meeting with officials last year, he wrote a letter at their request outlining his views, and his dismissal followed. In it, he said in part: `` The Scriptures provide a chronicle of how God has taken the initiative in concrete historical ways to save God's people ... `` In the Bible the term ` savior' properly is ascribed to God ... In the <ORGANIZATION> Christian </ORGANIZATION> gospel, God comes to the world in the person of a man, <PERSON> Jesus </PERSON> ... In the New Testament, the title ` savior' is applied sometimes to God and sometimes to <PERSON> Jesus </PERSON> <PERSON> Christ </PERSON>,'' emphasizing that he bears `` the authority of God.'' `` This established that <PERSON> Jesus </PERSON> <PERSON> Christ </PERSON> is the revelation of God who, as the Hebrew Scriptures teach, is the one and only ` savior' of the people of God To distinguish between the God revealed in the Hebrew Scriptures and the God revealed in <PERSON> Jesus </PERSON> <PERSON> Christ </PERSON> is, for Christians, a heresy ... `` God saves his people, the entire Bible asserts. This salvation is not brought brought about by the goodness of the people, but by the merciful initiative of God. <PERSON> Jesus </PERSON> <PERSON> Christ </PERSON> provides the way for the nations to be engrafted into the people of God ... `` I find in the entire Christian Bible no hint that God cancels out lovingkindness freely dispensed or promised. In fact, we find the gifts and the call of God are irrevocable. `` For this biblical reason ... I believe that the Jews of today, as ever, receive salvation through their having been chosen by God in covenant with <PERSON> Abraham </PERSON>, <PERSON> Moses </PERSON> and the prophets. `` The election of the church is prefigured in this election of <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>, and if the election of one is subjection to cancellation, so, too, is the election of the other.''
</TEXT>
