<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>In the Groove: Record Reviews</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVEN WINE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 `` Savage'' -LRB- RCA -RRB- _ Eurythmics On `` <PERSON> Savage </PERSON>,'' the <ORGANIZATION> Eurythmics </ORGANIZATION> are misanthropic, caustic and a bit paranoid. They're strong on attitude but weak on delivery. The record emphasizes a big beat, mostly via programmed drums and bass lines that make for mechanical music. Worst is the opening cut, `` Beethoven -LRB- I Love to Listen to -RRB-.'' Add singer <PERSON> Annie </PERSON> <PERSON> Lennox </PERSON>'s dry delivery, and the resulting sounds have both the pulse and personality of a locomotive Lost in the thundering shuffle are the lyrics by <PERSON> Lennox </PERSON> and <PERSON> Dave </PERSON> <PERSON> Stewart </PERSON>, which positively snarl on paper. <PERSON> Lennox </PERSON> spends much of the record telling us that love is cheap and men merit no respect. `` Love is a temple, love is a shrine, buy some love at the five and dime,'' she sings on the best song, `` You Have Placed a Chill In My Heart.'' Oddly, <PERSON> Lennox </PERSON> and <PERSON> Stewart </PERSON> ease up on the syncopation on the last two cuts of the record, which closes with the upbeat `` Brand New Day.'' After 11 songs filled with cynicism, it's hard to believe the optimistic message is sincere. But maybe it presages more subtlety and finesse on their next record.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 `` Live _ The Road'' -LRB- <ORGANIZATION> MCA </ORGANIZATION> -RRB- _ The Kinks It's bad news when the best thing on an album titled `` Live _ The Road'' is a studio cut. But that's the case with the Kinks' latest record It opens with a new composition, <PERSON> Ray </PERSON> <PERSON> Davies </PERSON>' engaging, autobiographical `` The <LOCATION> Road </LOCATION>.'' `` There's gas in my tank, and I've still got a ways to go,'' the veteran rocker sings On the rest of the album, recorded in concert last summer, the Kinks play with the verve of a driver intent on getting good mileage. There are stirring moments in the 50 minutes of music: `` Come Dancing,'' sparked by <PERSON> Dave </PERSON> <PERSON> Davies </PERSON>' fluid guitar work; the provocative `` Art Lover,'' which only <PERSON> Ray </PERSON> <PERSON> Davies </PERSON> could have written; and the rocking `` Destroyer'' and `` Around the Dial.'' But `` It,'' the album's other new song, and `` Cliches of the World'' are too long and too ambitious. The other performances are routine, with riffs and tempos that belong in a heavy metal cutout bin. `` Live _ The Road'' is not a bad set, and the Kinks deserve credit for reprising some of their lesser-known material from the 1980s -LRB- at one point they tease the audience with a false start of `` Lola'' -RRB-. But from such a well-respected band, it's a disappointment.
</TEXT>
