<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>Star Watch: George Burns _ Forever Young</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT MACY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LAS VEGAS, Nev. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Burns </PERSON> paced the darkened backstage of the Caesars Palace showroom, hummed softly and flicked ashes from his ever-present cigar. `` I'm just making sure I can still walk,'' he dead-panned to a couple sitting in the wings. Moments later, as the orchestra struck up `` Ai n't Misbehavin','' <PERSON> Burns </PERSON> sauntered on stage to a standing ovation, a rarity for the opening of a Las Vegas show. He would receive two more before exiting an hour later _ a sign of the respect audiences hold for this man who was a vaudeville star in their grandparents' time. At 92, <PERSON> Burns </PERSON> shows no signs of slowing down. He's a regular at the Palace on the <LOCATION> Las </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Vegas </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Strip </LOCATION> and at other Caesars properties in <LOCATION> Lake </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Tahoe </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Nev. </LOCATION>, and <LOCATION> Atlantic </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.J. </LOCATION> His pace would satisfy, and slow, most performers half his age. However, <PERSON> Burns </PERSON> has just completed a new movie, `` 18 Again,'' which opens April 9. And he's working on a new book about the one true love of his life, <PERSON> Gracie </PERSON> <PERSON> Allen </PERSON>, his stage partner, confidante, best friend and wife for 38 years until her death in 1964. The book, `` Gracie: A Love Story,'' is due out in October. <PERSON> Irving </PERSON> <PERSON> Fein </PERSON>, <PERSON> Burns </PERSON>' longtime friend and manager for 14 years, says the book will be `` a loving, warm story about <PERSON> Gracie </PERSON> <PERSON> Allen </PERSON> that has never before been told. `` <PERSON> George </PERSON> will always have this special love for <LOCATION> Gracie </LOCATION>,'' <ORGANIZATION> Fein </ORGANIZATION> said during <PERSON> Burns </PERSON>' recent appearance here. `` He goes to her grave -LRB- in <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> -RRB- once a month. He talks to her, tells her everything he's doing. He'll say ` I just got back from <LOCATION> Vegas </LOCATION>. We did great.' Or ` I just finished a movie. It's about me and my grandson and how we switch places.' `` He'll spend a lot of time just standing there talking to her, letting her know what's happening in his life. She's still a very special part of his life.'' <PERSON> Burns </PERSON> gives his long-time mate the credit for his success. `` If it was n't for <LOCATION> Gracie </LOCATION>, I would n't be here,'' he said, puffing on a cigar in his dressing room before a recent Caesars show. He crossed the room to a bar, poured a cup of coffee, then settled in a chair next to the piano. <PERSON> Morty </PERSON> <PERSON> Jacobs </PERSON>, his pianist of 18 years, began picking out tunes <PERSON> Burns </PERSON> sang as a teen-ager three-quarters of a century ago. `` What key is that?'' <PERSON> Burns </PERSON> inquired of <PERSON> Jacobs </PERSON>. `` Take it half a tone lower.'' `` We'll do some lovin', then you'll ask for more,'' <PERSON> Burns </PERSON> sang, tapping shiny patent leather shoes on the dressing room floor. Onstage, opening act <PERSON> Susan </PERSON> <PERSON> Anton </PERSON> was belting out a raucous version of `` Old Time Rock and Roll,'' a signal for <PERSON> Burns </PERSON> to exit his dressing room. He walked briskly back and forth in the darkened area, stopping to talk to workers or softly humming some of the songs he would sing. Miss <PERSON> Anton </PERSON> dedicated her final song, `` Forever Young,'' to <PERSON> Burns </PERSON>. He took a long drag on his cigar, then entered to the standing ovation. `` In 1981 I played God,'' he said, referring to the first of three movies in which he played the deity. `` I was a nervous wreck. We're both the same age, but we grew up in different neighborhoods. `` Why should n't I play God? Anything I do at my age is a miracle. `` I've written six books. That's pretty good for a guy who only read two.'' His formula for acting? `` If the director wants me to cry, I think of my sex life. `` If the director wants me to laugh, I think of my sex life.'' About that sex life? `` I'd go out with women my age, but there are no women my age.'' Another put-down: `` There is n't anything I ca n't do now that I could n't do when I was 18 _ which shows you how pathetic I was at 18.'' <PERSON> Burns </PERSON> smokes 15 to 20 cigars and drinks several martinis a day. What do his doctors think of that? `` They're all dead.'' <PERSON> Burns </PERSON> began in show business at the age of 8, quitting school to form a group of child singers known as the Peewee Quartet. Born <PERSON> Nathan </PERSON> <PERSON> Birnbaum </PERSON> to a poor family on <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> Lower </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Side </LOCATION>, he had only to look to his 11 brothers and sisters for his own ensemble. He bounced around the vaudeville circuit until he was 27. `` Then people discovered I had a talent _ a big talent. I was married to her for 38 years. `` <LOCATION> Gracie </LOCATION> did n't tell a joke, she explained it,'' <PERSON> Burns </PERSON> recalled of nearly four decades as straight man for the zany comedian. <PERSON> Burns </PERSON> admits he was devastated _ personally and professionally _ by <PERSON> Miss </PERSON> <PERSON> Allen </PERSON>'s death in 1964. A decade later, in August 1974, <PERSON> Burns </PERSON> underwent a triple heart bypass. At age 78, he was the oldest bypass patient in history at that time. Four months after his surgery, <PERSON> Burns </PERSON>' longtime friend, <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> Benny </PERSON> died. <PERSON> Benny </PERSON> had been scheduled to star in the movie `` The Sunshine Boys.'' <PERSON> Burns </PERSON> was tabbed to take his place, won an Academy Award for best supporting actor, and was on his way to his second time around.
</TEXT>
