<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>Music Makers: Thorogood and Co. Bring Bar Band to Arena Rock</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY McSHANE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 In the past decade, <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Thorogood </PERSON> has gone from playing hole-in-the-wall saloons to headlining stadiums. But the whiskey-voiced rocker figures his career holds a few more roadhouse bars before he hits the retirement home. `` I ca n't wait until I become a has-been _ a has-been that never was, actually,'' he said with a cackle. `` I ca n't wait till that happens, because I know I can make a living playing bars. And have a lot of fun _ a great time.'' Which is, he says, what his band The Destroyers are having now on their national tour _ although <PERSON> Thorogood </PERSON> makes no bones about saying they'd rather play <ORGANIZATION> Stubb </ORGANIZATION>'s Barbecue, a small <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> blues bar, than Madison Square Garden. `` We started out, and still are, a bar band,'' said <PERSON> Thorogood </PERSON>, whose career has kept alive the sound of Muddy Waters, <PERSON> Howlin </PERSON>' <PERSON> Wolf </PERSON> and other blues legends. `` It's just that the bars are a little bigger these days.'' <PERSON> Thorogood </PERSON> and company are to blame for that. Since 1977, they've cranked out a series of successful albums and singles, starting with a remake of <PERSON> Hank </PERSON> <PERSON> Williams </PERSON>' `` Who Do You Love? on their debut album and stretching to the current LP `` Born to Be Bad.'' Despite his success, <PERSON> Thorogood </PERSON> has not catered to Top 40 radio, studiously avoided studio tricks and stayed about as far from the mainstream as any contemporary band can. `` Even if I tried, I'm not going to be able to get out of this style of playing,'' <PERSON> Thorogood </PERSON> said during a <LOCATION> Manhattan </LOCATION> stop in the tour. `` There might be a different hook here or there, but basically it's going to be your two -, three-chord rock or your slow, tough-guy blues `` I do n't want to change that, and I could n't if I wanted o, because I have tried _ I have sat down and tried to play other styles of stuff, and it was a disaster.'' With that in mind, <PERSON> Thorogood </PERSON> and band included some classic covers on the new album: <PERSON> Elmore </PERSON> <PERSON> James </PERSON>' `` Shake Your Money Maker,'' <PERSON> Chuck </PERSON> <PERSON> Berry </PERSON>'s `` You Ca n't Catch Me'' and <PERSON> Hank </PERSON> <PERSON> Snow </PERSON>'s `` I'm Movin' On. <PERSON> Thorogood </PERSON> also wrote several songs in the same vein for `` Born to Be Bad'' _ songs which, he stressed, carry no deeper message than `` let's all have a good time.'' `` I figure, I'm not operating on anybody's skull here. It's not brain surgery, man,'' said <PERSON> Thorogood </PERSON>. `` It's just two chords. And people are supposed to dance to it and laugh at it, and two hours later forget about it. That's what entertainment is.'' <PERSON> Thorogood </PERSON> was introduced to the blues scene in his native <LOCATION> Delaware </LOCATION>, an area he quickly admits was no roots-rock hotbed. `` I was so foolish staying in the <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION> area, because it's not a blues area,'' he said. `` If I had my wits about me, I would have gone to <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION> or <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>, where people know this sound their whole lives.'' But no matter where he he grew up, <PERSON> Thorogood </PERSON> believes it was inevitable he'd end up listening to Muddy Waters and <PERSON> Chuck </PERSON> <PERSON> Berry </PERSON>. `` I think the things you're supposed to hear in your life will come to you. You do n't go finding them; they come to you,'' he said. `` So it just came to me a little later.'' Once <PERSON> Thorogood </PERSON> heard the music, he began taking it to audiences with the zeal of a Bible Belt preacher delivering the good word. The band is constantly on the road: In 1981, they went on a `` 50-50 Tour'' in which they played in all 50 states on 50 consecutive dates. And while they have moved up from bars to arenas, <PERSON> Thorogood </PERSON> figures that sooner or later he'll be back on the roadhouse circuit playing for barroom crowds, enjoying his golden years with a cold beer and some hot licks. `` I always thought, wow, would n't it be great if I did ` Bad to the Bone' and I was 60, and I had on a gut on me like -LRB- <PERSON> Jackie </PERSON> -RRB- <PERSON> Gleason </PERSON>, and I walked out there with a T-shirt that said something like, ` Sex Machine.'''
</TEXT>
