<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>Nashville Sound: Fiddler Vassar Clements And `Hillbilly Jazz'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOE EDWARDS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Fiddler </PERSON> <PERSON> Vassar </PERSON> <PERSON> Clements </PERSON> has played country music, jazz, rock' n' roll and classical for groups as diverse as the Grateful Dead and the <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Pops </LOCATION>. And for the past two decades, he's recorded in the top studios with his instrument. It's been a romance of sound separated only by the styles he performs. `` When the rhythm is good, I can play it,'' <PERSON> Clements </PERSON> says. The 59-year-old artist has just released an album with the intriguing title `` New Hillbilly Jazz.'' The name signifies a sound as versatile as the man who plays it. `` It's heavy rhythm, solid, dynamic,'' he said in his soft Southern voice that contrasts the exuberance of his playing. `` But it's not fidgety music. It's smooth, danceable.'' This marks his 20th year in <LOCATION> Nashville </LOCATION> where he's added luster to the city's country style after relocating from <LOCATION> Kissimmee </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Fla. </LOCATION> `` People ask me what kind of music I'm playing, and I say I do n't know,'' he said. `` It's just happy, moving music.'' Along the way, he played with rock veterans the Grateful Dead on their `` Wake of the Flood'' album and toured with them when they were known as Old and In the Way. It was a departure from the country music he grew up playing when he and his cousins formed a band. `` It was a challenge and I loved that,'' he recalled about his days with the Dead. `` It's exciting to take a chance.'' He also played with the <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Pops </LOCATION>, joining his close friend <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Hartford </PERSON> when <LOCATION> Hartford </LOCATION> was a guest artist in a Pops concert. In addition, he recorded with the <ORGANIZATION> Monkees </ORGANIZATION>. That was by coincidence. He was working on a recording session when someone asked him if he wanted to stay and play on another one. `` I did n't know until later it was the <ORGANIZATION> Monkees </ORGANIZATION>,'' he said. He's had no problem adjusting to the various styles, even on short notice such as the <ORGANIZATION> Monkees </ORGANIZATION>' session. `` You just go in and do it. After so many years, no tunes change much. I've never had a problem with that.'' <PERSON> Clements </PERSON> taught himself to play at age 7 and has no formal training. The first song he learned was `` There's an Old Spinning Wheel in the Parlor.'' `` It took forever,'' he said. `` It was God's gift, something born in me,'' he said about his talent. `` I was too dumb to learn it any other way. I listened to the -LRB- Grand Ole -RRB- Opry some. I'd pick it up one note at a time. I was young, with plenty of time and I did n't give up. You'd come home from school, do your lessons and that's it. No other distractions. `` I do n't read music. I play what I hear.'' But he understands how helpful it is for youngsters to be grounded in classical music and formal training. `` It should help them,'' <PERSON> Clements </PERSON> said. He was employed at the Kennedy Space Center in <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> for a year in the mid-1960s, working on plumbing. At various times, he also worked in a <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION> paper mill, was a switchman for <ORGANIZATION> Atlantic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Railroad </ORGANIZATION>, sold insurance and had a potato chip franchise. But music was always part of his life. `` I'd always play. Square dances, anything,'' he said. All the performing carried him to <LOCATION> Nashville </LOCATION> where one of his first breaks was being featured on the album `` Will the Circle Be Unbroken'' by the Nitty Gritty Dirt Band. He then became heavily in demand for recording sessions of all types. This year, he was nominated for a Grammy Award with French jazz violinist <PERSON> Stephane </PERSON> <PERSON> Grappelli </PERSON> for their `` Together at Last.'' `` It was a truly great time,'' he said about working with <PERSON> Grappelli </PERSON>. `` It was a challenge, but it came easy. We felt alike on a lot of things.'' <PERSON> Clements </PERSON> wo n't say that he's getting better at playing, but prefers to say that it just comes easier. `` If I quit improving, I'd have to quit. It would be work and there'd be no sense staying in a rut and not learning anything. I'd hate to play the same way all the time It would become mechanical.'' <PERSON> Clements </PERSON>, who owns three fiddles and still practices some, has no favorite song. `` When things go right, I enjoy playing all of them, anything that comes up.'' Similarly, he does n't mind if his instrument is called a fiddle or a violin. `` I say fiddle, but if someone says violin it does n't matter.''
</TEXT>
