found Eastern in contempt on March 10 for violating an order he had issued July 2. That order had forbidden the company from changing working conditions of the 12,000 mechanics and other ground workers represented by the machinists. Eastern, owned by <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, announced Feb. 5 that it would sell its shuttle to a newly created <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> subsidiary for $ 225 million. The shuttle flies between <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Lorenzo </PERSON>, chief executive of <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION>, has argued that financially ailing <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> needed the cash. But union leaders have insisted the move was aimed at stripping labor of power at the carrier by transferring thousands of workers to another corporate entity within <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> Air. The machinists' union had asked <PERSON> Pratt </PERSON> to force a court appearance by <PERSON> Lorenzo </PERSON> to discuss the shuttle deal. But in his ruling Monday, <PERSON> Pratt </PERSON> said <PERSON> Lorenzo </PERSON> could send another corporate representative. The union had also asked <PERSON> Pratt </PERSON> to fine Eastern $ 20,000 daily for future violations of the judge's orders. The judge instead ruled the airline would face $ 10,000-a-day fines for violations committed after April 5. <PERSON> Pratt </PERSON> did not grant a union request that the airline restore the jobs of all Eastern employees who quit because of the announcement that the shuttle would be sold. In 1986, <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION>, also the corporate parent of <ORGANIZATION> Continental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION>, took over <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION>, a large carrier that lost $ 182 million last year. Since that time, <PERSON> Lorenzo </PERSON> has sought wage concessions from unions and has tried selling several of <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION>'s most profitable assets to other <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> subsidiaries that he also controls. Unions representing <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> employees have waged well-publicized fights to thwart him.
