^Durable Goods Orders Fell Sharply Last Month</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 Orders to <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> factories for `` big ticket'' durable goods continued to fall sharply in February, the government reported today. The <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said orders for durable goods, items expected to last at least three years, totaled a seasonally adjusted $ 111.4 billion last month, a 1.8 percent decline which was identical to the drop in January. It was the first time since the spring of 1986 that durable goods orders had been down for two consecutive months. The back-to-back drops surprised analysts, who had been predicting that orders would turn up again in February following a January decline which was blamed on volatility in the aircraft sector. Separately, the <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said Monday the federal government ran a $ 23.9 billion budget deficit in February, following a rare surplus the previous month. The $ 16.1 billion January surplus occurred because that month's Social Security checks were mailed early and counted in the December spending figures For the first five months of the current budget year, the government has run up a deficit of $ 89.7 billion, 4.9 percent lower than the deficit incurred in the same period a year ago, according to <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> calculations. On Wall Street, analysts blamed inflation fears and lingering post-crash anxiety for the broad decline in stock prices. The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials fell sharply at the opening and remaining lower throughout the session, closing down 20.23 points at 2,067.14. Broader market indices also fell. On the bond market, analysts said prices slipped and interest rates edged up in light trading that reflected continued uncertainty about the outlook for inflation and the economy. The <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION>'s closely watched 30-year bond fell \ point, or about $ 2.50 for every $ 1,000 in face value, as its yield rose to 8.70 percent from 8.67 percent late Friday. Foreign exchange trading also was quiet, with the dollar responding to declines in stocks and bonds by dropping against all major currencies except the Canadian dollar. Oil futures prices rallied, with crude piercing the $ 17-a-barrel level before sliding back in late trading following a statement by Saudi King Fahd on prices and production. Fahd suggested that cheating on production quotas and prices by some members of the 13-nation <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Petroleum </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exporting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Countries </ORGANIZATION> encouraged further weakness in prices. That punctured the rally on the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, where contracts for April delivery of <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> Intemediate, the benchmark <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> crude oil, closed at $ 16.49 per barrel, down 9 cents from Friday. The April contract had been up as much as 45 cents during the day.
