<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Stocks rose early today after stumbling in the previous session over inflation fears and lingering anxiety stemming from the crash five months ago. The Dow Jones average of 30 industrial stocks rose 5.31 points to 2,072.45 by 10 a.m. on Wall Street. Among broader market indicators, the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>'s composite index of all listed issues rose 0.33 to 151.80 The <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>'s market value index rose 0.28 to 298.46. Gaining issues outnumbered losers by more than 5-to-3 on the <ORGANIZATION> NYSE </ORGANIZATION>, with 605 up, 364 down and 477 unchanged. Volume totaled 21.1 million shares after the first half hour. On Monday the Dow Jones industrials dropped 20.23 to 2,067.14. Losing issues outnumbered gainers by about 2-to-1 on the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, with 1,042 down, 502 up and 444 unchanged. <ORGANIZATION> Big </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> volume totaled 128.83 million shares against 245.75 million shares the previous session. It was the lowest level since a 111.58 million-share day Dec. 29.
