million, edits to conform; picks up 8th graf pvs: The non-public
...</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Merv </PERSON> <PERSON> Griffin </PERSON> today boosted his bid to acquire <ORGANIZATION> Resorts </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> to $ 295 million while also waging a court fight to help him win control of the hotel-casino company. <ORGANIZATION> Griffin </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, the entertainer-businessman's private investment company, said in a statement today that it decided to increase its initial bid of $ 225 million, or $ 35-a-share, after reviewing `` appraisals regarding the value of Resorts.'' Based on 6.43 million Class A and Class B shares outstanding, <PERSON> Griffin </PERSON>'s latest bid for both classes of stock is valued at about $ 46 a share. Separately, <PERSON> Griffin </PERSON> said Monday it filed a $ 500 million federal lawsuit in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> against real estate developer <PERSON> Donald </PERSON> <PERSON> Trump </PERSON> and Resorts' directors, claiming breach of fiduciary duty to shareholders, among other things. <PERSON> Trump </PERSON>, who has voting control of Resorts and is the company's chairman, sued <PERSON> Griffin </PERSON> last week, accusing the entertainer of interfering with <PERSON> Trump </PERSON>'s contractual agreement to acquire complete control over Resorts Since making its initial offer Thursday, the <ORGANIZATION> Griffin </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> has indicated it may raise the price if justified by non-public information from Resorts, a hotel-casino concern with operations in <LOCATION> Atlantic </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.J. </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Bahamas </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Griffin </PERSON> said <PERSON> Trump </PERSON> made that information available late last week. <PERSON> Trump </PERSON>, who is making his own $ 22-per-share bid for the Resorts stock he does n't already own, said he wo n't boost his offer and has maintained that he will not sell his shares to <PERSON> Griffin </PERSON>. Resorts' board said it decided not to pursue <PERSON> Griffin </PERSON>'s initial bid because, in light of <PERSON> Trump </PERSON>'s rejection, the issue was moot. <PERSON> Griffin </PERSON> said in a statement today that he would not approve any deal between Resorts and <PERSON> Trump </PERSON> `` unless class A shareholders receive a premium over my prior $ 35-a-share offer.'' The non-public documents were contained in a <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> filing <PERSON> Trump </PERSON> made on Friday to supplement his tender offer for Resorts. <PERSON> Trump </PERSON>'s tender offer, which had been scheduled to expire Monday, was extended until 12:01 a.m. EST on April 1. <PERSON> Griffin </PERSON>'s president, <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Nigris </PERSON>, said the documents included a $ 1.3 billion appraisal of Resorts' properties, including a when-completed value for its luxurious but troubled Taj Mahal hotel-casino in <LOCATION> Atlantic </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>. The appraiser further said it was prepared to support a bank mortgage loan of $ 550 million guaranteed by Resorts, <PERSON> Nigris </PERSON> said. `` Based on those numbers, we may be able to sweeten our $ 225 million bid,'' <PERSON> Nigris </PERSON> said Monday. The $ 550 million mortgage is the amount <PERSON> Trump </PERSON> has said will be needed to complete the Taj Mahal. When Resorts began work on the project in 1984, it estimated the total price at $ 535 million. That figure has since soared to $ 938.5 million based on <PERSON> Trump </PERSON>'s estimates <PERSON> Trump </PERSON> became involved with Resorts last year when the company ran into financial difficulties with the proposed 42-floor, 1,250-room Taj Mahal. He bought up most of Resorts' Class B common stock, which carries 100 votes per share, thus giving him 88 percent voting control. He also pledged to help arrange financing for the costly Taj Mahal project and, in exchange, was granted a five-year operating contract for Resorts properties valued at about $ 100 million. Resorts has 752,000 Class B shares. It has 5.7 million Class A shares that carry one vote each.
