<HEAD>Griffin vs. Trump: Courtly Crooner Battles Brash Builder Over
Resorts</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: INSERTS 1 graf after 3rd graf to UPDATE with Griffin
increasing bid, picks up 4th graf pvs: Both contestants ...</NOTE>
<HEAD>Laserphotos</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROGER GILLOTT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 In this corner: affable, courtly and somewhat portly <PERSON> Mervyn </PERSON> <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> Griffin </PERSON>, the singer and talk show host who in recent years has emerged as a wily and successful businessman. And in the far corner: brash <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> real estate developer <PERSON> Donald </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Trump </PERSON>, best known for building designer-label skyscrapers, owning casinos and having more than a modest dose of braggadocio. Late last week, <PERSON> Griffin </PERSON> and <PERSON> Trump </PERSON> squared off over control of <ORGANIZATION> Resorts </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, the New Jersey-based hotel-casino concern that <PERSON> Trump </PERSON> has been offering to acquire for $ 22 per share, or about to acquire. <PERSON> Griffin </PERSON> last week offered $ 35 per share, or $ 225 million for the <LOCATION> Atlantic </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City-based </LOCATION> company, which also has operations in the <LOCATION> Bahamas </LOCATION>. The battle escalated today when <PERSON> Griffin </PERSON> increased his bid to $ 295 million, which values both Class A and Class B Resorts shares at about $ 46 each. Both contestants among <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s wealthiest men. <PERSON> Trump </PERSON> is listed by <ORGANIZATION> Forbes </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> magazine </ORGANIZATION> as worth at least $ 850 million, and personally claims $ 3 billion in wealth. Forbes lists <PERSON> Griffin </PERSON> as worth $ 300 million. For 23 years, <PERSON> Griffin </PERSON> served as host of the popular `` <PERSON> Merv </PERSON> <PERSON> Griffin </PERSON> Show,'' one of TV's longest-running series, winning 10 Emmy Awards in the process. In 1986, he sold privately-held <ORGANIZATION> Merv </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Griffin </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Enterprises </ORGANIZATION> _ producer of the `` <PERSON> Merv </PERSON> <PERSON> Griffin </PERSON> Show'' and two of his other successful creations, `` Wheel of Fortune'' and `` Jeopardy'' _ to <ORGANIZATION> Coca-Cola </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> for a reported $ 250 million. But he remains chairman of the company, and there is speculation he may take over as host of `` Wheel of Fortune'' when host <PERSON> Pat </PERSON> <PERSON> Sajak </PERSON> leaves to do his own show. Unlike many entertainers who squander their money through bad investments and mismanagement, the 63-year-old <PERSON> Griffin </PERSON> has earned a reputation in <LOCATION> Hollywood </LOCATION> as a shrewd businessman. He has parlayed his entertainment fortune into a business empire that includes radio stations, a major closed-circuit television operation widely used at racetracks, and extensive real estate holdings in <LOCATION> Beverly </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hills </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Northern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Griffin </PERSON>, whose hobbies are music, tennis and good food, lives stylishly, but not ostentatiously, in a 10,000-square-foot <LOCATION> Beverly </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hills </LOCATION> mansion near the homes of <ORGANIZATION> MCA </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>. Chairman <PERSON> Lew </PERSON> <PERSON> Wasserman </PERSON> and investor <PERSON> Marvin </PERSON> <PERSON> Davis </PERSON> By contrast, the 42-year-old <PERSON> Trump </PERSON>, who in a decade transformed himself from a local landlord into a national real estate mogul, has worked hard to make his name synonymous with ostentation. He routinely travels in one of his fleet of five helicopters. When <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Bricker </PERSON> was ousted as chief executive of Dallas-based <ORGANIZATION> Diamond </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Shamrock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> amid criticism over his imperial lifestyle, <PERSON> Trump </PERSON> purchased his luxurious <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> 727 private jet. His primary home is a $ 10 million triplex penthouse atop his glitzy Trump Tower in midtown <LOCATION> Manhattan </LOCATION>. For relaxation, he retreats to his 118-room mansion in <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Palm </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Beach </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Fla. </LOCATION>, or his 15-bedroom Georgian manor in <LOCATION> Greenwich </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Conn. </LOCATION> `` I ca n't afford for things not to be the best,'' <PERSON> Trump </PERSON> has said, contending the glamour attached to his name _ and the buildings that bear his name _ allows him to attract prices of $ 1,700 per square foot for some of his <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> condos. With a massive war chest to spend, <PERSON> Trump </PERSON> was attracted by the lure of profits in takeover speculation. In the past year, he bought stakes in <ORGANIZATION> Allegis </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Holiday </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Bally </ORGANIZATION> Mfg. <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, and raked in about $ 122 million in profits when he later sold the stock to the company or rival suitors. Earlier this year, <PERSON> Trump </PERSON> said he was considering buying up to 24.9 percent of entertainment conglomerate <ORGANIZATION> MCA </ORGANIZATION>, the parent of <ORGANIZATION> Universal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Studios </ORGANIZATION> which is frequently mentioned as a takeover target. But nothing has come of it. Likewise, nothing has come of his indications in January that he might buy up to 15 percent of <ORGANIZATION> Federated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stores </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> _ which later became the takeover target of <ORGANIZATION> Campeau </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp </ORGANIZATION>. But when <PERSON> Griffin </PERSON> decided to battle <PERSON> Trump </PERSON> for Resorts, the fight generally was expected to be short and victorious for <PERSON> Trump </PERSON>. <PERSON> Griffin </PERSON> is offering more money, but <PERSON> Trump </PERSON> holds 88 percent of Resorts' voting power through his ownership of nearly all of its Class B common stock, which carries 100 votes per share. <PERSON> Trump </PERSON> has insisted he will oppose <PERSON> Griffin </PERSON>'s proposal, and for that reason Resorts' board decided it was moot to pursue the issue with the entertainer. But <PERSON> Griffin </PERSON> has persisted. On Monday, he slapped <PERSON> Trump </PERSON> and Resorts' directors with a $ 500 million lawsuit, accusing them, among other things, of breach of fiduciary duty. That action came after <PERSON> Trump </PERSON> on Friday filed a $ 250 million suit against <PERSON> Griffin </PERSON> and his allies, claiming fraud, stock market manipulation and interference with <PERSON> Trump </PERSON>'s contractual arrangements with Resorts. Meanwhile, some holders of Resorts' 5.7 million Class A shares who had earlier indicated they would support <PERSON> Trump </PERSON>'s $ 22-per-share offer now are having second thoughts, their lawyers say.
