<HEAD>Supreme Court Bars States From Regulating Interstate Gas Company
Securities</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A unanimous <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> today ruled that states are barred from regulating the way interstate natural gas companies issue securities to finance their operations. The court, ruling in a dispute between the <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION> <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> and a Detroit-based pipeline, said the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Regulatory </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> has sole authority to regulate such financing. Justice <PERSON> Harry </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Blackmun </PERSON>, writing for the court, said the state authority sought by the <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION> agency is pre-empted by the federal Natural Gas Act of 1938. A federal appeals court previously had ruled against the <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION> authorities. <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION> law required pipeline companies to get advance approval from the state <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> before issuing securities. The law was passed to assure that the securities were being issued for a legal purpose _ one related to the more efficient delivery of natural gas. The regulatory law was challenged in 1984 by <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Natural </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Resources </ORGANIZATION>, which operates a pipeline system carrying natural gas to distribution customers in <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Indiana </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Kansas </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Missouri </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Tennessee </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Wisconsin </LOCATION>. According to court documents, the <ORGANIZATION> ANR </ORGANIZATION> has plans to issue $ 150 million in securities to help finance projects costing about $ 560 million. <PERSON> Blackmun </PERSON> said the 0 21.90 +.09 Mon.'s sales 20,000. Mon.'s open int 88,173.
