<SECOND>PM-Wall Street 11am,0361</SECOND>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Stocks turned mixed today, strengthened by higher bond prices and takeover-related buying, but restrained by investor reluctance to participate in a market still suffering post-crash uncertainty. The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials rose 1.16 points to 2,068.30 by 11 a.m. on Wall Street. Among broader market indicators, the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>'s composite index of all listed issues rose 0.10 to 151.57 The <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>'s market value index rose 0.20 to 298.38. Gaining issues barely outnumbered losers on the <ORGANIZATION> NYSE </ORGANIZATION>, with 613 up, 558 down and 527 unchanged. Volume totaled 45.5 million shares after 90 minutes. Rising prices in the bond market injected some optimism on Wall Street because they dampened anxiety over inflation and higher interest rates. Bonds were buoyed by lower oil prices and a government report that showed a surprising drop in factory orders for durable goods in February. Some stocks also were boosted by rumored and actual takeovers, reflecting a stunning increase in merger activity over the past several weeks. Nevertheless, stockbrokers said the relatively low volume of trading and the lack of any significant economic signals showed that many investors remain reluctant to re-enter the market in the aftermath of the October crash. `` People still are wounded,'' said <PERSON> Philip </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Puccio </PERSON>, manager of institutional trading at <ORGANIZATION> Dillon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Read </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> `` Those wounds have not scarred over yet. There's fear we could be looking at another downdraft.'' Among the most active issues, <ORGANIZATION> Lucky </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stores </ORGANIZATION> shot up 14 \ to 46 -LCB- after rival chain <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stores </ORGANIZATION> announced a $ 45-a-share tender offer for the company <ORGANIZATION> Kansas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> City </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Southern </ORGANIZATION>, target of a $ 60-a-share takeover attempt by a <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> investor group, advanced 2 ~ to 57 On Monday the Dow Jones industrials dropped 20.23 to 2,067.14. Losing issues outnumbered gainers by about 2-to-1 on the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, with 1,042 down, 502 up and 444 unchanged. <ORGANIZATION> Big </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> volume totaled 128.83 million shares against 245.75 million shares the previous session. It was the lowest level since a 111.58 million-share day Dec. 29.
