<HEAD>Robins To File Another Reorganization Plan</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RICHMOND, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> A.H. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Robins </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> says it will submit another amended reorganization plan as the result of a court hearing on the adequacy of the company's disclosure statement. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Merhige </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON> and <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Bankruptcy Judge <PERSON> Blackwell </PERSON> <PERSON> N. </PERSON> <PERSON> Shelley </PERSON> conducted the hearing Monday, listening to a series of objections to the disclosure statement. The document is the basis by which women with <ORGANIZATION> Dalkon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Shield </ORGANIZATION> injury claims and other creditors of <PERSON> Robins </PERSON> will decide how to vote on the company's reorganization plan. <PERSON> Robins </PERSON> spokesman <PERSON> Roscoe </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Puckett </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON> said Monday evening that as a result of the hearing, the company `` will submit a sixth amended and restated plan of reorganization incorporating certain changes,'' mostly in the wording of the statement. The new plan will be filed in bankruptcy court by March 28, he said. <PERSON> Merhige </PERSON> set an April 25 deadline for mailing the plan of reorganization to <ORGANIZATION> Dalkon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Shield </ORGANIZATION> claimants and the company's other creditors for a vote. The votes must be received by July 11 and a confirmation hearing will be July 18, <PERSON> Puckett </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Merhige </PERSON> also said he hoped to choose by April 11 the five trustees who will administer the nearly $ 2.5 billion compensation fund for <ORGANIZATION> Dalkon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Shield </ORGANIZATION> victims. The <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>, in a related action Monday, let stand a ruling against a $ 15 million emergency fund to help women who became infertile from using the intrauterine device, which <PERSON> Robins </PERSON> sold in the early 1970s. The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> also refused to review a ruling that placed on hold several lawsuits against the insurer of the IUD. <PERSON> Robins </PERSON> has been in Chapter 11 bankruptcy proceedings since August 1985. The Richmond-based maker of pharmaceuticals sought court protection from creditors as lawsuits mounted against the birth control device. <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> McDowell </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> Manchester </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.H. </LOCATION>, attorney for 35 users of the IUD, told <PERSON> Merhige </PERSON> and <PERSON> Shelley </PERSON> the disclosure statement should not go out because it appeared to give a discharge from liability to not only <ORGANIZATION> Robins </ORGANIZATION> but to its insurer, corporate directors and members of the <PERSON> Robins </PERSON>' family. Attorneys for <PERSON> Robins </PERSON> and the <ORGANIZATION> Aetna </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Casualty </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <ORGANIZATION> Surety </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> that insured the <ORGANIZATION> Dalkon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Shield </ORGANIZATION> said claimants voting to ratify the reorganization plan are not prevented from subsequently going to court. <PERSON> McDowell </PERSON>'s objection was overruled. An attorney for the <ORGANIZATION> Internal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Revenue </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> challenged an arrangement for <PERSON> Robins </PERSON> to repay the federal tax agency's priority claim over a six-year period. `` We're being asked to make a $ 62 million unsecured loan at prime interest,'' said <PERSON> Stuart </PERSON> <PERSON> Gibson </PERSON>, an <ORGANIZATION> IRS </ORGANIZATION> tax lawyer. <PERSON> Merhige </PERSON>, however, overruled the objection. `` It's your own fault,'' the judge told <PERSON> Gibson </PERSON>. `` I asked you to settle it ... and you could n't do it.'' In <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> upheld the 4th <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION>' decision to reject the $ 15 million emergency fund, which <PERSON> Merhige </PERSON> had approved as a means of helping women still of child-bearing age to regain fertility through special surgery. The emergency fund was challenged by <PERSON> Robins </PERSON>' stockholders as giving preferential treatment to a select group of claims while the final reorganization was pending. The high court's decision not to review the stay of lawsuits against <ORGANIZATION> Aetna </ORGANIZATION> upheld <PERSON> Merhige </PERSON> and the 4th Circuit. The appeals court said the suits brought by women in <LOCATION> Kansas </LOCATION> and <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hampshire </ORGANIZATION> inevitably would pull in <PERSON> Robins </PERSON> and thus would detract from the ongoing bankruptcy proceedings.
