<HEAD>Ford Will Export Continentals, Sables to South Korea</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> said it will begin exporting its <ORGANIZATION> Lincoln </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Continental </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Mercury </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sable </ORGANIZATION> cars this spring to <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION>, where they will sell for about three times their <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> prices. <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> dropped a ban on car imports last year, but tariffs, taxes and fees remain in place. <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> said Monday that the Continentals and <PERSON> Sables </PERSON> will sell in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> for about $ 42,000 and $ 75,000, respectively. In the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Sables </LOCATION> sell for about $ 14,000 to $ 16,000 while Continentals fetch between $ 25,000 and $ 30,000 per car. <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motors </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> also has begun a small-scale program to ship luxury cars to <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION> said its Buicks and Cadillacs also will sell for about three times their <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> prices.
