<HEAD>Grain, Soybean Futures Open Mostly Lower</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Grain and soybean futures prices opened mostly lower today on the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION>. Analysts said soybean futures were pressured by accelerated overnight selling by farmers, while corn prices were hit by news that <LOCATION> Vermont </LOCATION> Sen. <PERSON> Patrick </PERSON> <PERSON> Leahy </PERSON> is moving ahead with legislation that would ultimately put more corn on the market. Wheat futures were higher, after a decline on Monday. At the opening, wheat was -RCB- cent lower to \ cent higher, with the contract for delivery in March at $ 2.96 -LCB- a bushel; corn was 1 cent to 1 -RCB- cents lower, with March at $ 2.00 -LCB- a bushel; oats were -LCB- cent lower to 1 cent higher, with March at $ 1.91 -LCB- a bushel; and soybeans were -LCB- cent to 1 \ cents lower, with March at $ 6.29 a bushel Livestock and meat futures were mostly higher at the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>. Live cattle were unchanged to .20 cent higher, with April at 73.65 cents a pound; feeder cattle were unchanged to .15 cent higher, with March at 82.20 cents a pound; live hogs were .15 cent lower to .30 cent higher, with April at 45.40 cents a pound; and frozzen pork bellies were .05 cent to .28 cent higher, with May at 55.15 cents a pound.
