<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Stocks turned mixed today, strengthened by higher bond prices and takeover-related buying, but restrained by investor reluctance to participate in a market still suffering post-crash uncertainty. The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials was down 1.49 points to 2,065.65 by noon on Wall Street. Among broader market indicators, the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>'s composite index of all listed issues was unchanged at 151.47 The <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>'s market value index rose 0.16 to 298.34. Gaining and losing issues were about even on the <ORGANIZATION> NYSE </ORGANIZATION>, with 636 up, 645 down and 520 unchanged. Volume totaled 65.3 million shares in the morning session, compared with 65.76 million Monday morning. Rising prices in the bond market provided some optimism to Wall Street because they dampened anxiety over inflation and higher interest rates. Bonds were buoyed by lower oil prices and a government report that showed a surprising drop in factory orders for durable goods in February. Some stocks also were boosted by rumored and actual takeovers, reflecting a stunning increase in merger activity over the past several weeks. Nevertheless, stockbrokers said the relatively low volume of trading and the lack of any significant economic signals showed that many investors remain reluctant to re-enter the market in the aftermath of the October crash. `` People still are wounded,'' said <PERSON> Philip </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Puccio </PERSON>, manager of institutional trading at <ORGANIZATION> Dillon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Read </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> `` Those wounds have not scarred over yet. There's fear we could be looking at another downdraft.'' Lucky Stores was the most active issue, jumping 14 -RRB- to 46 | in heavy trading after rival chain <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stores </ORGANIZATION> announced a $ 45-a-share tender offer for the company <ORGANIZATION> Kansas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> City </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Southern </ORGANIZATION>, target of a $ 60-a-share takeover attempt by a <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> investor group, advanced 2 \ to 57 On the Amex, Resorts International Class A shares rose 3 to 31 | after entertainer <PERSON> Merv </PERSON> <PERSON> Griffin </PERSON> boosted his offer for the company in a takeover battle with developer <PERSON> Donald </PERSON> <PERSON> Trump </PERSON>
