<SECOND>PM-Scotus-Taxes,0343</SECOND>
<HEAD>High Court Rejects IRS Attempt to Impose Stiffer Taxes</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> today rejected the <ORGANIZATION> Internal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Revenue </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>'s attempt to impose stiffer taxes when individuals or business partnerships form corporations to obtain financing. By an 8-0 vote, the court said real estate developers in <LOCATION> Kentucky </LOCATION> should not be subjected to a heavier tax burden because they formed corporations for the sole purpose of borrowing money. <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Bollinger </PERSON>, either individually or in partnership with others, developed eight apartment complexes in the <LOCATION> Lexington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ky. </LOCATION>, area beginning in 1968. To obtain construction-financing loans, <PERSON> Bollinger </PERSON> formed corporations to borrow the money at 8 percent interest. <LOCATION> Kentucky </LOCATION>'s usury law at the time limited the interest non-corporate borrowers could be charged to 7 percent, and lenders were not willing to finance <PERSON> Bollinger </PERSON>'s projects at that rate When <PERSON> Bollinger </PERSON> and his partners sought to claim business losses connected with the apartment projects on their individual federal income taxes, the <ORGANIZATION> IRS </ORGANIZATION> disallowed it. The tax agency said the losses must be attributed to the corporations, deemed to be the true owners of the apartment complexes. That designation worked to the tax disadvantage of <PERSON> Bollinger </PERSON> and his partners. A federal appeals court ruled against the <ORGANIZATION> IRS </ORGANIZATION>, and today's decision upheld that ruling Writing for the court, Justice <PERSON> Antonin </PERSON> <PERSON> Scalia </PERSON> said the corporations had been formed for a legitimate, non-manipulative purpose. `` It seems to us that ... tax-avoiding manipulation -LRB- is -RRB- adequately avoided when ... the corporation is acting as agent for its shareholders with respect to a particular asset -LRB- the apartment complexes -RRB- is set forth in a written agreement at the time the asset is acquired,'' <PERSON> Scalia </PERSON> said. He also noted that the corporations at issue in this case functioned `` as agent and not principal with respect to the asset for all purposes, and the corporation is held out as the agent and not principal in all dealings with third parties relating to the asset.'' The case is Commissioner, <ORGANIZATION> IRS </ORGANIZATION> vs. <PERSON> Bollinger </PERSON>, 86-1672.
