<HEAD>De Benedetti Wins 3.53 Percent More of Societe Generale in Public
Offer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Italian investor <PERSON> Carlo </PERSON> <PERSON> De </PERSON> <PERSON> Benedetti </PERSON> has increased his holdings in <ORGANIZATION> Societe </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Generale </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> de </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Belgique </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> SA </ORGANIZATION> by 3.53 percent, but it was not known if his alliance held a majority stake in <LOCATION> Belgium </LOCATION>'s largest holding company, officials said Tuesday. An official at <ORGANIZATION> De </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Benedetti </ORGANIZATION>'s French investment company <ORGANIZATION> Cerus </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> SA </ORGANIZATION>, who asked not to be named, did not know whether the public offer gave <PERSON> De </PERSON> <PERSON> Benedetti </PERSON> and his allies control of the company. This alliance claimed to control 47.01 percent of <ORGANIZATION> Societe </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Generale </ORGANIZATION>'s shares before Tuesday. The newly purchased shares would apparently raise this to 50.54 percent. But the <ORGANIZATION> Cerus </ORGANIZATION> official said the 47.01 percent might have included some shares from the public offer. On March 10, a Franco-Belgian alliance opposing <PERSON> De </PERSON> <PERSON> Benedetti </PERSON> claimed to control 50.7 percent of <ORGANIZATION> Societe </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Generale </ORGANIZATION>. Tuesday's announcement was the latest twist in one of <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>'s biggest and most complex takeover battles It failed to provide definite clues about the outcome, more than two months after <PERSON> De </PERSON> <PERSON> Benedetti </PERSON> first announced his bid for 166-year-old <ORGANIZATION> Societe </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Generale </ORGANIZATION>. On March 10, <PERSON> De </PERSON> <PERSON> Benedetti </PERSON> called for shareholders meeting, which should make it clear which side has a majority. The meeting is set for April 14. Meanwhile, a court case was still pending on a <ORGANIZATION> Societe </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Generale </ORGANIZATION> capital increase to fend off <PERSON> De </PERSON> <PERSON> Benedetti </PERSON>. The ruling in that case might still dramatically change the stakes each side claims to hold. <ORGANIZATION> Cerus </ORGANIZATION>, the investment firm through which <PERSON> De </PERSON> <PERSON> Benedetti </PERSON> was vying for control of <ORGANIZATION> Societe </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Generale </ORGANIZATION>, said Tuesday it had obtained 1.087 million additional shares, or 3.53 percent of the company's total share capital, including warrants. <ORGANIZATION> Cerus </ORGANIZATION> launched a public offer for the extra shares on Feb. 15. The bid was to have expired March 4 but has since been extended. The offer was designed to acquire 2.1 million shares, or about 7 percent of the share capital of <ORGANIZATION> Societe </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Generale </ORGANIZATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Cerus </ORGANIZATION> offered 8,000 francs, or $ 228, for ordinary shares in the last stage of its public offer. Reacting to Tuesday's announcement, the management of <ORGANIZATION> Societe </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Generale </ORGANIZATION>, which opposes <PERSON> De </PERSON> <PERSON> Benedetti </PERSON>, said there were no defections from the Franco-Belgian alliance to <ORGANIZATION> Cerus </ORGANIZATION>' camp. <PERSON> De </PERSON> <PERSON> Benedetti </PERSON> wants to turn <ORGANIZATION> Societe </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Generale </ORGANIZATION> into the platform of a pan-European holding company while the Franco-Belgian group wants to keep the company firmly entrenched in the Belgian economic fabric. On Tuesday, <ORGANIZATION> Societe </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Generale </ORGANIZATION> announced its net profit in 1987 fell 22.1 percent to stand at 4.138 billion francs. <ORGANIZATION> Societe </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Generale </ORGANIZATION> has a stake in over 1,200 companies world-wide and the government has stressed the company is vital for its investment strategy, technological development and its relations with its former colony <LOCATION> Zaire </LOCATION>. The <ORGANIZATION> De </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Benedetti </ORGANIZATION> group consists of <ORGANIZATION> Cerus </ORGANIZATION>, the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> investment bank <ORGANIZATION> Shearson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lehman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hutton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, the Swiss bank <ORGANIZATION> Companie </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> de </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Banque </ORGANIZATION> et d'Investissements and the food giant <ORGANIZATION> Nestle </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> SA </ORGANIZATION>, two Belgian partners and several smaller allies. The Franco-Belgian alliance is anchored around the French investment firm <ORGANIZATION> Companie </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Financiere </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> de </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Suez </ORGANIZATION> and <LOCATION> Belgium </LOCATION>'s biggest insurer, <ORGANIZATION> Groupe </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> AG </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> SA </ORGANIZATION> and includes several other partners.
