<HEAD>Precede WEST PALM BEACH</HEAD>
<HEAD>Jurors Award $7.95 Million in Delta Crash Suit</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A federal jury has awarded a record $ 7.95 million to the estate of an <ORGANIZATION> IBM </ORGANIZATION> executive and his wife killed in a <ORGANIZATION> Delta </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lines </ORGANIZATION> crash outside <LOCATION> Dallas </LOCATION>, including more than $ 6 million for his lost potential earnings at the computer company. The jury at <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Manhattan </LOCATION> deliberated just five hours before returning its verdict at 8:30 p.m. Monday in the suit by the estate of <PERSON> Philip </PERSON> <PERSON> D. </PERSON> <PERSON> Estridge </PERSON>, 47, of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Canaan </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Conn. </LOCATION>, and his wife <PERSON> Mary </PERSON> <PERSON> Ann </PERSON>. <PERSON> Estridge </PERSON>, who received much of the credit for moving <ORGANIZATION> IBM </ORGANIZATION> into the personal computer market, and his wife were among 137 people killed when the <ORGANIZATION> Lockheed </ORGANIZATION> L-1011 crashed on approach at <LOCATION> Dallas-Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Worth </LOCATION> <LOCATION> International </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Airport </LOCATION> on Aug. 2, 1985. `` I thought it would have been more, and it should have been more,'' said attorney <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> <PERSON> Kreindler </PERSON>, who had asked for $ 25 million for <ORGANIZATION> Estridge </ORGANIZATION> and $ 5 million for his wife. `` I was a little disappointed with the numbers.'' But <PERSON> Evelyn </PERSON> <PERSON> Eubanks </PERSON>, one of three daughters who filed the suit, said they were happy with the judgment and the end of the case. `` We do n't think anything could have happened any better and we're definitely relieved it's over,'' she said. `` It does n't make it better, but it helps us to live with it.'' <PERSON> Kreindler </PERSON> said the sum awarded Monday was a record for compensatory damages in a wrongful-death suit. The breakdown was $ 6.25 million for <PERSON> Estridge </PERSON>'s loss of earnings, $ 750,000 for loss of enjoyment of life and $ 100,000 for mental anguish. For Mrs. <PERSON> Estridge </PERSON>, the jury awarded $ 750,000 for loss of enjoyment of life and $ 100,000 for mental anguish. Shortly before <PERSON> Estridge </PERSON> died, the <LOCATION> Jacksonville </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Fla. </LOCATION>, native was named overseer of <ORGANIZATION> IBM </ORGANIZATION>'s worldwide manufacturing operations, based in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, at a salary of $ 240,000 yearly. Although the trial was held in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, the award was reached under the law of <PERSON> Estridge </PERSON>'s new home state of <LOCATION> Connecticut </LOCATION> to allow for the salary projection figures, <PERSON> Kreindler </PERSON> said. <ORGANIZATION> Delta </ORGANIZATION> lawyer <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Sabetta </PERSON> declined to comment on the award, but told Judge <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Sprizzo </PERSON> he would appeal. <ORGANIZATION> Delta </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Berry </PERSON> referred all calls to the company's insurance carrier, <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aviation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Underwriters </ORGANIZATION>, and had no comment. The Estridge verdict came on the same day of opening arguments in another suit stemming from the fatal crash. A wrongful-death suit on behalf of <PERSON> Julie </PERSON> <PERSON> Ann </PERSON> <PERSON> Zarnt </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Boca </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Raton </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Fla. </LOCATION>, opened Monday with a 12-minute videotape highlighting her 15 years of life. The first half of the tape was made from silent home movies. It showed her as a newborn first coming home and as a toddler celebrating birthdays and Christmas.
