<HEAD>Searle Didn't Withhold Information on Copper-7, FDA Finds</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 There is no evidence <PERSON> G.D. </PERSON> <PERSON> Searle </PERSON> and <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> withheld information from the <ORGANIZATION> Food </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Drug </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> in winning approval for its Copper-7 intrauterine contraceptive device, an <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION> spokeswoman said Tuesday. <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION> officials met with <PERSON> Searle </PERSON> representatives last week to discuss whether company documents recently unsealed in a <LOCATION> Minnesota </LOCATION> court case challenging the IUD were available to the government agency before it approved the device in 1974. `` The gist of our initial review is that we've had that information all along, and that we got it when we initially began reviewing'' <PERSON> Searle </PERSON>'s application for approval of the IUD, said spokewoman <PERSON> Susan </PERSON> <PERSON> Cruzan </PERSON>. `` There's no evidence they did n't give us all the necessary inforatmion when we began our review,'' she said. The Searle IUD remains on the government approved list, but the company stopped selling it in 1986, citing growing costs from court suits. The company faces about 500 suits by women who claim that the Copper-7 caused them to develop pelvic infections. The company has won 14 of the 17 suits that have gone to trial and maintains that the device was, and is, safe.
