<HEAD>Loss of $15.2 Million For Fourth Quarter Of '87</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MILWAUKEE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Allis-Chalmers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, a once-mighty industrial giant that filed for bankruptcy reorganization last June, Tuesday reported a net loss of $ 15.2 million, or $ 1.17 per share, for the fourth quarter of 1987. The loss, on sales of $ 109.3 million, compared with a loss of $ 5.8 million, or 52 cents per share, for the same period of 1986 when sales totaled $ 116.8 million. For the year, <ORGANIZATION> Allis-Chalmers </ORGANIZATION> reported a total loss of $ 29.3 million compared with a loss of $ 8.6 million in 1986. Sales in 1987 declined to $ 410 million from $ 510.3 million in 1986. <PERSON> Wendell </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Bueche </PERSON>, chairman and chief executive officer, said the results reflected obligations from years before the company scaled down by selling off many of its businesses. Once a major producer of farm machinery, the company later diversified into production of a wide range of other equipment. <PERSON> Bueche </PERSON> said the cost of health care benefits for retired employees was disproportionate to the company's size, althoughthe company has implemented a strategy aimed at reducing that expense.
