<HEAD>Fortune 44 Dropping Fortune Cookies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOULDER, Colo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Fortune 44 Co. of <LOCATION> Boulder </LOCATION> is getting out of the fortune cookie business, saying the slow market for the cookies could spell problems for the company's future. Company officials announced the decision on Monday, citing continuing losses and sales which have not met expectations. Fortune 44 believes the lack of sales are due to the limited market, the infrequent purchase cycle and intense competition in the low-price end of the fortune cookie market, officials said in a written statement. `` When's the last time you bought fortune cookies?'' said the company's controller, <PERSON> Mary </PERSON> <PERSON> Lou </PERSON> <PERSON> Schwab </PERSON>. `` We're in the grocery store business where things have to turn. People buy fortune cookies but mostly for a special occasion.'' The company will service existing customers through May, she said. Started in 1983, Fortune 44 employs eight people and offers 20 different varieties of the cookies, including its Wish Biscuits and Lucky Chan lines. Company officials said they have received inquiries from competitors interested in acquiring its lines and said Fortune 44 is pursuing those inquiries. Management also is seeking an acquisition or merger candidate and is having ongoing discussions with two companies, the statement said. The company is optimistic it can find a merger or acquisition that can benefit shareholders, officials said. Fortune 44 reported assets totaling nearly $ 1.2 million last September; it has 110 shareholders.
