<HEAD>High Court Questions Catalog Tax Practices</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD CARELLI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A department store chain's attempt to avoid paying taxes for merchandise catalogs received by its <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION> customers sparked skeptical questioning Tuesday in the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Andrew </PERSON> <PERSON> Rinker </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, representing New Orleans-based <ORGANIZATION> D.H. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Holmes </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, seemed to be having little success in arguing that his client should not have to pay a <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION> `` use tax'' on the catalogs' value <PERSON> Rinker </PERSON> spent nearly 30 minutes responding to the justices' questions By contrast, <LOCATION> Shreveport </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> La. </LOCATION>, lawyer <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> G. </PERSON> <PERSON> Pugh </PERSON> concluded his presentation for state tax officials in less than 10 minutes because he was asked so few questions. The court's decision is expected by July. <PERSON> Rinker </PERSON>, from <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Orleans </LOCATION>, contended that no tax should be assessed because the catalogs are published in other states and mailed directly to <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION> residents. The state imposes a tax on all tangible personal property bought or used within <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION>. When <PERSON> Rinker </PERSON> argued that the department store chain actually had paid for a service _ delivery of the catalogs _ and not for goods, several justices seemed to disagree. `` <PERSON> Holmes </PERSON> put this whole operation into creation,'' said Chief Justice <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Rehnquist </PERSON>. Justice <PERSON> Sandra </PERSON> <PERSON> Day </PERSON> <PERSON> O'Connor </PERSON> questioned whether delivery of the catalogs, even through the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> mail, is `` an activity that can be taxed.'' She later seemed to answer her own question in the affirmative: `` <PERSON> Holmes </PERSON> caused the distribution in <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION>. It ordered it. It paid for it.'' When <PERSON> Rinker </PERSON> contended that it is <PERSON> Holmes </PERSON>' customers, not <PERSON> Holmes </PERSON>, who use the catalogs, Justice <PERSON> Byron </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> White </PERSON> responded, `` <PERSON> Holmes </PERSON> is having that use provided.'' When Justice <PERSON> Thurgood </PERSON> <PERSON> Marshall </PERSON> asked, `` Could <PERSON> Holmes </PERSON> have made a dollar in the state of <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION> without the catalogs?'' <PERSON> Rinker </PERSON> said many of the customers who frequent <PERSON> Holmes </PERSON>' 13 stores in <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION> did so long before catalogs were mailed out. `` Those are pretty old people,'' <PERSON> White </PERSON> quipped. <PERSON> Rinker </PERSON> acknowledged that the department store chain could be subjected to the <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION> tax if the catalogs are delivered to the state and distributed from there. But he said the current set-up precludes state tax liability. <PERSON> Pugh </PERSON> argued that the real taxable activity undertaken by <PERSON> Holmes </PERSON> is `` maintaing a market in <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION> for their sales.'' <ORGANIZATION> D.H. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Holmes </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> also operates stores in <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Alabama </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> but 82 percent of its catalogs are mailed to <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION> residents. The state tax imposed on <PERSON> Holmes </PERSON> is based on 82 percent of the catalogs' value, and the validity of applying the tax to the catalogs was upheld by state courts. The case is <ORGANIZATION> D.H. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Holmes </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> vs. <PERSON> McNamara </PERSON>, 87-267.
