<SECOND>AM-Liability Crisis, 2nd Ld-Writethru, f0268,0987</SECOND>
<HEAD>Precede AUSTIN, Texas</HEAD>
<HEAD>States Accuse Companies of Restricting Coverage</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New throughout to UPDATE with attorney general's comments in
California, where most suits filed, other details, reax, moving
list of plaintiffs lower. Changes byline; Also moved on general
newswires</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BOB EGELKO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Eight states on Tuesday filed suit accusing dozens of insurance companies of conspiring to create the liability insurance crisis, making coverage unavailable or too costly for many governments and businesses. The companies' actions were `` a major contributor to the insurance crisis that forced so many cities and businesses up against the wall,'' <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> Attorney General <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Van </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Kamp </PERSON> said at a news conference. `` It was the public and the consumer who paid the price for this collusive exercise in corporate greed,'' he said. <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Ostwald </PERSON>, a vice president of the <ORGANIZATION> Insurance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION>, a 1,400-member rate and policy advisory organization named in the lawsuits, called the claims unfounded and denied the existence of a conspiracy. The lawsuits filed in <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> here by seven states accuses major <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> and British insurance firms, reinsurers and <PERSON> Ostwald </PERSON>'s trade group of using secret agreements and internal pressure several years ago in an effort to eliminate the most common type of general liability policy, that covering any damage that occurs during the policy term regardless of when the damage is discovered. Reinsurers provide vital backup coverage for other insurers, <PERSON> Van </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Kamp </PERSON> said. The attorneys general of <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Wisconsin </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Minnesota </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Alabama </LOCATION> filed similar suits in <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION>, naming 32 insurance companies, underwriters and associations. <PERSON> Van </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Kamp </PERSON> said <LOCATION> Arizona </LOCATION> would sue in the same court Wednesday. A separate lawsuit was filed in state court in <LOCATION> Austin </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>. `` These defendants have sucked the blood of our nation's economic well-being,'' <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> Attorney General <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Mattox </PERSON> said at a news conference <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> filed suit in state court because the state `` has one of the toughest, best antitrust laws in the nation,'' he said. As a result of the conspiracy, <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>'s suit said, property damage insurance for local governments, non-profit agencies such as child care centers, and various businesses suddenly became unavailable or prohibitively expensive. In <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> and elsewhere, local governments cut back or eliminated services, such as parks and police, because of insurance expenses, <PERSON> Van </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Kamp </PERSON> said. Many local government officials blamed rising damage awards in injury suits and joined the insurance industry in efforts to restrict the right to sue. The lawsuits claim the companies targeted for elimination coverage for spills and other types of pollution incidents and general liability for damage discovered after the life of a policy, known as `` occurrence'' coverage. The companies instead favored more limited policies, covering only losses that were suffered and claimed within the policy term, excluding damage that was discovered later, the suits said. The lawsuits said four major insurance companies _ <LOCATION> Hartford </LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Allstate </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Cigna </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Aetna </ORGANIZATION> _ started a campaign in 1984 to curtail coverage that was generally available in the industry. According to the suits, the companies got major <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> and British reinsurers, including underwriters at <ORGANIZATION> Lloyd </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> London </ORGANIZATION>, to threaten a boycott of any <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> insurance company that provided the broader coverage. Among other things, the plaintiffs seek to restructure the <ORGANIZATION> Insurance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> by giving non-insurers a majority on its board and making public its data on insurance coverage losses. <PERSON> Ostwald </PERSON> said from his office in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> that pollution insurance and `` occurrence'' coverage remained available, with some restrictions. Pollution coverage was changed in response to expansive court decisions, he said. `` It's simply incorrect to assert that an attempt was made to impose this policy on the marketplace,'' he said, referring to the alleged effort to scrap `` occurrence'' coverage. Insurance rates increased mainly because of `` a demonstrable increase in claims losses and a drop in interest rates, slowing down -LRB- insurers' -RRB- investment income,'' he said. <PERSON> Steven </PERSON> <PERSON> Perelman </PERSON>, a spokesman for <ORGANIZATION> Aetna </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Casualty </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Surety </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, a defendant in <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>, termed the action `` another political move by political officeholders who have consistently opposed any and all efforts to address the real problems of the nation's liability system.'' <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Willis </PERSON>, spokesman for the <ORGANIZATION> Cigna </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Property </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Casualty </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION>, also named in both lawsuits, said, `` It's really an ingrained condition of how we operate in all our jurisdictions that we conform to whatever antitrust regulations exist. We do not violate laws.'' In addtion to <ORGANIZATION> ISO </ORGANIZATION>, the suit in <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> named eight companies that served on the <ORGANIZATION> ISO </ORGANIZATION> executive committee: <ORGANIZATION> Aetna </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Cigna </ORGANIZATION>, Fireman's <ORGANIZATION> Fund </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Insurance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Hartford </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fire </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Insurance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Liberty </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mutual </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Insurance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> St. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Paul </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fire </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Marine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Insurance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Travelers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Insurance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> USF </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> G </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>. Also named in <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> were the <ORGANIZATION> Reinsurance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION